<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia     09-12 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopia Celebrates 14th Anniversary of Marxist Revolutiuon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam
marked the 14th anniversary of Ethiopia's Marxist revolution Monday
with a brief address devoted to the nation's longstanding civil war
in the north.
   Government troops and civilians mobilized since the conflict
intensified in March are ``presently engaged in a bitter fight,''
Mengistu told the thousands of people packed into the capital's
downtown Revolution Square.
   His forces claim to have repulsed insurgencies in its
northernmost province, Eritrea, and Eritrea's southern neighbor,
Tigray, where Ethiopia says it has retaken all major cities and
towns since the rebels overran the region in April and May.
   No major engagements have been reported with the separatist
Eritrean People's Liberation Front since the government in May said
its forces had foiled rebel attempts to take the strategic city of
Keren, 56 miles northwest of the provincial capital of Asmara.
   However, Mengistu said the rebels were sabotaging and
endangering the lives of all citizens and hampering the development
of public and private institutiones.
   The task ahead ``is clearly an arduous one,'' he said in his
20-minute address.
   The Eritrean guerrillas have been fighting a separatist battle
for 27 years in Africa's longest civil war. In Tigray, the Tigray
People's Liberation Front took up arms 14 years ago demanding
greater autohomy for their region.
   Mengistu inherited the insurgencies when he and a clique of
military men dethroned Emperor Haile Selassie in 1974 and replaced
the emperor's 44-year feudal reign with a Marxist government.
   One day before last year's anniversary of the revolution, the
provisional military government which had ruled since the
revolution was replaced by a People's Democratic Republic which has
a popularly elected legislature. However, power still sits with
Mengistu who has ruled Ethiopia since Feb. 12, 1977.
   In his speech, Mengistu also referred to Ethiopia's unusually
good rains this year and expressed confidence that if the wet
weather continues, the nation ``will, in a short time, be free of
food shortages which have made us the butt of an unhealthy
comment.''
   The Horn of Africa nation suffers chronic droughts which in
1984-85 led to a famine that killed an estimated 1 million people
and sparked the largest international relief effort in history.
   Rains failed again in 1987 causing widespread crop failures that
threatened an estimated 3.2 million people with starvation in
Eritrea and Tigray.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
