<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FrogLegs     09-12 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Frog Legs,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pascagoula Businessman Gears Up For Frog Leg Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman is leaping to fill the gap
created by dropping supplies of bullfrogs, whose legs are consumed
as a cripsy delicacy in the South.
   Bruce Maghan was almost hopping in anticipation Monday of an
experimental program to raise the big, hopping amphibians.
   ``It's not really even off the ground yet. But we're pretty
excited,'' the owner of Stillashak Institutional Sea Products said
in a telephone interview from Pascagoula on the Gulf Coast.
   ``If you look what has been done in this state for the shrimp,
oyster, striped bass and redfish industies, there's no reason it
can't be done for frog legs,'' Maghan said.
   Maghan said that three years ago he was paying $2.15 to $2.20 a
pound for frog legs. The price is now about $4.06 per pound.
   ``I have been quoted as much as $5 to $5.10. That goes to show
you that the market is way up. Three years ago, I was getting about
six to eight pair of legs to the pound. Now, its about four to six
pairs per pound.
   ``But we are also looking at the remnants of supplies, and those
are depleting fast,'' he said.
   Maghan said in 1986-87, more than 8.6 million pounds of frog
legs came into the United States from India and Bangladesh. He said
the market could be as much as 10 million pounds.
   But India and Bangladesh have put a five-year moratorium on such
exports, he said.
   ``They (the bullfrogs) are wild over there and they have taken
so many of them that the insect problem has increased, so they
aren't shipping any more.
   ``But I believe there is no reason why Florida, Georgia,
Alabama, Louisiana and Mississippi can't raise all the frogs we
need,'' he said.
   Maghan said the adult frogs eat insects, but he's trying to come
up with a feed that will increase their size and growth.
   He plans to start with tadpoles and raise them all the way to
adults.
   ``It is a long process,'' Maghan said. ``It is not something we
expect to do overnight. We expect to raise the critters in a pond,
but everything else is still up in the air.''
</TEXT>
