<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VermontPrimary     09-12 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Primary,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont's Lone Congressman Seeking Open U.S. Senate Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, Republican James Jeffords,
Vermont's lone member of the U.S. House, has enjoyed the backing of
many state Democrats. Two years ago, he even won re-election with
both the GOP and Democratic nominations.
   This year, though, as Jeffords seeks the seat of retiring U.S.
Sen. Robert Stafford, R-Vt., his popularity among Democrats is
being used against him by GOP challenger Michael Griffes, who calls
himself the real Republican in the race.
   Griffes and Jeffords will face off next Tuesday in Vermont's
Republican primary. The winner will face Democrat William Gray, a
former U.S. attorney, in the November election. Gray is unopposed
in Tuesday's Democratic primary.
   Jeffords is the clear favorite in the primary, but his support
of Democratic initiatives over the years has angered many of the
GOP faithful, including former four-term Gov. Richard Snelling, who
donated $1,000 to the Griffes campaign.
   ``Jim Jeffords, while he clearly has provided a long service to
Vermont, has not, in my opinion, been very often mindful of the
fact that he gets his nominations from the Republican Party,'' said
Snelling, himself considered a moderate to liberal.
   While Snelling was willing to give money to Griffes, he withheld
his formal endorsement, saying the 35-year-old political newcomer
had not ``sufficiently established his credentials.''
   And that is clearly Griffes' weak point. While Jeffords, 54, has
lived his life in Vermont and served as a state senator, attorney
general and member of the U.S. House, Griffes had lived in the
state only a year or so in the 1970s before returning here this
spring to challenge Jeffords.
   He served in the Navy and then worked for Grumman Corp., a major
defense contractor, in Washington. He said he decided to move back
to Vermont to challenge Jeffords when the congressman was the only
Republican in the House last fall to vote for a $12 billion
deficit-reduction measure backed by the Democratic leadership on a
crucial 206-205 vote.
   That vote was only one of the many times Jeffords has broken
party ranks. In 1981, he was the sole House Republican to vote
against President Reagan's tax-cut package. In 1987, Jeffords had
the second-highest anti-Reagan voting record among Republicans in
the House, as analyzed by Congressional Quarterly magazine. He
opposed the president on 71 percent of the key votes.
   ``When you get to the point where you start making decisions or
doing things based upon political expedience, you've worn out your
usefulness as someone who can really help,'' said Jeffords, who
says he makes his decisions on what's best for Vermonters, not on
what's best for the Republicans.
   Griffes campaigns by saying that Jeffords should be honest and
seek the Democratic nomination. ``My record will be more like Bob
Stafford's and not like House Speaker Jim Wright's,'' says Griffes,
a reference to Vermont's retiring Republican senator and the
Democratic speaker of the House.
   Jeffords is considered the strong favorite in the November
election, should he win the primary, because of his strong
Democratic support.
   The Republican primary for the U.S. Senate is one of three
statewide contests that will be decided Tuesday.
   With Jeffords giving up his House seat, four Democrats and two
Republicans are seeking their respective party nominations. The two
winners will be joined on the November ballot by Burlington Mayor
Bernard Sanders, a socialist who is running a strong independent
campaign for the House seat, and candidates representing the
Liberty Union, the Libertarian Party and the Small Is Beautiful
Party.
   Former Lt. Gov. Peter Smith is favored to win the Republican
congressional race, while the Democratic race, featuring former
Secretary of State James Guest, House Majority Leader Paul Poirier,
Senate President Pro Tem Peter Welch and University of Vermont
professor Dolores Sandoval, is considered wide open.
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin, seeking her third term, is unopposed in
Tuesday's primary, as is her Republican challenger, state Rep.
Michael Bernhardt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
