<DOCNO> AP880912-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WisconsinPrimary     09-12 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wisconsin Primary,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Bucks Spent For Proxmire's Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR L. SRB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big spending has become a big issue in
Tuesday's heated Democratic primary battle for the seat held for 31
years by retiring Sen. William Proxmire, whose last re-election
campaign cost him $145.10.
   Milwaukee millionaire Herbert Kohl, running in his first
election, stands accused of trying to buy the nomination by
spending more than $2 million, much of it on TV advertising and
much of it his own money.
   ``Politics should be people, ideas and leadership, not
multimillion-dollar TV hype,'' said Secretary of State Douglas La
Follette, one of Kohl's Democratic foes.
   Wisconsin is one of six states holding primary elections Tuesday.
   Kohl, 53, owner of the Milwaukee Bucks of the National
Basketball Association, said he had to buy the ads to win the name
recognition enjoyed by La Follette, former Gov. Anthony Earl and
Edward Garvey, who was the Democratic Senate nominee two years ago.
   ``I'm not looking to get ahead of the other (candidates),'' Kohl
said. ``I just want to get to the point where we are even.''
   On the Republican side, state Senate Minority Leader Susan
Engeleiter, 36, and Stephen B. King, 47, former chairman of the
state GOP, are running a more ideological race. He has labeled her
a liberal and she has called him an ultra-conservative.
   Proxmire, who devoted nearly 32 years in the Senate to fighting
for budget cuts, said he was disappointed by the hefty spending in
the race to replace him. Proxmire said he spent $145.10 in breezing
to re-election in 1982.
   Kohl, whose slogan is ``nobody's senator but yours,'' said he
would not be obligated to special interest groups if elected
because the money he spent was mainly his own.
   In his last campaign spending report, Kohl said he spent nearly
$2.1 million between his June 1 entry into the campaign and Aug.
24. He reported more than $1.5 million hand.
   ``We're spending way too much,'' Earl said. As of Aug. 24, Earl
had spent $431,719 and Garvey $360,000. La Follette reported
expenditures of $15,536. Engeleiter reported she spent $858,580
through Aug. 24, and King $342,907.
   One early Democratic candidate, Rep. Jim Moody, dropped out
shortly after Kohl's entry. He said he couldn't afford to compete
with Kohl.
   A recent poll commissioned by several TV stations showed Kohl
with 35 percent support and Earl with 33 percent among those who
said they were likely to vote. Garvey had 16 percent and La
Follette 6 percent. Nine percent were undecided.
   On the GOP side, Engeleiter led King 48 percent to 32 percent.
   Earl, 52, is a Madison attorney and former legislator who lost
his 1986 bid for re-election as governor to Republican Tommy G.
Thompson.
   Garvey, 48, a lawyer and former executive director of the
National Football League Players Association, lost a close battle
to unseat Republican Sen. Robert W. Kasten Jr. in 1986.
   La Follette, 48, in his third term as secretary of state, was a
professor at the University of Wisconsin-Parkside before his
election to the state Senate in 1972. He is a distant relative of
the La Follette family that produced several top Wisconsin
politicians, including two governors, and was an unsuccessful
candidate for lieutenant governor in 1978.
   King, now a businessman, is a former FBI agent who later served
John Mitchell when Mitchell headed President Nixon's
Watergate-tainted re-election campaign. His major campaign
fund-raiser featured Oliver North, a key figure in the Iran-Contra
affair.
   Engeleiter, a 12-year veteran of the Legislature.
   Differences between her and King became personal when King
brought up the subject of Engeleiter's two children, ages 1 and 4.
``If my family were young, if they were pre-schoolers, I would not
be making this race,'' King said.
   Engeleiter countered that nearly three out of four women work
outside the home, and that under King's philosophy, neither Kasten
nor Republican Rep. Thomas Petri would have a place in Congress.
   Here are highlights of the voting Tuesday:
   ARIZONA _ A large number of GOP legislators who voted to impeach
or convict ex-Gov. Evan Mecham earlier this year are being
challenged by his ultra-conservative supporters.
   MINNESOTA _ Both GOP Sen. David Durenberger and his likely
Democratic opponent, state Attorney General Hubert H. Humphrey III,
face minor opposition from within their parties.
   NEW HAMPSHIRE _ Republican Rep. Judd Gregg is favored to win the
nomination for governor to succeed John Sununu, who is retiring.
Democrat Paul McEachern has no primary opposition.
   VERMONT _ Rep. Jim Jeffords faces conservative Michael Griffes
for the GOP nomination for the seat of retiring Republican Sen.
Robert Stafford. William Gray is the unopposed Democratic nominee.
   UTAH _ Democrats Craig S. Oliver and Robert W. Stringham both
seek the nomination to oppose three-term Republican Rep. Howard C.
Nielson for Congress.
</TEXT>
