<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fires-Yellowstone     09-12 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires-Yellowstone,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Becomes Fiery Battleground In Losing War With Nature</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buffalo graze
nonchalantly near flaming trees, but people are not reacting so
coolly, and residents once worried about losing business to forest
fires now fear losing their homes.
   Fire has destroyed buildings around the Old Faithful geyser and
has threatened tourist towns on the periphery of the country's
first national park.
   The Montana towns of Cooke City and Silver Gate outside the
park's northeast entrance were evacuted twice last week. Jardine,
Mont., near the northern gate, was evacuated Saturday.
   Firefighters saved Cooke City and Silver Gate, but only by
burning thousands of acres of forest to remove fuel from the fire's
path. The so-called backfires left the once-picturesque towns
flanked by black, skeletal trees.
   ``All we can do ... is herd it around improvements and
structures _ and don't get anybody killed,'' said Bob Martines, a
structure protection officer in Cooke City.
   The 2.2 million-acre park, dedicated in 1872, attracts more than
2 million visitors a year who marvel at geysers and hot springs,
mountain scenery and wild animals.
   But tourists have stayed away in droves this summer, and
residents of tourism-dependent towns around the park have
complained bitterly about the Park Service's initial reluctance to
respond to the fires.
   ``A guy gets really bitter when it keeps dragging on and on and
on,'' said David Klatt of Cooke City, who spent spent three days in
a motel room outside of town last week, waiting out an evacuation.
   In this summer of heat and drought, Yellowstone is suffering the
worst fires in at least 200 years.
   Forest fires have charred more than 1 million acres in
Yellowstone and in the surrounding national forests and parks in
Montana, Wyoming, and Idaho.
   Each day, firefighters pray for rain, but at park headquarters
near Mammoth Hot Springs this is the third-driest summer on record.
Only 1.6 inches of rain fell at Mammoth in June, July and August _
one-third the normal rainfall.
   It was also the hottest summer on record, with temperatures
steaming an average of 5 degrees above normal, the weather service
said.
   Though other areas are hard hit, Yellowstone is the top concern
of federal officials. Of $250 million spent so far on fighting
fires, $78 million has gone toward efforts around the park, said
the Boise Interagency Fire Center, which coordinates firefighting
in the West.
   Since 1972, park officials have allowed lightning-sparked fires
to burn.
   ``In the past 16 years, we had 140 fires that burned 33,000
acres. That averages about 240 acres apiece before they went out on
their own,'' said John Varley, chief of the park's research
division.
   The fires help cleanse the pine forest. They clear deadwood,
create new meadows for forage, release nutrients for new plants and
free the pines' seeds from their cones.
   A cool, wet spring lulled park officials into believing this
summer would be no different. But the heat and low humidity left
the forest more parched than kiln-dried lumber.
   By July 15, when the Park Service decided to start fighting the
fires, it was too late to stop them.
   Fire crew boss John Borton has battled forest fires in the West
for 18 years, but the blaze he had been fighting and sleeping near
for 25 nights was something new.
   ``This is the edge of a fire that goes back 50 miles,'' he said.
``It's as out of control as it was six weeks ago. This is the most
extreme fire behavior that just about any of us has ever seen.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-RedBarron     09-12 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Red Barron,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Red Barron' of Florida Legislature Ousted After Three Decades</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the portraits of former Florida
Senate presidents hanging in the chamber, it's easy to pick out
Dempsey Barron. He's the one riding the horse.
   The Panhandle lawyer-rancher, who friends and foes alike call
one of the most powerful men in Florida government, exercises his
authority ``exactly like the Godfather,'' a former colleague says.
   But that era is coming to an end. The 66-year-old, auburn-haired
``Red Barron'' was narrowly defeated in the Democratic primary on
Tuesday. He lost to Vince Bruner, a Fort Walton Beach lawyer born a
year after Barron was first elected to the Legislature 32 years ago.
   A conservative Democrat, Barron served as Senate president in
1975-76, once ordering then-Gov. Reubin Askew to stay out of the
upper chamber, although in much more colorful words.
   Since then, he has served almost continuously as chairman of the
Senate Rules Committee, giving him control over the legislative
calendar and make-or-break authority over bills.
   ``He's really one of a kind,'' said Allen Morris, historian and
former clerk of the state House. ``I've been here since 1941 and
really can't think of anybody who compares to him.''
   His departure ``will reorganize the thinking in the Senate,''
Morris said. ``The senators no longer will have to puzzle over wat
Dempsey thinks of each bill.''
   In his successful primary challenge, Bruner cited Barron's
support of a tax increase and claimed Barron failed to pay
attention to constituent needs and was too cozy to state business
interests.
   His challenge was aided by feminists angered that Barron helped
kill the Equal Rights Amendment and by trial lawyers who opposed
Barron's efforts on behalf of insurance companies, many of them
represented by his law firm, to limit the size of verdicts in
negligence suits.
   ``He was the architect of the defeat of the Equal Rights
Amendment in Florida,'' said Molly Yard, president of the National
Organization for Women. ``Good riddance! I think we helped to dig
his grave.''
   As a result of Barron's departure, some colleagues have been
predicting a more partisan and open Senate, and reforms to reduce
the virtually dictatorial power of the leadership.
   Barron exercised his power ``exactly like The Godfather,'' said
former Democratic Sen. Roberta Fox. ``His ability to do that was
seductive, not in a sexual sense, but he had a truly seductive
personality.''
   The power was wielded with little regard to party labels and
party loyalty.
   When unable to get his way in Democratic caucuses, he forged
coalitions between conservatives in his own party, or
``Dempseycrats,'' and Republicans. He angered Democrat leaders by
throwing his support to Republican candidates for national and
statewide office, including Bob Martinez in his successful run for
governor in 1986.
   Republicans did much of the mourning over his loss.
   ``I'm shocked, I'm sick,'' said Tommy Thomas, a former state
Republican Party chairman.
   ``We knew he was in a tight race,'' said Brian Ballard, chief of
operations for Martinez. ``But we all thought he would make it
because he's Dempsey, he's the `Red Barron,' and he's supposed to
pull out.''
   But the Democratic state chairman, Charles Whitehead, had little
sympathy. ``Sen. Barron lost the race when he and Bob Martinez rode
their horses together and put their arms around each other at the
Bonifay Rodeo two years ago,'' Whitehead said. ``He alienated all
the Democrats in the area by doing that.
   ``And it turns out Martinez and Barron joined together to give
us the biggest tax increase we ever had.''
   Bruner had hammered Barron, usually a steadfast opponent of
taxes _ any taxes _ for his support of Florida's ill-fated, $1
billion-a-year services tax. The tax was repealed in the wake of
stiff opposition last year, but the governor and Barron wound up
accepting an even bigger increase in the general sales tax.
   Barron said he has no regrets and plans to spend more time at
his ranches in the Florida Panhandle and Wyoming.
   ``I'm a pretty private person and I'm going to live my life with
my friends and move down the road,'' he said. ``My cattle are in
good shape. I'm going to go up and cut hay. ... I've enjoyed the
ride. Shed no tears for me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
