<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a777,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Race Time with Warmer Weather on Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `In Oregon,' with one graf to CORRECT that
residents were told to be ready to evacuate, UPDATE acreage. Subs
16th graf `We'd have' witho one graf to UPDATE acreage of Montana's
Red Bench fire.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XYS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters took
advantage of chilly, damp weather Monday to strengthen lines around
fires that have ravaged nearly 1 million acres inside the park, but
hot, dry weather was predicted by midweek.
   ``It's a sleeping giant now,'' Denny Bungarz, a fire incident
commander, said during a briefing Monday. ``We want to tie it down
so when it wakes up it can't run on us.''
   Fire activity was limited Monday after a weekend of showers and
light snow _ the first significant precipitation since spring _
that gave firefighters a needed break from high wind and
temperatures that let fires grow by thousands of acres per day last
week.
   The fires inside the 2.2-million-acre park had burned 939,270
acres as of Monday.
   Temperatures remained in the 40s in the park Monday, keeping
humidity levels at up to 50 percent, but the weather was expected
to begin clearing Tuesday and temperatures were to reach 70 degrees
by Wednesday, drying the area once again.
   The cool, wet weekend also helped firefighters in surrounding
areas of Montana, Idaho and Wyoming, and in Colorado and Utah,
where a 15,700-acre fire was declared under control Monday.
   ``We're more optimistic this morning than we have been for some
weeks,'' said Bill Baden, Forest Service director at the
Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho. ``With the moisture we
have on the fires now it's cooled them down to where we can in and
work them directly.''
   The center, which coordinates forest fire suppression, calls
this the worst forest fire season in 30 years.
   Forests and brush also burned in Washington, where a 400-acre
fire that apparently began from an illegal campfire in an alpine
area of Olympic National Park had crews from three states fighting
it. And a fire in California's Gold Rush country in the Sierra
Nevada forced most of the 4,500 residents of Lake Wildwood to
evacuate for a second time Monday.
   In Oregon, a fast-moving fire broke out in dry grass and timber
in the Willamette National Forest and sheriff's deputies warned
residents about six miles southeast of Oakridge to be ready to
evacuate. The fire quickly burned 1,000 acres in rolling hills 10
to 15 miles southeast of Oakridge, forest spokeswoman Lorette
Laferriere said.
   Baden said there 28 fires still out of control in the West that
had charred 1.8 million acres.
   The favorable weather allowed Yellowstone officials to open all
roads through the park Monday except its northeastern entrance
leading to Cooke City, Mont., the route inside the park from
Mammoth Hot Springs to Canyon and Tower, and Craig Pass.
   About 1,000 Marines from Camp Pendleton, Calif., were to reach
Yellowstone on Wednesday and Thursday to help firefighters, while
some of the first soldiers sent to Yellowstone from Fort Lewis,
Wash., were not to be released until at least Saturday.
   ``We'll have lots of people here, so maybe we can nail this
thing,'' Bungarz said.
   Although moisture helped slow the advance of the flames, with
little growth recorded during the weekend, it would probably dry
out quickly, Bungarz said. He added, however, none of the fires
would make major progress until the area is thoroughly dried.
   ``We'd have to have a heck of a lot of rain to put the fire
out,'' said fire information officer Jim Payne on the 31,500-acre
Red Bench fire at Glacier National Park in Montana. ``You're
talking numbers of inches of rain.''
   Despite the return of warmer weather, the arrival of autumn
weather with lower temperatures and shorter days had officials
optimistic the fires would no longer make major advances.
   ``We still expect fire activity, but it won't be as intense or
as much or as fast as it has been in the past,'' said fire
information officer Sonya Capek. ``The days are getting shorter, so
the burning period is getting shorter.''
   North of the park in Montana, Gov. Ted Schwinden canceled his
sweeping ban on all recreational activities in the state's
fire-ravaged countryside because of the weekend weather.
   About 1,000 firefighters got the day off Monday in Montana
because up to a foot of snow fell on the eastern half of the
247,000-acre Cnyon Creek fire north of Helena, said fire
information officer Jane Weber. They were taken to a National Guard
facility to warm up and dry out their clothes.
   More than 100 residents evacuated from scattered homes, cabins
and ranches along the fire's eastern front were returning to the
region by Sunday and Monday, she added.
   Also in Montana, the Hellroaring Creek fire that had charred
81,900 acres and moved into Yellowstone was contained Sunday, said
information officer Chris Comstock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
