<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Smyslovsky     09-12 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Smyslovsky,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exiled Russian General Whose Troops Fought With Germans Is Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris Smyslovsky, an anti-communist
former Russian general whose World War II unit fought with Hitler's
troops against the Red Army, has died at age 91.
   Maj. Gen. Smyslovsky, who then called himself Arthur Holmston,
led a 6,000-man contingent known as the First Russian National Army
of the German Wehrmacht.
   At the end of World War II, he and 500 remaining soldiers
managed to reach neutral Liechtenstein, where staunchly
anti-communist Prince Franz Josef II granted them political asylum.
   Death notices published in Liechtenstein newspapers said he died
in the capital Vaduz last Monday and was buried Thursday. The
mass-circulation Swiss newspaper Sonntagsblick reported his death
Sunday.
   Once an officer in the Russian Imperial Guards, Smyslosvky went
into Polish and German exile after fighting the Bolsheviks in the
civil war. After Hitler invaded Russia in 1941, he became the first
Russian to command a Russian unit fighting for the Germans on the
eastern front.
   In a 1985 interview with The Associated Press, he said his goal
was to end communism in the Soviet Union and get rid of Stalin. But
he said he was not a Nazi.
   ``I thought that the Germans would be the only ones who could
defeat the Soviets and that the Allies then would defeat the
exhausted Germans,'' he said.
   ``What the Germans did was horrible. Hitler corrupted their
souls,'' he said. ``But the Soviets destroyed a whole nation,
Russia.''
   Smyslovsky said volunteers from among Soviet prisoners of war
formed the bulk of his army, with the rest made up of prewar exiles
like himself.
   When the eastern front collapsed, the unit fled westward and was
decimated by fighting.
   But Smyslovsky and his men, still heavily armed, marched through
Austria and crossed into Liechtenstein on May 3, 1945.
   Among them was Grand Duke Vladimir Cyrillovich, heir to the
Russian throne, whom the soldiers had picked up in Austria.
   The group encountered no resistance from Swiss border patrols
guarding the tiny principality between Austria and Switzerland,
which dissolved its army in 1868. The Russians were disarmed and
granted political asylum.
   A Soviet repatriation commission later interviewed Smyslovsky's
men, and almost half of them agreed to return.
   ``We have never heard from them again,'' Smyslovsky told AP.
   Most of the rest went into exile in Argentina, including
Smyslovsky. But in 1975, he returned to Liechtenstein with his wife
Irene, who survives him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
