<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0402,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Executive Slain, Supporters Celebrate Marcos' 71st
Birthday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to CORRECT that firm is
Malaysian-Filipino, sted Swiss-American as reported initially by
police, and Tree's age; picks up 4th graf pvs: Communist rebels...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAVAO CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six men firing submachine guns
killed a British executive in an ambush about 12 miles southwest of
this Mindanao island city, police said Sunday.
   Investigator Ernesto Fuertes said the victim, John Tree, 56, was
aboard a service vehicle that left a cocoa plantation when six
gunmen opened fire about noon Saturday.
   Tree died instantly. His Filipino driver suffered only slight
injuries, Fuertes said. Tree was vice president of the Philippine
Cocoa Estate Corp., a Malaysian-Filipino firm. Police initially
reported the firm was Swiss-American.
   Communist rebels near Davao City have threatened attacks on
American interests. But no such warning has been issued to British
businessmen.
   Lt. Col. Franco Calida, Davao area police commander, said by
telephone that the gunmen may have intended to kill the Filipino
plantation manager for Philippine Cocoa.
   The Filipino manager had refused demands to pay ``revolutionary
taxes'' to the New People's Army and had been receiving death
threats, Calida said.
   Calida added that the manager, Dioniso Capusan, was supposed to
have driven down the same road at the time of the noon attack.
Calida said he did not know if Tree had received similar threats.
   Supporters of Ferdinand Marcos meanwhile celebrated the ousted
president's 71st birthday Sunday with a rally in Manila and a giant
birthday cake in Laoag, a northern provincial capital about 250
miles to the north.
   About 5,000 Marcos supporters cheered under a light rain as
Marcos' niece, Cynthia Rocka, blew out the largest of 71 candles on
the 30-feet-by-75-feet cake, baked by dozens of volunteers.
   ``I thank you for having made by brother's birthday as great as
this,'' said Marcos' sister, Fortuna Barba, as she was presented
the first piece.
   Organizers of the cake project hoped about 24,000 people would
turn out for the celebration, but police estimated the crowd at
about 5,000.
   In Manila, about 3,000 Marcos supporters marked their leader's
birthday with fireworks and a rally in a downtown square, where
speakers denounced President Corazon Aquino, who toppled Marcos
during a popular uprising in February 1986.
   Marcos greeted his supporters in a telephone interview broadcast
over Manila radio station DZEC from Hawaii, where he fled after the
uprising.
   ``By the grace of the Almighty, we are still alive and it is my
hope that I can go back there, I can come back to the
Philippines,'' Marcos told his followers.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow Marcos to return, citing
national security. But the ousted president has asked the
anti-corruption court to order his return to defend himself during
a court hearing set for November.
   A decision by the court is pending. If the tribunal orders
Marcos home, the government is expected to appeal to the Supreme
Court.
   Marcos' late mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos, still lies in state.
She died in Manila last May 4 but remains unburied, and Marcos
supporters say the funeral will be delayed until Mrs. Aquino allows
the former president to come home for the service.
</TEXT>
