<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Press 2Takes   09-12 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Press, 2 Takes,0925</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Say They'd Be Accessible Presidents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush and Gov. Michael
Dukakis have issued matching promises of accessibility to the White
House press, but neither was saying how often he would hold formal
presidential news conferences.
   The rival presidential nominees made their statements on news
and information policies in written responses to inquiries by the
Freedom of Information Committee of The Associated Press Managing
Editors Association.
   Their replies were made public as APME officers and committee
chairmen met in New York on Monday.
   ``I hope words like `accessible,' `candid,' `honest' and `fair'
will be adjectives used to describe my relationship with the media
by historians,'' Republican Bush said. ``It certainly is what I
will strive for during my tenure as president.''
   The Reagan administration has come under frequent criticism for
limiting access to information.
   Dukakis renewed that criticism. The Democratic nominee prefaced
his comments on his plans with a charge that ``the Reagan-Bush
administration has waged an assault on the Freedom of Information
Act with every weapon in its arsenal.''
   Dukakis said he has a proven record of accessibility to
reporters, and would continue on that course as president.
   ``Throughout my public career I've believed in a free press and
my record shows I've practiced that belief,'' he said. ``As
president, I would hope to continue this pattern of accessibility
to the White House press corps, giving them and me the opportunity
to utilize our First Amendment freedoms.
   A questionnaire prepared for the FOI committee was given to both
candidates. Bush responded directly, answering each of the
questions. Dukakis replied by issuing a two-part position paper,
with one section on the freedom of information law and a second on
his press relations.
   Here is a partial transcript of their replies:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GEORGE BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. As president, what sort of tone would you set regarding
openness in government, access to government information and
freedom of information?
   A. Within the limits of national security, government should be
open to scrutiny by the media and the public. Ours is a democracy
where goverment must be accountable to the people. The
information-gathering process, from a news conference to the
Freedom of Information Act, is vital and essential to our system of
democracy.
   Q. What kind of relationship do you think you've had with the
media during your public career? How would you seek to improve it,
if at all?
   A. I think I have had a good relationship with the media. As
president, I hope that I will be able to spend more time talking
with smaller groups of reporters. I enjoy a good give and take, and
that kind of format allows me to get to know reporters a little
better and them to know me. Not only will this benefit reporters
but, more importantly, such free exchange will ultimately benefit
the general public as well.
   Q. Throughout history, presidents have had a variety of
relationships with the media. Are there any styles you would
emulate? Are there any you would avoid? When it comes time to write
the history of your relations with the media, what will it say?
   A. With the media, the Congress or the public, it would be a
mistake to attempt to be something or someone you're not. So, warts
and all, what you see is what you'll get.
   I hope words like ``accessible,'' ``candid,'' ``honest'' and
``fair'' will be adjectives used to describe my relationship with
the media by historians. It certainly is what I will strive for
during my tenure as president. ...
   Q. How frequently would you meet with reporters? How would you
conduct press conferences? How often would you hold press
conferences? Would you make any changes in the way President Reagan
has done his press conferences?
   A. There are a number of ways to communicate with both the media
and the public. Press conferences are one important way and they
would certainly be central to my effort to ensure accessibility in
my administration. One-on-one and group interviews, satellite
interviews with regional media, national televised addresses are
other examples of methods that a president can and should use to
provide the media with opportunities to discuss administration
policies and programs.
   My goal would be to get the right ``mix'' of all of the options
available to guarantee an open administration. Realistically, you
can't put a number on any of the working parts of an open approach
to accessibility, but you can make and keep a commitment to the
goal itself.
   Q. More specifically, what message will you send to your
executive agencies regarding Freedom of Information requests?
   A. My message will be simple: obey the law. ...
   Q. Here's a chance to offer some contructive criticism. What
things would you most like to change about the news media? What
should the nation's media do differently to better serve the public
interest?
   A. Accuracy and fairness are the name of the game. The media
goes to great lengths to be accurate. It needs to go to the same
lengths to be fair. While it is often necessary to use unnamed
sources in gathering information for a story, it puts the validity
of a story at a disadvantage. I hope the news media would rely as
little as possible on this approach to information gathering and
reporting.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
