<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Abortion     09-12 1065</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Abortion,1093</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0430 to change cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Campaign '88: Bush, Dukakis Take Opposite Stands on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to abortion, George Bush and
Michael Dukakis agree on one thing: each man says he personally
does not favor the controversial procedure.
   But beyond their personal feelings, the Republican and
Democratic presidential nominees have staked out opposite stands on
whether abortion should be legal and whether the government should
pay for the operation for poor women.
   Bush favors a constitutional amendment to overturn the 1973
Supreme Court decision, Roe vs. Wade, that legalized abortion. He
favors outlawing all abortions except in cases of rape, incest or
to save the life of the mother. He opposes Medicaid funding of
abortions for poor women except to save the woman's life.
   Dukakis, as a legislator and governor of Massachusetts, has been
a resolute supporter of women's legal right to choose abortion, as
well as government-funding of the operation for the poor.
   Anti-abortion pickets are a common sight at rallies for Dukakis
and his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, just as they
hounded the Democrats' ticket of Walter Mondale and Geraldine
Ferraro in 1984.
   Prior to becoming Ronald Reagan's running mate in 1980, Bush
opposed a constitutional amendment to overturn legalized abortion.
He once supported federal funding of abortions in cases of rape or
incest, as well as to save the mother's life.
   Asked in 1984 why he changed his position, Bush replied: ``There
has been _ I have to make a confession _ an evolution in my
position. There's been 15 million abortions since 1973, and I don't
take that lightly.''
   While Bush has altered his stand on the issue, others in the
Republican Party remain pro-choice, including the vice president's
campaign co-chairman, Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill. Recently, Bush said
his opposition to abortion is not a stand that he expects everyone
in his party has to share.
   Questioned about Martin's position during a campaign stop in
Illinois on Friday, Bush said, ``I have a lot of key supporters who
agree with Lynn and a lot that agree with me.'' He added: ``Who's
going to have a litmus test that everybody has to agree with
everybody on every single issue?''
   Asked about the hardline stand against abortion in the
Republican platform, Bush said, ``The platform states the position
of the platform but nobody in our party takes a litmus test that
says that everybody has to agree on every issue. I expect the
Democrats could say the same thing.''
   Dukakis has been called ``a pro-abortion zealot'' by Dr. J.C.
Willke, president of the National Right to Life Committee. The
group's legislative director, Douglas Johnson, said, ``Dukakis says
he's personally opposed, but he wants to subsidize it on demand.''
   He pointed to Dukakis' sponsoring of a bill in 1970 to legalize
abortion in Massachusetts, and later, as governor, his vetoes of
several bills with restrictions on abortion funding.
   Facing a strident anti-abortion protest in a Chicago suburb
Tuesday, Dukakis said: ``While I don't favor abortion or think it's
a good thing, I happen to think that in the last analysis it's up
to the woman, in the exercise of her own conscience and religious
beliefs, to make that decision.''
   ``We should not brand women as criminals for making that
decision. I think that's what most Americans believe, and it's
certainly what the Supreme Court has held,'' said Dukakis.
   Bush, in his acceptance speech at the Republican National
Convention in New Orleans Aug. 18, said, ``Is it right to believe
in the sanctity of life and protect the lives of innocent children?
My opponent says no _ but I say yes. ... We've got to change from
abortion to adoption.''
   Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League, said, ``There is a stark, stark difference
between the two candidates'' and between the two parties' platforms
on abortion.
   The Democrats' terse platform, without mentioning the word
abortion, says, ``the right of reproductive choice should be
guaranteed regardless of ability to pay.''
   The GOP platform contains anti-abortion language in several
sections, including a plank that declares: ``the unborn child has a
fundamental individual right to life which cannot be infringed.''
It endorses both a human life amendment and legislation to extend
the 14th Amendment's protections to the unborn.
   Bentsen has said he, too, personally opposes abortion and does
not favor federal funding except in cases of rape, incest or to
save the mother's life. But the National Right to Life Committee
and the National Abortion Rights Action League both agree that
Bentsen has usually voted against restrictions on abortion funding
and against constitutional amendments to ban abortion.
   Bentsen was absent July 27 when the Senate voted 73-19 to allow
Medicaid funding of abortions in promptly reported cases of rape or
incest.
   The House, on a 216-166 vote Friday, refused to go along with
the Senate move, which would be the first liberalization of
Medicaid abortion funding in seven years. The Senate may take up
the issue early this week.
   Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, voted with that
Senate majority July 27. But NARAL says he was among ``many
anti-choice senators'' who voted for the amendment only as an
alternative to accepting even fewer restrictions on Medicaid
funding.
   Quayle is rated highly by the anti-abortion groups and lowly by
NARAL. Quayle says he generally opposes abortion except to save the
mother's life.
   Activists on both sides agree the next president is likely to
make several appointments to the Supreme Court that could sway the
tribunal's ruling on abortion.
   The current court has four justices who generally support the
1973 Roe vs. Wade decision, four who have been critical of it and
one _ the newest member, Anthony Kennedy _ whose views are not yet
clear.
   ``My biggest concern is the next president's role in appointing
at least three Supreme Court justices, if not more,'' said
Michelman, whose organization helped defeat President Reagan's
nomination of Robert Bork to the Supreme Court. Bork had criticized
Roe vs. Wade.
   Johnson said, ``On Inauguration Day next January, there'll be
three pro-abortion justices over 80 years of age.''
   A human life amendment is ``a long ways down the road,'' he
said, but if the Democrats capture the White House, ``Dukakis could
appoint a pro-abortion majority for years to come.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
