<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Well Fire,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Effort to Cap Burning Oil Well Fails</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CeCe in 2nd graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FILLMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters failed in their first
attempt to cap a burning oil well Sunday after draining thousands
of gallons of oil from storage tanks near the blaze, a spokeswoman
said.
   Another attempt to cap the well was planned for Monday, said
Ventura County fire dispatcher CeCe Grives.
   An attempt to flood the well with saltwater failed when a crack
was found in a pipe on the oil rig, she said.
   Draining oil from 11 storage tanks in the vicinity of the
inferno was a pressing concern soon after the fire began Thursday.
Each tank holds about 33,600 gallons, county authorities said.
   One man was burned and $5 million worth of drilling equipment
was destroyed when the well ignited at a Seneca Corp. oil field in
Los Padres National Forest.
   The blaze apparently began when a spark from an electric fan
ignited fumes, officials said.
   Oil field worker John Henry, 24, was in serious but stable
condition Sunday evening at Sherman Oaks Burn Center with burns
over 50 percent of his body.
   Oil rig firefighter Coots Matthews, whose Houston-based firm,
Boots & Coots Inc., was called to extinguish the blaze, has said
the effort would probably take a week.
   The fire burned at the southern end of the national forest,
which reaches into five Southern California counties.
</TEXT>
