<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     09-12 0987</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought-related River Traffic Losses Pegged at $200 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary review by the Agriculture
Department of this summer's barge traffic on drought-reduced rivers
shows some of the huge problems that have plagued the movement of
grain from inland farm points into export shipping channels.
   In mid-June, low water levels on the lower Mississippi and Ohio
rivers began to stall barges at choke points for more than a day.
By the end of the month stoppages were a regular occurrence.
   ``Reduced load size, smaller tows and lengthened transit times
have dropped the capacity of the Mississippi River system by at
least 50 percent,'' the report said. ``Difficult navigation and
increased travel time add to costs, especially for fuel and labor
which normally account for about 35 percent of total operating
costs.''
   Overall, according to a recent industry study, barge operators
could lose as much as $200 million this year.
   The smaller river flow forced gyrations in barge rates, the
report said. Even before the drought's full effect, rates were
going higher because of greater demand. In the first five months,
they averaged nearly a fourth more than in the same January-May
period of 1987.
   In the first two weeks of June, barge rates jumped 4 percent
from the end of May. By the end of June, rates had nearly tripled.
   ``This increase was short-lived,'' the report said. ``In the
first week of July, rates fell to about 125 percent above the end
of May, and by month's end had returned to pre-drought levels.''
   By the first week of August, rates from Peoria, Ill., to export
points at New Orleans, La., averaged $6.85 per ton, up 12 percent
from a year earlier.
   ``The decline in rates after the first week of July resulted
from a sharp reduction in demand for barge service,'' the report
said. ``As export volume shrank and producers held stocks in
anticipation of higher prices, shipments of grain and soybeans in
June fell 16 percent from May, and in July dropped 37 percent from
May.''
   According to the new outlook report by the department's Economic
Research Service, the higher transportation costs and reduced
capacity sharply boosted prices of corn delivered by barge to
Louisiana's Gulf ports.
   Between June 17 and June 23, corn prices rose from $3.31 to
$3.32 per bushel to a range of $3.63 to $3.66 per bushel, the
report said.
   ``These ports account for about 50 percent of U.S. grain exports
and receive 70 percent of the grain, chiefly corn, by barge,'' the
report said. ``Similar price increases are anticipated in the
poultry producing areas of the Southeast. Barges normally carry
about a third of the grain shipped to these states.''
   Trucks are not an alternative to barges for moving grain, the
report said. A fully loaded barge holds 1,500 tons of grain, or
about 35 truck loads. A mile-long truck convoy, bumper-to-bumper,
would replace fewer than 2{ barges.
   ``One day, 1,760 barges were stacked above Greenville, Miss.,
287 miles from New Orleans,'' the report said. ``Grain in these
barges would have filled a line of trucks 755 miles long.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A forecast by the Agriculture Department that
the cash receipts of farmers are likely to increase this year
despite huge production losses due to drought has put economists to
work explaining why.
   Cash receipts, or the gross from sales of crops and livestock,
are expected to rise $5 billion to $9 billion this year from 1987,
says the department's Economic Research Service. In 1980, another
drought year, farm cash receipts climbed nearly $8 billion.
   Since droughts have an impact on production, why don't cash
receipts decline?
   ``One reason is that the prices of drought-affected commodities
tend to increase more than production falls, raising the total
value of the crop,'' the agency says in a new outlook report.
``Another reason is that marketing does not drop as much as
production because stocks (inventories) are sold to make up the
harvest shortfall.''
   The economists say the demand for farm commodities is inelastic,
meaning that a 1 percent decline in production, for example, leads
to a price increase greater than 1 percent.
   ``Some farmers may benefit from the higher prices _ those in
areas with adequate rainfall, those who irrigate and those with
large unsold stocks of previous years' crops,'' the report said.
``However, higher cash receipts (nationally) do not imply that all
farmers are better off because of the drought.''
   The report added: ``Many farmers will suffer large declines in
cash receipts if their individual production falls by much more
than prices rise. Farmers in drought-stricken areas without large
stocks of unsold crops from previous years have little to fall back
on.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honey bees are famous for pollinating crops,
but an Agriculture Department scientist says the bees don't work
hard enough when it comes to hybrid cotton plants.
   Gerald M. Loper, a plant physiologist at the Carl Hayden Bee
Research Center, Tucson, Ariz., said there's something about cotton
pollen that bees don't like.
   ``They will spend 20 minutes meticulously combing the pollen off
their bodies before returning to their hives,'' he said. And that's
time lost from their ``job'' of pollinating cotton plants.
   Bees are needed to pollinate hybrid strains of cotton by
carrying pollen from male to female plants, which produce the
hybrid seed. Regular cotton does its own pollinating without the
help of bees.
   The hybrid strains have a potential for boosting cotton yields
by as much as 25 percent and producing long fiber for specialty
markets, Loper said in a recent report. If only the bees would work
harder.
   India and Mexico grow hybrid cotton but rely on hand labor for
pollination to produce seeds. Labor costs and import restrictions
on foreign cotton seed have put pressure on the honey bee to do the
job in the United States, Loper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MarijuanaMedicine     09-12 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marijuana Medicine,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Opinion Notwithstanding, Changes Still Years Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Drug Enforcement Administration official
created a stir last week with a formal recommendation to his agency
chief that marijuana be made legal for limited medical uses, but
any changes are still years away.
   The opinion by administrative law judge Francis L. Young
amounted to a ringing endorsement of certain benefits from smoking
pot _ mainly to help cancer patients tolerate highly toxic
chemotherapy.
   Moreover, he concluded that federal law gives officials no
choice but to change the way they classify the ancient weed. To do
otherwise, he wrote, would be to act in an ``unreasonable,
arbitrary and capricious'' manner.
   That is the legal jargon for the criterion courts use to decide
whether administrators are acting within the laws they administer
or are imposing their own desires.
   At the same time, however, Young's decision took tacit note of
political realities that left even those strongly favoring his
position doubtful that changes are likely for several years.
   Laurence O. McKinney, president of a small company called
Cannabis Corp. of America in Cambridge, Mass., and a petitioner in
the case, was jubilant with the decision because he believes there
will be an eventual financial bonanza for his company.
   The key word is eventual.
   McKinney said in a telephone interview that he is not optimistic
the DEA administrator will accept the law judge's finding and
predicted it will take at least two years before he and other
petitioners can get federal courts to order the finding implemented.
   Then, he acknowledged, the matter would have to go to the Food
and Drug Administration, a process he said probably would take at
least two more years.
   There would be a certain irony in the FDA being instructed by
courts to deal with marijuana.
   Young noted in his opinion that the agency ``is looking at a
synthetically formed new drug'' when it operates under the Federal
Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act that gives it regulatory authority.
   ``The marijuana plant is anything but a new drug,'' Young wrote.
``Uncontroverted evidence in this record indicates that marijuana
was being used therapeutically by mankind 2,000 years before the
birth of Christ.''
   To say it would be a voyage in uncharted regulatory waters for
the FDA to regulate marijuana would be an understatement. The
question is not before the agency now and efforts to get three
separate and normally helpful FDA officials to discuss the issue _
even informally _ were unsuccessful.
   Young noted in his decision that the question is politically
touchy.
   ``The judge realizes that strong emotions are aroused on both
sides of any discussion concerning the use of marijuana,'' Young
wrote. ``Nonetheless, it is essential for this agency, and its
administrator, calmly and dispassionately to review the evidence of
record, correctly apply the law, and act accordingly.''
   He continued: ``There are those who, in all sincerity, argue
that the transfer of marijuana to Schedule II will `send a signal'
that marijuana is `OK' generally for recreational use. This
argument is specious. It presents no valid reason for refraining
from taking an action required by law in light of the evidence.''
   And the evidence, he said, clearly shows that smoking marijuana
helps many cancer patients tolerate their treatment.
   His recommendation is that marijuana be moved from Schedule I _
strictly illegal except in research _ to Schedule II, whereby it
could be prescribed by physicians but only under the same tightly
controlled conditions that apply to such drugs as morphine and
cocaine.
   His 69-page opinion, summing up a 15-volume record, is replete
with testimony from physicians, patients and relatives that
marijuana counters the nausea and vomiting that can be so severe in
some patients it causes them to abandon potentially live-saving
treatment.
   Young concluded that marijuana cigarettes are superior in many
cases to synthetic capsules containing the active chemical present
in the plant. ``Attempting to orally administer the synthetic THC
capsule to a vomiting patient presents obvious problems,'' he said.
``It is vomited right back up before it can have any effect.''
   Having concluded that the marijuana plant meets the first
criterion of having a legitimate medical use, Young went on to
address safety issues.
   ``In strict medical terms marijuana is far safer than many foods
we commonly consume,'' he said. ``For example, eating 10 raw
potatoes can result in a toxic response. By comparison, it is
physically impossible to eat enough marijuana to induce death.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
