<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignNotebook     09-12 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Notebook,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush, Saying Reagan Isn't Scary, Spooked By
`Pig'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To George Bush, the current occupant of the
White House is blessed with ``a great sense of humor if you like
jokes and stuff.'' What's more, he's ``not scary.''
   That's how the Republican presidential nominee sized up
President Reagan during an impromptu lunch with two fifth graders
he plucked at random from a crowd at a downtown rally in Pekin, Ill.
   John Keene and Brent Chandler, both 10, were invited by the vice
president to dine with him at the Red Hen Restaurant. He ordered a
chicken sandwich for himself and hot dogs for his two young lunch
partners. Talk turned quickly to sports and politics.
   ``What's your opinion of the Olympics?'' Bush asked the two boys.
   Brent said he hoped to watch the games on television. Bush said
he had just been to a sendoff in Disneyland for U.S. Olympic
athletes headed for Seoul, Korea _ an event he said he enjoyed
immensely.
   Bush asked if either one lived on a farm.
   John said he did, one with horses and cows, and that in fact his
mother had just gotten a bad bruise in a riding accident on a
``really crazy horse.''
   She was ``very lucky'' the horse didn't fall on top of her, Bush
observed, recalling the rodeo accident that claimed the life of
Commerce Secretary Malcolm Baldrige in 1987.
   Brent then got his question in: ``What's the president like?''
   ``He's a good guy, he's got a sense of humor if you like jokes
and stuff. He's very, very nice, not scary, a guy you can talk
to,'' Bush said.
   ``Some guys you can relax with and some you can't,'' he added.
   But the two fifth graders themselves were anything but relaxed.
Not only were they eating lunch with the vice president in front of
an imposing troop of photographers and reporters, but so much time
had elapsed that they feared being stranded. They had come to town
on a school field trip.
   ``How will you get back?'' Bush himself wondered. ``I don't
know,'' John responded glumly.
   ``Somebody ought to tell them (the teachers) that they're
here,'' Bush told an aide.
   The veep assured the two boys he'd make sure they got home _
even if it meant taking them for a ride in his motorcade.
   However, classmates had been waiting outside the restaurant _
and gave the pair a hero's welcome.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Another meal, another place.
   It was Los Angeles, the end of a day that began with a campaign
appearance at a fish packing plant in San Diego, and the vice
president was in a romantic mood as he dined alone with Barbara,
his wife of 43 years.
   ``I looked over at her and said, `Bar, you mean a lot to me.''
   To which, the vice president playfully told reporters traveling
with him on Air Force Two, Mrs. Bush responded: ``May I tell you
something?''
   ``I said, `anything.' She said, `Fish spilled on your red tie.'''
   ```Look, sweetie, 43 years, I'm talking emotion,''' Bush quoted
himself. ``We're talking family values here,'' Bush continued.
   ``There was an understanding between us at that very moment that
transcended the skeptical look on the waiter's face. It was a
special moment there.
   ``Once in a while you luck into something like that on the
campaign trail.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   When Bush presided over the sendoff of U.S. Olympic athletes at
Disneyland, his staff took pains to make sure that the vice
president was not standing directly alongside Goofy, Mickey Mouse
or other well-recognizable Disney characters.
   They didn't want the inevitable photo of such a pairing to fall
into the wrong hands.
   When reporters observed to Bush that he appeared to be keeping
his distance from Mickey Mouse, the vice president responded: ``I
was only one down from the damn guy.''
   However, Bush said that he was rattled by one of the Three
Little Pigs. ``He just kept staring at me, with this expression,''
Bush said, making a funny face.
   ``My word of honor: I looked over there, and said, It's not the
mouse that's bothering me. And he (the pig) kept, he kept...His
expression never changed, never changed. Just stared at you all the
time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum, a Washington-based reporter for The
Associated Press, is covering George Bush's presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
