<1ST_LINE>r a PM-O'Connor-Gays     09-12 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O'Connor-Gays,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Condemns Anti-Gay Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, who has been the target
of protests by homosexuals, condemned recent attacks of gays as the
work of ``utterly stupid'' people.
   ``I wish I had language strong enough to condemn this kind of
cruelty,'' O'Connor said at St. Patrick's Cathedral before his
sermon Sunday.
   ``Anyone who performs such actions in the belief that he or she
is in some way helping society is utterly stupid,'' said the head
of the New York archdioces. ``Anyone who does such a thing thinking
it is justified by church teaching about homosexual behavior is
grossly ignorant of what the church actually teaches.''
   The cardinal specifically mentioned an Aug. 22 incident in which
two men walking on Manhattan's Upper West Side were surrounded and
beaten by a group of teen-age boys shouting anti-homosexual
epithets. One of the two men was stabbed three times and remains
hospitalized.
   ``These actions were so brutal that they could have resulted in
murder,'' O'Connor said.
   For more than a year, a group of gay Catholics has picketed
outside the cathedral once a month to protest what they see as
discrimination against homosexuals by the Roman Catholic church.
   The leader of one gay rights group _ Thomas B. Stoddard,
executive director of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund _
on Sunday called O'Connor's statement, ``an important step
forward.''
</TEXT>
