<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Official Says Shuttle Launch May Take More Than One Try</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the nation's space flight program
says NASA will not launch space shuttle Discovery late this month
unless conditions are virtually perfect for the nation's first
shuttle flight since the 1986 Challenger disaster.
   ``We're going to wait until we have it right, and then we're
going to do it,'' said Rear Adm. Richard Truly, head of the shuttle
program. ``I think the American people expect that of us and that's
what we're going to do.''
   Truly, appearing on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,
said it may take more than one countdown to get the Discovery off
the ground. He said that if two recent successful simulations had
been the real thing, a launch would not have taken place because of
weather and winds.
   ``I think that when we get do get to a launch date on the latter
part of this month, it wouldn't surprise me at all if it took us
two or three times to get airborne,'' Truly said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prison Population Hit Record Total of 604,824 in June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says federal and state prison
population grew to a record 604,824 inmates in June, increasing at
a rate that would require 900 new prison beds every week.
   The federal Bureau of Justice Statistics reported Sunday that
the national inmate population grew by 4 percent in the first six
months of 1988, with the number of female prisoners increasing by
6.7 percent.
   California, which added 5,146 inmates for a 7.7 percent increase
during the period, accounted for 22 percent of the nationwide
growth in the prison population and housed nearly 12 percent of all
federal and state prisoners, the report said.
   The largest percentage increases from Jan. 1 through June 30
occurred in Rhode Island, which reported 17.9 percent more inmates.
