<2ND_LINE>PM-Miss America-Losers,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Bitterness Among Pageant Contestants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Miss America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the 50 women who vied for the
Miss America 1989 title and lost to Miss Minnesota say they're
looking forward to an exciting year as a state queen.
   Miss Alabama Jenny Lee Jackson, fourth runner-up in the 62nd
Miss America Pageant, said Sunday she was happy to be headed home.
   ``They already treat me like I'm Miss America down there,'' the
21-year-old Auburn University senior said.
   The mood of the 50 women after the pageant ended early Sunday
was marked by expressions of glee, not gloom.
   ``No gripes here,'' said Miss Hawaii Desiree Moana Cruz, one of
10 pageant finalists.
   ``This is one happy girl,'' said the 26-year-old from Hilo.
``Instead of being 5-9, I'm like 6-2. My feet haven't touched the
ground.''
   The new Miss America is Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson, a
22-year-old Stanford University student who wants to be a
Harvard-trained lawyer. Miss Carlson left this seaside resort on a
yearlong tour of the country.
   For Carlson and the other finalists, the competition was a
chance to perform before a television audience of millions in what
was probably a once-in-a-lifetime moment.
   ``I did what I came here to do,'' said third runner-up Miss
California Marlise Sharleen Ricardos, whose emotional singing was
one of the most polished performances of the pageant.
   ``I couldn't believe I was standing up there,'' said the
26-year-old from San Pedro, who wants to be a movie actress. ``I
knew that I did the best I possibly could have. I know I could have
been Miss America.''
   The contestants said that they saw no hint of nastiness or
unfair competition among the women.
   ``There was no one that was out for blood,'' said Miss
Mississippi Carla Haag.
   ``I met and made some wonderful friends,'' said Miss Jackson.
   Miss Cruz said she recalls the contestants hugging each other
backstage after the pageant, vowing, ``Friend for life. Friend for
life.''
   The contestants said Miss Carlson, the new Miss America, seemed
quiet during the pageant, intent on the competition.
   ``To tell you the truth, I didn't really notice her,'' said Miss
Haag.
</TEXT>
