<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   09-12 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0401,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with closing Nikkei, dollar</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices rebounded moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed higher at
27,756.74. The index, a 93.01-point loser Friday, regained 109.64
points or 0.40 percent after opening at 17,698.93.
   The dollar closed at 133.42 yen, up 0.47 yen from last Friday's
close of 132.95 yen. It opened at 133.82 yen and eased toward the
end of trading after moving in a range of 133.34-133.85 yen.
   Dealers said last Friday's report of a 0.6 percent increase in
the U.S. wholesale price index for August boosted investor
confidence in the U.S. economy and prompted them to buy back some
dollars.
   ``Some foreign exchange banks were buying the dollar to adjust
their positions, but investors are basically in a wait-and-see mood
before the scheduled announcement of the U.S. trade figures,'' said
an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The Commerce Department is to announce July U.S. trade figures
in Washington on Wednesday.
   Trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange was ``a bit slow mainly
because it's `sleepy Monday,' but the market overall is in good
shape,'' according to a dealer at Nomura Securities.
   A national holiday later in the week, Respect for the Aged Day,
will close markets and financial institutions on Thursday, further
slowing the momentum of trade, he added.
</TEXT>
