<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gorbachev     09-12 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Leader Back From Vacation, Leaves for Siberia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Tass news agency reported today that
Mikhail S. Gorbachev left Moscow for a city in Siberia, indicating
the Soviet leader had returned from his summer vacation.
   On July 30, Gorbachev met in the Kremlin with visiting Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany, then dropped from
official view.
   Soviet officials, speaking on condition they not be identified,
said Gorbachev had gone on vacation in the southern Soviet Union,
as he does every year.
   The personal lives of Kremlin officials remain little known,
despite the increased openness in society inaugurated by Gorbachev,
and no official announcement was made of the Soviet leader's
whereabouts in August.
   In a dispatch labeled with the Russian word for lightning,
indicating news of the greatest importance, Tass today announced
Gorbachev's departure for Krasnoyarsk from Moscow.
   It gave no details of how long Gorbachev will stay in the
Siberian city some 2,000 miles southeast of Moscow, and did not say
what his activities there will be.
