<HEAD>Cargo Rocket Docks With Soviet Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo rocket brought fuel, food and mail today
to the three Soviet cosmonauts manning the orbiting Mir space
station, the Tass news agency reported.
   Tass said the Progress rocket docked with the Mir at 5:22 a.m.
Moscow time (9:22 p.m. EDT Sunday) with the help of automatic
on-board systems.
   ``It brought supplies of fuel for the united propulsion system
of the station, foodstuffs, equipment, apparatus and mail,'' Tass
said. The news agency had announced the launch of the Progress-38
on Saturday.
   Tass said the three Soviet spacemen aboard the Mir _ Vladimir
Titov, Musa Manarov, Valery Polyakov _ are feeling fine, and that
on-board systems are working normally.
   Last week, two other cosmonauts, a Soviet and an Afghan, had
difficulties when they separated their Soyuz capsule from the Mir
for a return to Earth. Equipment problems and human error delayed
their landing by a day.
</TEXT>
