<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-12 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen, while
stock prices rebounded moderately in Tokyo today.
   The dollar closed at 133.42 yen, up 0.47 yen from Friday's close
of 132.95 yen, with spot volume estimated at $4.8 billion.
   After opening at 133.82 yen, the U.S. currency gradually
declined, then reversed direction after Japanese trade figures for
August were released late in the afternoon, said Hajime Sugiyama of
the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``The trade surplus, $4.9 billion, was less than most of the
investors had expected. Now they have started worrying that the
U.S. trade balance for July may not be too bad,'' he said.
   The U.S. trade figures are scheduled to be announced Wednesday.
   ``That's why some investors sold yen to buy dollars,'' Sugiyama
added.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues closed at 27,756.74, up 109.64 points or 0.40
percent from Friday's close of 27,647.10.
   Steels and high-tech issues, which attracted investors during
the afternoon session, pushed up the Nikkei index, which had
fluctuated in the morning. Volume traded on the market's first
section was estimated at 700 million shares.
   ``Volume was quite satisfactory for a day like this, considering
it's Monday, especially when everybody is worried about the U.S.
trade figures due soon,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``Investors are getting rather optimistic here,'' the analyst
added.
   Other dealers said a fall in crude oil prices last week wiped
out Tokyo investors' concern over inflation and higher interest
rates in the United States.
</TEXT>
