<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissAmerica-Reax     09-12 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miss America-Reax,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Town Residents, Relatives Joyous Over Selection Of Miss
America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Miss America, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for Minneapolis-dated item on digest.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANOKA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this Minneapolis suburb, which
bills itself as the ``Halloween capital of the world,'' are eager
to add a new label: Home of Miss America.
   ``It puts the city on the map,'' Mayor Steve Halsey said after
Miss Minnesota Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson was crowned Miss America
1989 early Sunday.
   ``I can see it now,'' said Bruce Frank, general manager of KANO
radio in this city of 16,000 about 10 miles northwest of
Minneapolis: ``Welcome to Anoka, home of Gretchen E. Carlson, Miss
America.
   ``Everyone I talked to is just ecstatic,'' said Frank, whose
station sent a good-luck telegram with 276 signatures to Miss
Carlson in Atlantic City, N.J., before the pageant's finale began
Saturday.
   Anoka claims to sponsor the largest celebration of Halloween in
the world. The city has held a parade and other Halloween
activities since the 1930s, when city officials organized events to
deter young people from tipping over outhouses and performing other
pranks and vandalism, Halsey said.
   Miss Carlson is well known in Anoka because of her talent as a
violin virtuoso and academic excellence at Anoka High School, where
she was a class co-valedictorian in 1984.
   Her father, Lee, owns a car dealership here and a grandfather,
the Rev. William Hyllengren, was pastor of a Lutheran church here
before he retired.
   Anoka-Hennepin School District Superintendent Lew Finch said he
shouldn't have been surprised because Miss Carlson has been a
success all her life, but said he couldn't believe it when she was
crowned.
   ``We were about as ecstatic as her family,'' Finch said. ``We've
watched Gretchen grow up and she's just been a marvelously talented
person. From the time she was a little girl, when she played the
violin, she just held people in awe.''
   Miss Carlson is the third Minnesota winner to be crowned Miss
America. Bebe Shopp was the winner in 1948 and Dorothy Benham won
in 1977.
   Peter Turok, executive vice president of the Anoka Area Chamber
of Commerce, said he participated in a training exercise organized
by Miss Carlson's father before the pageant in which people quizzed
her to prepare her for pageant interviews.
   ``I asked her what she would like to see on her resume 10 years
from now,'' Turok said. ``She said, `Well, being crowned Miss
America.'''
</TEXT>
