<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RapStabbings     09-12 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rap Stabbings,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seek Gang Members in Rap Concert Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man was stabbed to death and a
dozen other people were beaten or knifed at a rap-music concert in
this New York City suburb, say officials who are contemplating a
ban on such events.
   Knives and pistols were apparently smuggled inside Nassau
Veterans Memorial Coliseum before Saturday night's violence even
though the 10,000 people who attended ``Jam 88'' had to pass
through an electronic weapons check, police said.
   Investigators believe a gang of about a dozen people may have
been responsible for much of the violence, which apparently
occurred during chain snatchings and other robberies, Deputy Chief
Otto Geiger said Sunday.
   It was the latest in a series of violent incidents nationwide
connected with concerts of rap music, rhyming songs with a driving
beat and often-aggressive lyrics.
   Eight people were stabbed and at least five others were beaten
during the concert, which featured such top rap stars as Eric B.
and Rakim, Kool Moe Dee and Doug E. Fresh.
   Three of the stabbing victims were listed in critical but stable
condition early today at Nassau County Medical Center.
   Detective Sgt. John Nolan described the gang as organized.
   ``It looked like these men had a discipline, a leader and a
plan, and they carried it out with some precision,'' Nolan said.
The plan involved surrounding the mugging victim and stabbing him
so the thief could get away, Nolan said.
   The man who was slain, 19-year-old Julio Fuentes of New York
City, was stabbed once in the chest shortly after he entered the
colisuem.
   ``He was with his girlfriend,'' Geiger said. ``He resisted and
he was stabbed in his upper chest.''
   Ten of the wounded were taken to Hempstead General Hospital, but
only two were admitted, said acting hospital administrator Marilyn
Hurley said only two were admitted. Both were in fair condition
today, said a hospital spokeswoman who refused to give her name.
   Last month, two people were stabbed at a Run-DMC concert at the
colisuem. Geiger said the same gang may have been responsible.
   Police and coliseum officials will meet in the next few days to
determine what steps should be taken to prevent violence, he said.
   Those steps could include a ban on rap concerts, said colisuem
spokeswoman Hilary Hartung.
   Mineola is on Long Island about six miles east of New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland     09-12 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unionists: Talks Will Go Nowhere Without Legalization of
Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity advisors say round-table talks
with communist authorities may not get off the ground unless the
government shows it is willing in principle to reinstate the
independent labor movement.
   On Sunday, a group of intellectuals and artists met with
Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa to endorse his participation in the
talks.The roughly 60 advisors, calling themselves the Council on
Poland, also demanded the immediate legalization of Solidarity.
   The government promised the talks on jointly solving Poland's
economic and social crises in exchange for an end to a nearly
three-week strike wave and a mediator said Sunday that the
discussions could begin this week.
   A resolution adopted by the the advisors said: ``The most
important condition for the beginning of a true dialogue between
the civil opposition and the authorities (is) the legalization of
Solidarity and the immediate implementation of pluralism.''
   The labor unrest that began in mid-August and ended Sept. 3
posed the most serious threat to the government since it suppressed
Solidarity with a 1981 military crackdown. Authorities had promised
Walesa in talks Aug. 31 that they would discuss legalizing
Solidarity if he persuaded workers to end their occupation strikes.
   ``We are extending our full support in negotiations concerning
this issue to the founder of Solidarity,'' Sunday's resolution
said, referring to Walesa.
   No date has been set for the talks with authorities, but Andrzej
Stelmachowski, the law professor who has been acting as a mediator
in arranging the meetings, said they could begin this week.
   Union advisers said the talks might not get anywhere unless
there is evidence authorities are willing in principle to legalize
Solidarity.
   ``No round-table talks make sense unless at their first stage,
or even in the preparatory stage, the authorities' intentions are
made credible ... by some form of recognition of Solidarity's right
to function legally,'' Piotr Konopka, a Walesa aide, told reporters.
   Solidarity hopes for some signal on the government's willingness
to recognize Solidarity during a preparatory meeting to be held
with officials before the round-table talks, several Solidarity
advisers said.
   Sunday's session was part of a two-day Solidarity conference in
the northern port of Gdansk.
   About 100 people gathered after Sunday Mass in a room at St.
Brygida's Roman Catholic Church, which serves as the headquarters
of the Solidarity leadership.
   Walesa joined intellectuals, workers and regional Solidarity
leaders for the session, chaired by Bronislaw Geremek, a historian
and one of Walesa's closest advisers. Included in the group of
writers, actors and scholars were filmmaker Andrzej Wajda, Catholic
newspaper editor Jerzy Turowicz and former head of the journalists'
union, Stefan Bratkowski.
   A spokesman for the group, author Edmund Osmanczyk, told
reporters during a break in the discussions: ``By means of
recognizing pluralism we might finally become a normal state, where
a majority of citizens control the ruling minority, like elsewhere
in the world.''
   At the Mass earlier, the Rev. Henryk Jankowski spoke to a
congregation of 5,000 Solidarity supporters, stressing the need for
unity in Polish society as the talks begin.
   ``Today there is a chance for round-table (talks) and we cannot
waste it,'' he said in his sermon. ``Just the opposite, we have to
break down all the barriers, cast in solid concrete, to get there
and sit at that table.''
   Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Solidarity activist from Warsaw who
monitors human rights abuses in Poland for the union, said before
Sunday's meeting that the mood was optimistic. He said Solidarity
was more active and better organized than it has been in years.
   The union federation was banned the year after martial law was
imposed in 1981.
</TEXT>
