<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     09-12 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floodwaters Drop, But Disease Climbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Problems of distributing relief
materials to millions of stricken people and combating the rapid
spread of disease plagued this flooded nation today despite steady
declines in river levels.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad told a news conference his
government has been trying to reach an estimated 30 million to 40
million people who were either marooned by the floods or in need of
food and medical assistance.
   The flooding that started June 13 has claimed 866 lives,
according to the government. Daily reports by Dhaka newspapers put
the death toll at 1,647.
   The number of known diarrhea cases in the country continued to
rise, with the government's Health Control Center reporting more
than 211,000 cases nationwide. However, the pro-government
newspaper Bangladesh Times today quoted relief officials as saying
the number exceeded 300,000.
   Ershad said 130 people were known to have died of diarrhea. He
said he was unaware of any cholera cases, but doctors and
newspapers said cholera has been diagnosed in patients who drank
flood-contaminated water.
   About 5 percent of the patients admitted to the International
Center for Diarrheal Disease Research in Dhaka had contracted
cholera, according to a doctor who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   When asked about cholera at his news conference, Ershad said,
``I have no reports of cholera, but I will check up.''
   Both illnesses have similar symptoms, but cholera is more
serious and verified through laboratory tests.
   The doctor said 550 people suffering from diarrhea or cholera
had been admitted to the diarrhea center since Sunday. Last month,
the center averaged 155 patients a day. He said the current
percentage of cholera cases was normal, even during non-flood
periods.
   ``Cholera is endemic in Bangladesh,'' he said.
   Asked about the possibility of illness escalating as the flood
waters receded, Ershad said: ``The fear of having an epidemic is
already there.''
   He noted that his country has only 8,000 doctors. In a country
with a population of 110 million, that is a ratio of 13,750 per
doctor, compared with one doctor per 5,000 in India and one per 780
in the United States.
   Ershad said estimates indicate 3.5 million tons of grain have
been destroyed by the floods _ 20 percent of the grain needed to
feed the country this year.
   Ershad said foreign pledges for flood relief have reached about
$280 million. He said the rebuilding of roads washed away by the
floods would require at least that amount.
   About half the aid offered so far has come from the United
States, which has pledged nearly $150 million in wheat, wheat seeds
and cash for emergency airlift assistance as well as contributions
to international agencies such as Save the Children, CARE and World
Vision Relief and Development.
   An American C5-A Galaxy trasnport plane arrived in Dhaka today,
carrying water tanks and purification units and plastic sheeting to
be used for temporary shelters.
   The floodwaters have covered three-fourths of Bangladesh,
according to Ershad.
   ``For centuries the people of Bangladesh have lived with floods,
but never before have the rivers unleased such fury on her
people,'' the president said.
   The Flood Control Center said today that all major rivers were
falling but remain above flood level.
   The Brahmaputra dropped 8 inches at some stations since Sunday.
The smaller Buriganga, which has flooded about half of Dhaka,
dropped 2 inches during the same period.
   ``The flood situation in the country is steadily improving,''
said one control center official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   On Sunday, Ershad called for water experts from India, China,
Nepal and Bangladesh to meet to discuss flood-control in the
region, which is hit by annual monsoons from June through September.
   Ershad told a gathering in the northern township of Grudaspur
that Bangladesh did not have the expertise nor resources to tackle
the problem alone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
