<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha     09-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Botha,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Embarks on Historic Trip Into Black Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha embarked
today on his first summit-level mission into black Africa, flying
to Marxist-ruled Mozambique for talks with a government that has
blamed its woes on South Africa.
   After meeting with President Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique near
a South African-assisted hydroelectric project, Botha was to
continue on to Malawi for talks Tuesday with President Hastings
Kamuzu Banda. Malawi is the only African state maintaining full
diplomatic ties with white-ruled South Africa.
   Botha and Chissano were expected to discuss a mutual
non-aggression treaty signed between the two countries in 1984.
   The treaty lapsed in 1985 when Mozambique produced evidence that
South Africa violated it by continuing to assist the Mozambique
National Resistance rebel movement, which began an insurgency two
years after independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The war, combined with drought, has left millions of Mozambicans
homeless and short of food.
   Many Western governments, including the United States, have
increased aid to Mozambique and endorse its contention that the
rebels receive covert logistical and communications aid from South
Africa.
   South Africa insists it no longer aids the rebels, and Botha is
expected to try to convince Chissano to mute the allegations.
   Botha, whose plane departed from an air force base at Pretoria,
was accompanied by his defense minister, Gen. Magnus Malan, and
Foreign Minister Pik Botha. Chissano's delegation, which left
Maputo for the northwestern town of Songo early today, included
three Cabinet ministers and two military commanders, according to
the Mozambican news agency AIM.
   In the past year, as part of an effort to improve its regional
image, South Africa has expanded its trade mission in Maputo and
pursued economic development possibilities in Mozambique.
   The two countries also have signed an agreement aimed at
rehabilitating Cahora Basso, the giant hydroelectric project in the
northern, war-torn province of Tete, so that South Africa can
purchase electricity.
   The rebels repeatedly have sabotaged power lines leading from
Cahora Basso to South Africa.
   Even when their relations were badly strained, Mozambique and
South Africa maintained extensive ties. Tens of thousands of
Mozambicans work as miners and migrant laborers in South Africa,
and Maputo's electricity is supplied by South Africa.
   Botha, during his 10 years in power, has had few chances to
travel in black Africa. In 1986, he was one of numerous dignitaries
who attended the coronation of Swaziland's King Mswati III, and in
1987 he made a secret visit to South African troops fighting in
Angola.
   He had hoped to visit Brazzaville, Congo, earlier this year in
conjunction with peace talks on Angola and South-West Africa, or
Namibia, but Angola's Cuban allies reportedly threatened to scuttle
the talks if he went.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
