<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru a0498 09-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Down Sharply</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To reflect early closig of Zurich market, SUBS third-to-last
graf, `In Zurich ... later Friday.' Picks up penultimate graf,
`Earlier, in ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar opened higher in Europe today, but fell
against many major foreign currencies following reports the West
German central bank intervened and sold dollars, dealers said.
   Gold prices fell as much as $11.
   Traders in Rome said they were surprised by the Deutsche
Bundesbank's intervention, as the dollar had been trading steadily
in a narrow range for most of the morning.
   Traders had said they expected the dollar to remain steady until
American trade figures for July are released in Washington on
Wednesday.
   Those figures are expected to show a trade deficit of between
$10 billion and $13.5 billion, they said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar edged up 0.47 yen to close at 133.42 after Japanese
trade figures for August were released. Dealers said the trade
surplus of $4.9 billion was lower than many expected.
   Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 133.60 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8470 West German marks, down from 1.8490
   _1.5605 Swiss francs, down from 1.5620
   _6.2785 French francs, down from 6.2865
   _2.0900 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0835
   _1,381.00 Italian lire, up from 1,379.50
   _1.2388 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6955, little changed from
$1.6980 late Friday.
   Gold prices fell sharply in Europe after oil prices fell again.
   The precious metal opened in London at a bid price of $421.80 a
troy ounce, down $5 from the $426.80 bid late Friday. At midmorning
Monday, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended
price of $418.
   In Zurich, gold was quoted at $418.00 when the market closed at
6 a.m. EDT for a local holiday, down more than $11 from the $429.50
bid late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.60 to close at a bid $419.18.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.39 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.63.
</TEXT>
