<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0744EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarcosParty     09-12 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos Party,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferdinand Marcos Celebrates 71st Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
promised supporters at his 71st birthday party that he would return
to his homeland without resorting to violence.
   ``It is my habit every birthday to ask, `Who am I? What have I
done to be remembered in history?''' the exiled Marcos told about
3,500 supporters at a celebration here Sunday. ``Today I am faced
with the greatest crisis that has confronted me. God knows who I
am. But how will the people know?'
   ``Am I a scoundrel? A thief of ill-gotten wealth? I am no
scoundrel,'' Marcos said, adding that the Philippine government
should allow him to face accusations in person.
   ``I will go back, I intend to go back, at any price, without
violence,'' Marcos said. ``I say face me now, or face the verdict
of history.''
   Several criminal and civil lawsuits filed by Marcos' opponents
in the Philippines and the United States accuse the ousted leader
of plundering billions of dollars from his country during his
20-year rule. Marcos has filed a petition to return to the
Philippines, but President Corazon Aquino has denied his request.
   Thousands of supporters, many wearing T-shirts or waving
placards bearing Marcos' likeness, yelled ``Bring Home Marcos'' and
``Mabuhay Marcos,'' which in the Philippine language Tagalog wishes
a long life.
   Imelda Marcos, dressed in a long, turquoise-colored gown and
several pieces of gold and diamond jewelry, addressed the crowd in
Tagalog but switched to English to say ``the only hidden wealth of
Marcos is in his heart and his mind _ enrichment and
enlightenment.''
   The event _ which was part birthday party, part floor show and
part political rally _ was sponsored by the local group ``Friends
of Marcos.''
   Marcos, who has lived in exile here since February 1986, was
greeted by cheers and choruses of ``Happy Birthday'' when he and
his wife arrived through a back entrance at the Blaisdell Center
Arena.
</TEXT>
