<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0751EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RajneeshReunion     09-12 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rajneesh Reunion,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disciples Say Goodbye to Rancho Rajneesh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAJNEESHPURAM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 disciples of Indian guru
Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh spent the weekend taking a final look at the
isolated central Oregon ranch that served as the sect's showplace.
   Rancho Rajneesh, 64,000 acres of sagebrush-dotted hills on the
high desert, will be sold at auction next month. It had been for
sale for $28 million, but fell under foreclosure proceedings by
Connecticut General Life Insurance Co.
   ``It's such a beautiful place, such a peaceful place and this
planet has no use for it,'' said Swami Prem Niren, the American
lawyer who serves as Rajneesh's ``ambassador to the United States.''
   ``Nobody wants to put the resources into even using it for what
it's already been built for ... a great big meditation center.''
   The commune, incorporated as Rajneeshpuram on part of the ranch,
was home to thousands of red-clad disciples from 1981 to 1985. They
toiled 12-hour days and showered Rajneesh with jewels and Rolls
Royces that he used for daily drives past lines of singing,
clapping followers.
   The commune disbanded in 1985 after the guru pleaded guilty to
federal immigration charges. Under a plea agreement, he received a
suspended 10-year sentence, paid a $400,000 fine and agreed not to
return to the United States for five years without the written
permission of the U.S. attorney general.
   Rajneesh, 56, returned to Pune, India, where he carries on his
meditation teachings as the self-described ``guru of the rich.''
   The ``family reunion and picnic'' drew about 150 West Coast
disciples who endured the perilous gravel road into the ranch to
tour the abandoned buildings and reminisce about the commune's
heyday.
   The reunion ``happened by itself,'' Niren said. ``Some people
wanted to come here and be here while it's still possible.''
   The gathering was closed to the public except for a news
conference Sunday at which Niren reiterated accusations that the
U.S. government destroyed the commune and poisoned Rajneesh after
he was arrested. Niren acknowledged, however, that he had no
evidence of such a crime.
   The news conference followed an emotional singing and meditation
session outside the house where the guru lived.
   Tears streamed down the faces of several disciples as Niren
recalled the turbulence that marked the commune's downfall.
   He criticized the reign of Ma Anand Sheela, Rajneesh's personal
secretary who is in federal prison.
   ``She's just another power-hungry politician,'' Niren said.
   Among those on hand for the news conference was Wasco County
Judge William Hulse, who said he came to the reunion when offered a
ride by the county sheriff. Sheela was convicted of assault for
handing Hulse a glass of poisoned water.
   ``I didn't want the people out here to think I was going to rub
it in,'' Hulse said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
