<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope-Africa     09-12 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Africa,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Makes Appeal for Peace In Violence-Wracked Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II traveled today to
the violence-wracked provincial capital of Matabeleland and
preached reconciliation and peace.
   ``It is only eight years since your struggle for national
independence (in Zimbabwe) was brought to an end,'' the Roman
Catholic pontiff said. ``Even after that, many people in
Matabeleland did not find true peace. ... The civilian population
continued to suffer from guerrilla warfare and other forms of
violence.''
   The pope celebrated Mass at Ascot Race Course on an altar
festooned with white Madonna lilies. Many in the crowd of 50,000
waited at the race track six hours for the Mass.
   The pope began the Mass speaking in Sindebele, the tribal
language of the Ndebele of Matabeleland.
   John Paul flew from Harare, the capital, to Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's
second largest city and provincial capital of Matabeleland, early
today. He was welcomed by Joshua Nkomo, a senior minister in the
government and the province's political chief.
   The pope's one-day visit to this western province is the most
sensitive part of his three-day trip to Zimbabwe, which began
Saturday. The pope is to travel on to the black-governed countries
of Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland and Mozambique during his 10-day
tour of southern Africa.
   Before the Mass, John Paul was welcomed by Bishop Henry Karlen.
   In 1984, the Swiss-born Karlen and President Robert Mugabe
clashed after Karlen accused government troops of atrocities
involving hundreds of civilians in Matabeleland.
   Mugabe denied the allegations and accused the bishop of siding
with rebels.
   ``The people of Matabeleland have suffered much during the
liberation war,'' Karlen said in his welcoming speech. ``The blood
of 10 missionary martyrs of the diocese of Bulawayo has flowed into
the soil of this area. May this blood bear abundant fruit.''
   Until recently, Matabeleland was the center of a tribal-based
insurgency that began shortly after Zimbabwe gained independence in
April 1980. Hundreds of people were killed in the conflict between
the rebels and government troops, among them the 10 Catholic
missionaries.
   Suspected rebels shot and killed Killian Knoerl of the
Matabeleland diocese on April 19, hours after the government
announced a general amnesty for rebels. The government said 113
rebels surrendered under the amnesty and that there have been no
rebel-related killings since.
   The amnesty came four months after Mugabe and Nkomo, formerly
his chief political rival, signed a unity accord.
   Mugabe and Nkomo led rival guerrilla armies during the
seven-year war that led to white-ruled Rhodesia becoming
black-ruled Zimbabwe.
   Mugabe, a member of the Shona tribe that accounts for 70 percent
of Zimbabwe's 8.5 million people, accused Nkomo of controlling the
rebels in Matabeleland, Nkomo's Ndebele tribal stronghold. Nkomo
denied the charge.
   The Ndebele make up about one-quarter of Zimbabwe's population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
