<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BlackBart     09-12 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Bart,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town That Sent Black Bart to Prison Honors Outlaw</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in poem in 13th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANDREAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proving that time heals all wounds, a
lawman presided when this Gold Rush town paid tribute to Black
Bart, the Old West stagecoach robber famed for his calling card
poems.
   About 2,500 people turned out during the weekend for a parade,
barbecue and dance to celebrate the release of the ``Gentleman
Bandit'' from San Quentin Prison 100 years ago.
   Bill Claudino, a California Highway Patrol officer, was the
parade chairman.
   ``Some people might think it is a little odd to pay so much
attention to a stagecoach robber, but Black Bart really was quite a
dapper thief,'' Claudino said.
   Black Bart was the alias of Charles E. Bolles, who robbed 28
stages between 1875 to 1883 before he was caught and served five
years in prison.
   He was released on Jan. 21, 1888 but because January's weather
is foul here, the celebration was postponed until Saturday.
   San Andreas, the seat of Calaveras County, laid claim to the end
of the Black Bart legend because it sent him to San Quentin.
   A handkerchief and two shirt cuffs dropped during a stage holdup
at nearby Copperopolis was traced by laundry mark to Boles who
lived in San Francisco. When captured, he was wearing a derby,
diamond jewelry, a gold watch and twirling a cane.
   Black Bart became known for the poems he left behind at
robberies, all signed in the same manner. The first of several was
scribbled on the back of a freight waybill:
   ``I've labored long and hard for bread
   ``For honor and for riches
   ``But on my corns too long you've tread
   ``You fine-haired sons of bitches.''
   Below was the signature: ``Black Bart the PO8.''
   Bolles was never reported seen again after he left prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
