<DOCNO> AP880912-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Eastern     09-12 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another 4,000 Jobs Go; Union Leaders Vow To Keep Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines officials say the elimination of
4,000 workers was the only way to end mounting losses, but union
leaders warned that the latest round of firings dooms the company's
ability to compete.
   Dozens punched their time cards for the last time here this
weekend as part of a cutback that eliminates Eastern service to 14
cities and drops the carrier's workforce to 30,000.
   Less than four years ago, Eastern had 42,000 workers.
   ``We're back on death watch again,'' said Katherine Ferer, a
vice chair of the Transport Workers Union representing flight
attendants.
   Eastern officials acknowledge the cuts are painful, but said
something had to be done.
   ``The fact is we have lost over a billion dollars in this
decade,'' said Robin Matell, the company's chief spokesman. ``We
have to take prudent, although admittedly painful, measures.''
   Union leaders say laying off employees will drive up labor costs
per flight because the less-senior workers being laid off were paid
less than those who remain.
   ``The last thing you want to do in the airline industry is
downsize,'' said Charles E. Bryan, president of District 100 of the
Machinists, Eastern's largest union with nearly 12,000 workers.
``Many of the costs are fixed, and the break-even yield goes way
up. It's a lose-lose proposition that just feeds on itself.
   Of the 4,000 jobs eliminated, 1,500 were non-union positions,
including management and clerical. Some 500 pilots positions are
being eliminated without layoffs by having pilots clear backlogs of
vacation time, and some 400 flight attendants are taking
one-to-six-month leaves of absence, the company said.
   A few hundred more flight attendants, mechanics, baggage
handlers and ramp agents are taking early retirement or simply
quit, Eastern said.
   Eastern is $2.5 billion in debt and its cash reserves dwindled
from $560 million to $420 million in the quarter ending June 30.
   President Phil Bakes said Eastern was cutting out money-losing
Western routes and its Kansas City hub, along with some sluggish
Caribbean routes. The company estimates the new cuts will save $100
million a year.
   The Houston-based Texas Air Corp., chaired by Frank Lorenzo,
took over Eastern two years ago.
   Eastern's unions will make arguments against the layoffs later
this month in the District Court of Appeals in Washington, which
allowed Eastern to go ahead with the layoffs after it posted a $4.7
million bond to pay back salaries if workers are later ordered
reinstated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
