<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Comedie Francaise,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Director Named For Comedie Francaise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Culture Jack Lang today named Monique
Barbaroux as the new director general of the Comedie Francaise, the
prestigious national theater founded in 1690 under Louis XIV.
   Mrs. Barbaroux will direct both the main theater, located
between the Palais Royale and the Louvre, and the Odeon on the Left
Bank.
   The new director general formerly was in charge of music and
theater administration in the Ministry of Culture.
   The repertoire of the Comedie Francaise traditionally has
performed the French classics, with strictly defined
interpretations of works by playwrights such as Racine,
Beaumarchais and Moliere, who founded the company in the 17th
century.
   The company has in recent years ventured into foreign and 20th
century authors such as Pirandello, Claudel and Anouilh.
</TEXT>
