<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Malek-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0449 09-12 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malek-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Malek Devoid of Bigotry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with Bush comment on Malek; picks up pvs 2nd
graf bgng, Malek, who.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said today that Frederic V. Malek
was ``without one ounce of bigotry or prejudice'' even though he
resigned from the Republican National Committee because of a report
that he tallied the number of Jews in a federal agency for
President Nixon in the early 1970s.
   Reporters shouted questions about Malek's departure as the vice
president embarked on a five-state tour including major industrial
centers. He said he stood by a statement he issued Sunday, and
expressed similar sentiments in a conversation with Malek.
   ``I know this man, and I know him to be without one ounce of
bigotry or prejudice in his makeup,'' Bush said.
   Malek, who had been deputy chairman of the Republican National
Committee since Aug. 19, had admitted compiling the data in 1971
but denied Sunday he had any part in the demotion of government
employees because of their religious affiliation. He said he
resigned in order to keep the campaign focused on the issues.
   In a separate statement, Bush said: ``I respect Fred Malek's
decision. I know him to be a most honorable man without a trace of
bigotry in his makeup ... I condemn any vestiges of anti-Semitism,
prejudice or bigotry and so, I believe, does Fred Malek.''
   The Washington Post story and the resignation follow a report
last week that members of an ethnic coalition for Bush were
associated with anti-Semitic and fascistic activities.
   A co-chairman, Jerome Brentar, resigned after disclosures he was
active in the defense of John Demjanjuk, a former Ohio autoworker
convicted in Israel of being a Nazi death camp guard. The
Washington Jewish Week also reported that Brentar denied the
existence of the Holocaust.
   ``The moral clock is ticking for the Bush campaign,'' Rep.
Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., said Sunday, noting that Jews around
the country were preparing to celebrate Rosh Hashana, the Jewish
New Year.
   ``How can we trust George Bush to be a friend of Israel?'' he
asked.
   Malek, a Harvard business school graduate known for his
management abilities, was chosen by Bush late in April to run the
Republican National Convention.
   Before the convention, Bush announced that he would place Malek
in the RNC position. At the same time, Bush spurned Chairman Frank
Fahrenkopf's offer to resign. The move, however, gave Bush greater
control of the party.
   ``I think Malek going up there will maximize coordination
between the campaign and the important functions of the RNC,'' Bush
said at the time.
   The committee voted in Malek the day after the convention in New
Orleans.
   The Post reported Sunday that former President Nixon had ordered
Malek in 1971 to investigate what was described in notes as a
``Jewish cabal'' at the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   At the time, Malek was Nixon's White House personnel chief and
had been assigned to evaluate the BLS staff because Nixon thought
the bureau was interpreting unemployment data in an unfavorable
light.
   On July 27, 1971, Malek reported to H.R. Haldeman, Nixon's chief
of staff, that 13 of 35 top BLS officials were Jewish. Post
reporters found the memo last week in the archives of Nixon's
presidency.
   Less than two months after Malek's memo to Haldeman, two senior
officials who were Jewish were moved to less visible positions in
the Labor Department. They were Peter Henle, then chief economist
for BLS, and Harold Goldstein, then director of current employment
analysis.
   In his statement Sunday, Malek said, referring to the demotion
of anyone for religious reasons, ``I find that kind of action _ or
even the suggestion that I engaged peripherally in that kind of
effort _ to be morally wrong and totally out of bounds.''
   Malek, who worked as a senior executive for the Marriott Corp.,
came to Washington with the Nixon administration.
   While with the administration in 1972, Malek oversaw a program
of redirecting federal grants to benefit Nixon's re-election
efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
