<1ST_LINE>r i PM-USNavy-Cannibalism     09-12 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Navy-Cannibalism,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Navy Officer May Be Court-Martialed In Cannibalism Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military court began hearings
today to determine whether a Navy captain should be court-martialed
for failing to rescue Vietnamese refugees who said they ate human
flesh to survive at sea.
   Capt. Alexander G. Balian was relieved as skipper of the USS
Dubuque last month Vietnamese refugees said they resorted to murder
and cannibalism after the Navy ship refused to take them aboard in
the South China Sea in June.
   The Vietnamese eventually were rescued by fishermen and are in a
refugee camp on the Philippine island of Palawan.
   Today's proceedings at Subic Bay Naval Base were a preliminary
session and were adjourned for two weeks to allow Balian to prepare
his defense, according to Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Kevin Mukri.
   The hearing, which is the first step leading to a possible
court-martial, was conducted by Cmdr J. E. Halvorson, a circuit
military judge, Mukri said. He gave no other details.
   Balian faces charges of ``wrongfully failing to render
appropriate assistance'' to the refugees and of dereliction of duty
by not properly investigating the refugees' condition.
   Navy officials decided to begin proceedings against Balian, 48,
after he refused to appear at an admiral's mast, a closed-door
session during which an admiral serves as the only judge, sources
in Washington said.
   The Dubuque, an amphibious landing ship, was sailing toward the
Persian Gulf on June 9 when it encountered a boat filled with
Vietnamese refugees in the South China Sea. The Navy said the
Dubuque gave the refugees several hundred pounds of food and water
and navigational aids, but did not take them aboard because Balian
judged their boat to be seaworthy.
   The refugees told Philippine and United Nations officials that
after encountering the American ship, they drifted for weeks and
many of them starved.
   Philippine and U.S. officials quoted the survivors as saying
they killed and ate three of their companions after being turned
away by the Dubuque. They said they also ate two other companions
who had starved.
   Only 52 of the 109 Vietnamese survived the 37-day crossing. They
said they encountered the Dubuque 19 days after they left Vietnam.
</TEXT>
