<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-NationalSecurity     09-12 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-National Security,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Names National Security Panel, Attacks Dukakis on Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today named a
bipartisan, 13-member campaign panel to advise him on national
security issues, and both immediately accused Democrat Michael
Dukakis of lacking the capacity to handle world crises.
   One panelist, Zbigniew Brzezinski, former national security
adviser to Democratic President Carter, said that of the two
current presidential candidates, ``George Bush is the one who can
best fashion an effective, bipartisan foreign policy.''
   Bush said Dukakis would question the Reagan administration's
direct initiatives in Grenada, the Persian Gulf or Libya and rely
instead on the United Nations or other international organizations.
   ``We cannot abdicate our responsibility for leadership,'' Bush
said.
   Brent Scowcroft, who was President Ford's national security
adviser, said the Democratic nominee ``has demonstrated neither the
capacity nor the instincts'' to handle world crises.
   Bush said the 13 panelists will provide him with ``sound advice
and counsel'' in his campaign for the White House. He noted they
were both Democrats and Republicans but said that on defense
matters, ``they are neither Republicans nor Democrats _ they are
Americans.''
   Besides Brzezinski and Scowcroft, the panelists include Henry A.
Kissinger and Alexander Haig, former secretaries of state; former
ambassador Anne Armstrong; former White House chief of staff Howard
Baker; Melvin Laird and Donald Rumsfeld, former secretaries of
defense; Sens. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., and
Richard Lugar, R-Ind.; former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, and retired
Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., former chief of naval operations.
   Former U.N. ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick, who has endorsed the
Republican ticket, did not accept an invitation to join the panel
because of a potential conflict with her job as a syndicated
newspaper columnist, Bush spokeswoman Alixe Glen said.
</TEXT>
