<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites Sub a0479 09-12 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, Sub, a0479,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd item, dateline NEW YORK, to CORRECT to Dallara, sted
Dalara, in last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burglary suspect tried a rooftop escape, but
fell into a chimney and was stuck there for three hours before
being rescued by police.
   Wayne Mitchell, 20, was not seriously hurt in his 30-foot fall
down the narrow shaft, police said.
   He and five other people allegedly broke into a leather goods
store in the Bronx on Sunday morning, but while the other five were
caught near the store, Mitchell took off across a roof, followed by
two police officers.
   He fell down the chimney of a three-story building adjoining a
one-story doughnut shop on the corner.
   Officers from the Emergency Service Unit first tried to pull him
up with a rope. Then they knocked a hole in the rear wall of the
doughnut shop, but couldn't reach him.
   Finally, they went to an adjacent grocery store, where the
chimney shaft ended above a water heater.
   Emergency Service Officer John Dallara used a jackhammer to chop
a hole in a concrete wall. Mitchell was then pulled through the
hole.
   ``Thank you, thank you,'' he said as police extricated him.
   ``You're welcome,'' Dallara replied, ``and you're under arrest.''
</TEXT>
