<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MexicanIndependence     09-12 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexican Independence,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100,000 Cheer Mexican Independence At L.A. Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 people cheered a parade of
beauty queens, movie stars and floats through seven miles of city
streets to mark Mexico's struggle for independence from Spain.
   ``This holiday is to Mexicans what the Fourth of July is to
Americans,'' Juan Arellano, who moved to California more than 50
years ago, said Sunday.
   ``Grito de Dolores'' marks Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla's
impassioned speech in 1810 urging his peasant congregation in the
city of Dolores to take up arms against Spanish monarchs who had
ruled Mexico for more than three centuries.
   By 1821, the Mexicans had won their independence.
   Sal Lopez, 74, whose parents immigrated from Mexico in 1921, has
organized the parade for the past 25 years and has attended twice
as many.
   ``When the parade was first organized, it was nothing but a
bunch of brewing companies that put a couple of Mexican flags on
their trucks and drove down First Street, but as the Mexican
population here increases, the parade gets bigger and bigger,'' he
said.
   Authorities estimated 100,000 people turned out in the
predominately Hispanic community of East Los Angeles.
   The parade featured Indian dancers in glistening silver and gold
robes with anklets of dried nuts that could be heard rattling above
the sound of the trumpets and guitars of mariachis.
   Men thrust their fists in the air and shouted ``Viva la
Independencia'' as military bands marched by and fans swooned over
the singing group Menudo and such Mexican movie stars as Parade
Grand Marshal Richard Iniquez.
   Mexican beauty queens smiled at the crowd from colorful, 30-foot
floats.
   About 30 protesters shouted as Romeo Flores, Mexico's consul in
Los Angeles, passed, demanding the appointment of Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas as president of Mexico. Cardenas, the National Democratic
Front candidate, recently was defeated by Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, who protesters said cheated his way into office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-US     09-12 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-US,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Destroyer Rescues Fishermen, Vincennes Leaves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. destroyer rescued three
shipwrecked fishermen and was searching for a fourth after their
two small craft foundered in rough seas in the Gulf of Oman,
American naval sources said today.
   A Navy official said the destroyer John Hancock had just
finished escorting two U.S.-chartered cargo vessels out of the
Persian Gulf when its patrol helicopter spotted the fishermen
clinging to pieces of wreckage.
   The fishermen were two Pakistanis and a United Arab Emirates
citizen, all from the Emirates port of Fujairah.
   The three men were quoted as saying one of their craft was
swamped in the heavy seas and the second sank after trying to come
to its rescue.
   The missing man was another Emirates citizen, said the Navy
official, who asked not to be identified.
   The 7,800-ton John Hancock, based at Mayport, Fla., is one of
five U.S. warships scheduled to leave the gulf within the next two
weeks. All will be replaced by ships now on their way to the gulf.
   It was the second reported rescue of fishermen by a U.S. warship
in the past month. In August, the missile cruiser Vincennes picked
up eight Iranians who had been adrift for eight days in the Gulf of
Oman. They later were repatriated.
   The Vincennes, which on July 3 mistakenly shot down an Iranian
jetliner, killing all 290 aboard, left the gulf region Sunday for
its home port of San Diego, Calif., a week after it was originally
scheduled to leave, U.S. officials said.
   The departure of the Vincennes represents the first U.S. force
reduction in the gulf _ from 27 to 26 warships _ since the
Iran-Iraq cease-fire took effect Aug. 20. U.S. Navy sources
confirmed that there were no plans to replace the 9,600-ton Aegis
cruiser.
   Navy sources, who demanded anonymity, said the Vincennes was
ordered to delay its departure after an Arab gulf country objected
to the Vincennes being pulled out while the Iran-Iraq cease-fire
talks in Geneva remained stalled.
   The sources declined to identify the Arab government or say why
the Vincennes was leaving now. The Geneva talks have continued to
show no significant progress.
   U.S. officials in Washington said the Vincennes was being
withdrawn because its long-range radar and weapons capability ``is
no longer needed there.''
   As the latest U.S. Navy-escorted tanker convoy reached Kuwait
overnight, that country's top tanker official said the cease-fire
in the 8-year-old war does not mean an end to its reliance on U.S.
and other foreign flags to protect its ships.
   ``Kuwaiti tankers will continue to sail under U.S., Soviet and
British flags. The reflagging is a purely economic policy and has
nothing to do with the war,'' Abdel-Fattah Al-Bader, chairman of
the state-run Kuwait Oil Tanker Co., was quoted as saying in an
interview with the newspaper Al-Watan.
   The United States, Britain and the Soviet Union have all
reflagged vessels and protected Kuwaiti shipping from Iranian
attack in the gulf during the past year.
   One of the 11 U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers, the 46,723-ton
carrier Gas Princess, arrived in Kuwait overnight, escorted by the
U.S. missile frigate Nicholas. It was the 63rd such convoy this
year and the 85th since the reflagging began in July 1987.
</TEXT>
