<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WakeShootings     09-12 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wake Shootings,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Albanian-Americans Fatally Shot At Wake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMTRAMCK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gun battle at a wake left two men dead
and three others wounded, authorities said.
   ``Both may have been shot by each other, although the
possibility of another gunman does exist,'' police said in a
statement. No other suspects had been identified or arrested.
   Authorities are investigating the possibility that the men, both
Albanian-Americans, were killed by two or three suspects, police
Sgt. David Misak said.
   Fran Gojcha, 52, of Sterling Heights and Fran Nicha, 27, of
Detroit were pronounced dead at Detroit Receiving Hospital after
the shootings Sunday outside the Polish National Alliance Hall in
the Detroit enclave, police said.
   Two other men attending the wake were treated at North Detroit
General Hospital and released. A woman walking near the hall was
hit by a stray bullet and was reported in serious condition at
Henry Ford Hospital.
   The victims were attending a wake for Mark Dedvukaj, 65, of
Hamtramck, who died two weeks ago in Yugoslavia and was buried
there.
   Gjeka Gjelaj, 40, who also was at the wake, said one of the
shooting victims were ``dishonored'' by the other six months ago.
Gjelaj said one man had carried the Albanian flag in a wedding
after the other had been chosen earlier.
   The man whom Gjelaj said had been dishonored confronted the flag
bearer at the wake and said, ``The time has come to pay what you
owe.''
   Both left the hall, drew guns and began shooting, Gjelaj said.
Investigators have not recovered the weapons, although 15 to 20
shell casings were found at the scene.
</TEXT>
