<1ST_LINE>r a PM-C&NWStrike     09-12 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-C&NW Strike,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Normal Rush Hour Service For C&NW Commuters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago & North Western commuters, who endured
hours of delays in their last ride with the railway, enjoyed a much
smoother commute today, a railroad spokesman said.
   This morning's commute went ``perfectly,'' said Chris Knapton, a
spokesman for Metra, the Chicago-area commuter rail agency that
buys service from C&NW.
   ``All the trains are running on time,'' Knapton said.
   Friday's evening rush hour was disrupted by a one-day strike of
the 2,600 members of the United Transportation Union. The strike
was ended Friday night by a congressionally imposed settlement, but
President Reagan signed the bill too late to allow usual train
service to resume.
   The C&NW serves about 41,000 commuters in suburban Chicago and
has freight operations in 10 states.
   Railroad officials were forced to scramble to put together train
crews because about half the C&NW conductors failed to report for
work once Reagan signed the bill.
   ``We told all our members to go back to work when the president
signed the emergency board recommendations'' approved by the House
and Senate, said Robert Reppe Jr., president of UTU Local 577,
which represents 382 Chicago-area brakemen and conductors.
   Trains began running on schedule Saturday as union members went
back to their jobs, officials said.
</TEXT>
