<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Sextuplets     09-12 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sextuplets,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Day Of School For Britain's Sextuplets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALLASEY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's only surviving girl
sextuplets started school on Monday and were paired off into three
different classrooms.
   Hannah, Jenny, Kate, Ruth, Lucy and Sarah Walton, who celebrate
their fifth birthday on Nov. 18, were led by their parents into St.
George's Primary School in Wallasey near Liverpool, northwest
England.
   The school, with 712 students, is the largest in the area and
was chosen because it allowed the girls to be split up, their
parents said.
   ``I think they will really enjoy it,'' said their father, Graham
Walton, ``They mix very well with other children and they are
excited about it.''
   Headmaster Bruce Harry said the girls were divided into three
groups because ``if they had all gone into one ... class the
teacher would have found difficulty balancing the time she gave
them and the other children.''
   The girls resemble one another but are not identical.
</TEXT>
