<HEAD>Two Die After Being Shot With Taser Stun Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men, one of them naked, died in separate
incidents after being shot with stun guns during struggles with
police, authorities said Monday.
   Autopsies were scheduled, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Deputy
Gabe Ramirez said.
   An unidentified man about 38 years old was shot with a Taser
dart after a struggle with Bell-Cudahy police Sunday, Ramirez said.
   The unidentified man, believed to be under the influence of
drugs, became violent and began fighting with officers.
   ``During the altercation, a Taser was used to subdue him,''
Ramirez said. The man was pronounced dead at St. Francis Medical
Center in Lynwood.
   In the other incident, Charles Eugene Miles, 37, was found
standing nude Sunday at an intersection in Paramount, 12 miles
south of downtown Los Angeles.
   ``When the sheriff's department stopped to investigate, he
became combative and a violent struggle began,'' Ramirez said.
   A Taser was unsuccessful in controlling Miles, who also was
believed to be under the influence of drugs, officials said.
   ``When it failed to bring him under control, he was finally
physically subdued,'' Ramirez said.
   Miles, of Bellflower, was taken to the jail ward of Los Angeles
County-USC Medical Center, where he died.
   Information on how many times each victim was shot with the
Tasers and the identities of the officers involved was not released.
   Tasers are described by police as non-lethal guns that fire
darts which deliver a brief, 50,000 volt, low-amperage charge that
temporarily paralyzes the nervous system.
</TEXT>
