<HEAD>Former Mayor Out of Prison, On the Air</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Mike Roark, who resigned
last year after pleading guilty to federal drug possession charges,
will become a commentator for West Virginia Public Radio, officials
said Monday.
   Roark, a Republican, will go on the air once or twice a month to
provide a conservative viewpoint on current events, said public
radio spokeswoman Beth Vorhees. His first segment will run in the
next few weeks, she said.
   Commentators decide for themselves what they will discuss and
receive $5 each time they go on the air, Vorhees said Monday. West
Virginia Public Radio has about 12 commentators, she said.
   ``This is not a full-time, hired position,'' Vorhees said.
``He's doing us a favor. We needed a conservative commentator, so
we asked him.''
   Roark pleaded guilty to six misdemeanor charges of cocaine
possession and was sentenced to 179 days in prison on Jan. 14. He
resigned as mayor as part of his plea agreement.
   He was released July 20 after serving 5{ months of his term. A
state Bar subcommittee is deliberating whether to recommend that
Roark's law license be revoked.
