<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForeverFighting     09-12 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forever Fighting,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Fights System For Nine Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former janitor has fought for nearly nine
years since his acquittal on rape charges to get his old job back
at the University of Pittsburgh and to get a speedy resolution of
his case in state courts.
   ``The guy's going to be dead and buried by the time this is
resolved,'' attorney Robert Kane said.
   Arthur Robinson, 62, was fired from his janitor's job on Aug.
10, 1979, after a woman charged that he raped her two months
earlier.
   Robinson, who had no criminal record, was acquitted in December
1979, but he was not given his job back even though he had worked
at the university for 14 years.
   He sued, charging his firing was unjustified. He also filed a
complaint with the city Human Relations Commission charging the
university with race discrimination. Robinson is black.
   A Common Pleas Court jury in 1982 ordered Robinson's
reinstatement and awarded him nearly $125,000. After the university
appealed, Robinson settled the case in 1985 for $15,000 and
attorney's fees.
   Meanwhile, the city Human Relations Commission ordered
Robinson's reinstatement with back pay in March 1984.
   The university appealed that decision, too, but Common Pleas
Court officials apparently lost Robinson's file, delaying a trial
until December 1987, when Judge Robert A. Doyle affirmed the
commission's ruling.
   The university appealed again, to Commonwealth Court, on Jan. 8.
Commonwealth Court officials failed to get Doyle to forward
Robinson's files until last Friday, when a judge from that court
ordered Doyle to send the information.
   Robert Prorok, attorney for the university, said the case has
been appealed because there was no racial discrimination against
Robinson.
   ``The university's basis for discharging (Robinson) was an
investigation that, in their judgment, concluded that he committed
the rape. We sincerely believe that race had absolutely nothing to
do with his dismissal,'' he said.
   ``The fact that someone is acquitted in a criminal case doesn't
necessarily mean he didn't commit the crime,'' Prorok said.
   Robinson's wife, Odessa, said her husband hasn't worked since
1979. He said the family has lived on Social Security, welfare, a
small pension and a newspaper route.
   ``I believe God in his own time will clear this up,'' she said.
``But it looks as if somebody somewhere came between us and the
Lord.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
