<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WashingtonSketch     09-12 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington Sketch,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Credited With Return Of Washington Sketch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KILLINGWORTH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long-lost sketch in pen and ink
owned by George Washington has been placed in the first president's
Mount Vernon estate after a man found it among the belongings of an
elderly neighbor.
   Chester Norback, 85, a former appliance salesman, said in 1975
he noticed an old sketch in a neighbor's home in Killingworth,
which is 20 miles east of New Haven. The sketch, about 20 by 16
inches, is of a huge stone prison being demolished.
   The neighbor, Allen Carswell, acquired the sketch about 40 years
earlier from a Brooklyn, N.Y., warehouse, Norwell said.
   Norback said Carswell's wife, Dorothy, showed him a 1958 New
York Times clipping that included a photograph of the sketch. The
caption said the sketch was entitled, ``Destruction of the
Bastille,'' and explained that it was a gift from Lafayette to
Washington.
   The sketch's whereabouts had been unknown since its sale at
auction in 1891, the story said.
   Norback said that in 1984, when Dorothy Carswell had been a
widow for five years, she gave Norback power of attorney, handed
him the key to her home and asked him to help her into a nursing
home.
   Norback found the sketch and hid it under his bed.
   A month later, Mrs. Carswell died. ``For a period of time there
wasn't a person in the world _ but myself _ who knew about that
picture,'' Norback said.
   Norback sent a note to Mount Vernon, saying in part, ``If you
are still searching for this picture, ... I think I can help you.''
   Christine Meadows, Mount Vernon's curator, called Norback almost
immediately.
   Mrs. Carswell bequeathed her $400,000 estate to the Shriners
Hospitals for Crippled Children and to the Masonic Charity
Foundation of Connecticut.
   The charities at first expected to keep the sketch, appraised at
$20,000. But a letter Norback sent each, together with Mount
Vernon's interest and the necessary legal releases, moved both
organizations to loan the treasure to the Virginia estate.
   ``That painting belonged to Mount Vernon and the country,''
Norback said.
</TEXT>
