<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FlowerHouse     09-12 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flower House,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recent Thefts Prompt `Flower Man' To Uproot House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who worked five years to surround his home
with flowers uprooted his plantings and moved after burglars stole
everything but his bed frame and clothes.
   Cleveland Turner's yard, located in a poor section of the city,
had been full of flowers and adornments such as plastic swams and a
wood cutout of Mickey Mouse.
   But Turner, frustrated over two recent burglaries, pulled out
the bright surroundings last week and moved from the three-room
house to another rental home about two miles away.
   ``They (burglars) usually break in once a year, but they hit me
two times last week and stole everything but my bedstead and
clothes,'' said Turner, 53, who cleans residential windows and does
other odd jobs for a living.
   ``I just couldn't cut it anymore. I cried for two nights
straight to keep from moving. But I just couldn't stay there
anymore.''
   Eddie Minor Jr., 41, a former neighbor, was saddened to see
Turner leave.
   ``He had it looking nice, too _ you couldn't find nothing like
that anywhere,'' Minor said. ``Everybody loved it.''
</TEXT>
