<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BombDoorstop     09-12 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb Doorstop,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World War II Bomb Used As Farmhouse Doorstop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE EARTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auctioneer Merle Scherman decided not
to sell off one item he discovered at a farm near this northwestern
Minnesota town: a World War II bomb used as a farmhouse doorstop.
   Scherman, an auctioneer, came across the 2-foot-long brass
projectile as he was conducting inventory for an estate auction at
the farm. He said it had been used as a doorstop for a number of
years.
   Concerned that the 35-pound shell could pose a danger to people
attending the auction, Scherman contacted the Minnesota National
Guard Armory.
   The armory contacted the Mahnomen County Sheriff's Department to
have officers pick up the projectile. Sheriff Dennis Spickard
picked up the shell Thursday and brought it to his office.
   He contacted the National Guard camp at Fort McCoy in Wisconsin,
which has facilities for exploding a shell. He said he wasn't
concerned about having the device in his office.
   ``The way I look at it, it's been sitting around being used as a
doorstop for maybe 40 years or more and nothing has happened yet,''
he said.
   Personnel from Fort McCoy picked up the device and brought it to
the southern Wisconsin fort.
   Mary Binder, public affairs officer at Fort McCoy, said Monday
it was destroyed at the fort. She said it was a World War II Navy
anti-aircraft projectile.
   Asked if the device could have exploded during the years it
served as a doorstop, she said, ``It was designed to be shot from
aircraft and several things had to be done to it before it would go
off.''
   But she noted the device still had explosives in it and ``things
have been known to go off.''
</TEXT>
