<HEAD>Justice Spokesman to Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Korten, the Justice Department's chief
spokesman and staunch defender of former Attorney General Edwin
Meese III throughout a 14-month criminal investigation, said today
that he is resigning.
   Korten will be replaced effective next week by Loye Miller, who
is press secretary and director of public affairs for the
Department of Education. Korten plans to spend several months at
the Heritage Foundation, a conservative Washington think tank which
Meese joined last month. While there, Korton plans to carry out
some writing projects at the foundation while hoping to return
eventually to broadcasting.
   In an interview Korton said that he will remain at the
department for three or four weeks to assist in the transition to a
new director of public affairs. Korten, who has been under fire in
recent days for a trip he took to Japan at public expense, said he
told Attorney General Richard Thornburgh in July that he planned to
leave the department.
   Miller, a former political writer for Knight-Ridder and Newhouse
Newspapers, has known Attorney General Richard Thornburgh for a
number of years. Miller, 58, has been with the department of
education since June 1985. His boss, Education Secretary William
Bennett, is leaving the department next week.
   Korten, 40, who spent 11 years in radio and television news
before joining the Reagan administration, came to the Justice
Department in July 1985 as the deputy director of the office of
public affairs. In May, he became director after Meese fired chief
spokesman Terry Eastland.
   py
</TEXT>
