<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherBoycott     09-12 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Boycott,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Urged To Boycott School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of a black boycott of the
district's 17 public schools urged teachers in the school system to
call in sick Monday, but a school official said teacher attendance
was normal.
   The boycott was called to pressure officials to oust school
superintendent Nolan Vickers and his assistant, Janet Sweatt, both
of whom are white. Protesters say the two are not sensitive to the
needs of the mostly black school district.
   ``From 1869 they've had a white (superintendent),'' said protest
leader Willie Long, education chairman of the group, Save Our
Children. ``We ask for one black person, and we're racist.''
   Vickers and Sweatt have declined to comment on the boycott.
   ``From what I gathered, it is a normal day for absences on the
part of teachers,'' Assistant Superintendent Arthur Peyton said
Monday.
   Some parents also have been holding their children out of class
in protest. For two days last week, almost one-third of the
district's students were absent from classes.
   Peyton said 5,564 students were in attendance Monday.
   Before the boycott began, attendance was 8,834 in the district's
17 public school. Thursday, 5,879 students attended, and 6,082
attended Friday.
   About 200 people marched Saturday through the downtown area in
support of the boycott. Police escorted marchers for about a mile
through the downtown as they sang ``We Shall Overcome'' and carried
banners calling for the superintendent's ouster.
</TEXT>
