<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Earthquake     09-12 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earthquake,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Earthquake Jolts California Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake centered offshore
near metropolitan Los Angeles awakened residents early Monday, but
there were no reports of damage or injury, authorities said.
   Police were flooded with calls after the shaker, which struck at
6:24 a.m. and registered 3.8 on the Richter scale of ground motion,
according to preliminary readings. The U.S. Geological Survey in
Golden, Colo., recorded the quake at 4 on the Richter scale.
   The quake was centered four miles southwest of the coastal city
of El Segundo, 19 miles southwest of downtown Los Angeles, said
Steve Bryant, seismic analyst at the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena.
   No damage was reported to county sheriff's stations or police or
fire departments in El Segundo, Manhattan Beach, Hermosa Beach,
Redondo Beach and on the Palos Verdes Peninsula. A lifeguard on
Santa Catalina Island said he did not feel the temblor in Avalon.
   ``We've had lots of calls from people asking what that was,''
said Torrance police officer Jeannie Metcalf. ``I think it woke up
quite a few people.''
   Sgt. James Hirt of the Santa Monica Police Department said they
had also gotten dozens of calls, but he hadn't felt the temblor.
   ``It's not earthshaking, unless it's really earth shaking,'' he
said.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area.
</TEXT>
