<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Lange     09-12 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Lange,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jessica Lange Says America Facing Family Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jessica Lange says the problems facing
Americans should not be blamed on men or women but on the fact that
the family unit has become ``disposable.''
   ``I think that it's not only what's wrong with men. It's what's
wrong with women, what's wrong with children. It think that's
what's wrong with civilization in America,'' Lange says in the
October issue of Vanity Fair. ``The family's become disposable.''
   ``You know, if you don't like your wife, you can get rid of her;
if you don't like your husband for a day, you can get rid of him.''
   The star of ``Frances,'' ``Tootsie'' and ``Sweet Dreams'' says
she fears the disintegration of the family is ``a signal of the
end, of this whole kind of apocalyptic feeling that is in the air
now.''
   Despite her feelings, Lange has resisted remarrying. She lives
with playwright Sam Shepard and they have two children. She has a
third child by dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov.
   Her marriage, to a Spanish photographer, ended before she became
an actress.
   ``I think marriage is about your commitment to the other
person,'' she says. ``It has absolutely nothing to do with some
government decree. The legality of it means absolutely nothing to
me whatsoever.
   ``That's not going to make people live their lives together and
be responsible to each other,'' she says.
</TEXT>
