<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HometownGifts     09-12 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hometown Gifts,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Analyst Showers Gifts On Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLIVAR, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A San Francisco stock analyst who began
giving gifts to his Ozark hometown almost two years ago with the
donation of a $3 million trust has delivered another bonanza.
   David Delarue last week gave Bolivar $300,000 to put toward
development of a civic center and new city hall.
   Bolivar Mayor Joe Lemmon said the gift came so unexpectedly that
no plans were drawn up yet for the civic center. But he said
$104,000 was spent Thursday to buy property for the new center. The
rest of the money will be used to build the civic center after
matching funds are raised.
   ``A civic center has been discussed here for years, but we
haven't had the funds,'' Lemmon said.
   In December 1986, Delarue established a $3 million trust fund
that he said was a gesture of thanks to the community where he grew
up.
   The trust benefits the city, Polk County and various public
agencies. Recipients received an initial interest payment of
$150,000 this year and expect to receive annual payments of
$240,000 until 2100, when the principal will be given to the city.
   Delarue said he keeps track of what is going on in Bolivar
through old friends who still live in the town of about 6,000
people 30 miles north of Springfield.
   He said he learned about two weeks ago that a 2.2-acre plot of
land near the central square was available through an estate sale,
and immediately thought of buying it for the city.
   ``There was no planning,'' Delarue said Monday in a telephone
interview from his San Francisco home. ``It's probably the city's
last chance to find such a nice piece of property (close to
downtown.) I mainly thought they needed a community hall or
community center.''
   The mayor was delighted. ``We never know what to expect'' from
Delarue, he said. ``We love it.''
</TEXT>
