<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Snake-Burns     09-12 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Snake-Burns,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Hospitalized After Touching Power Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEWARD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was critically burned when he climbed a
utility pole to remove a dead snake he believed was interfering
with electricity in the neighborhood.
   Denny Lee Perry, 26, of Berwick, was airlifted from a ballfield
near his parents' home to West Penn Hospital in Pittsburgh, where
he was in critical condition Monday with burns over 56 percent of
his body.
   The snake was killed Saturday at the home of Perry's parents,
Ken and Patsy Perry, by Perry and his brother, Louie, said Lynne
Shoup, 19, fiancee of Louie Perry. It then was tossed onto the
power lines.
   Fire Chief Jim Edwards said Perry later tried to remove the
snake because he thought it was affecting power.
   ``All the electricity was blinking on and off,'' Miss Shoup said.
   Perry climbed the utility pole, touched a 23,000-volt power line
and fell 23 feet to the ground, Edwards said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
