<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Church-Bombing     09-12 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church-Bombing,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Hit By Deadly 1963 Bombing Now Finds Membership Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attendance at the Sixteenth Street
Baptist Church has declined dramatically in the 25 years since
dynamite killed four black girls, but the pastor says its
membership is worldwide in spirit.
   ``Sixteenth Street is not a local church _ Sept. 15, 1963, made
sure of that,'' said the Rev. James E. Young. ``It is in the truest
sense the people's church.''
   The church, which is marking the 25th anniversary of the bombing
this week, nearly filled its 1,500 seats regularly in the 1940s and
1950s and became a rallying point for civil rights demonstrators
who filled it in the 1960s.
   Now, it has about 100 members. The church has suffered common
urban church problems such as members moving away from downtown.
   At Sunday's service, which opened the week's anniversary
observance program, the balcony was empty, as were many pews on the
main floor, and visitors outnumbered members when asked to stand.
   ``That didn't look so good, as far as the church itself was
concerned,'' said James L. Lowe, a deacon and member of the church
for 60 years. Lowe, who plays the clarinet and saxophone, is the
lone member of the church orchestra, which once had 20 musicians.
   Lowe said the church's role during the civil rights movement,
while making it a landmark, did not please all the members.
   ``We suffered a great deal because we had so many threats coming
into the church,'' said Lowe.
   The church was formed in 1873 and the building, designed by a
black architect and built by a black contractor, was erected in
1906. The bombing heavily damaged the basement area where the girls
were killed but the damage was not as severe elsewhere in the
building. A white man, Robert Edward Chambliss, was convicted of
murder in the explosion.
   Young said the media coverage of the 25th anniversary may help
bring more people to the church.
   ``Our hope is that there will be some benefits to the whole
community, including members of Sixteenth Street Baptist Church,''
he said.
   ``We are hoping that we will get the attendance up,'' said
William M. Parker, chairman of the church's board of trustees and a
member since 1965. ``That would help us a lot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
