<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NBC-MainStreet     09-12 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC-Main Street,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Cancels `Main Street'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC has canceled its critically praised but
low-rated ``Main Street,'' an afternoon news program for children.
   ``I made the decision last Wednesday that there was just no way
that show could live. It was a decision widely expected. I met with
the staff on Friday afternoon,'' NBC News President Michael G.
Gartner said Monday.
   For Gartner, a newspaper editor and executive who took over as
head of the news division in July, it was a quick introduction to
the realities of television programming.
   ``Sure it's hard,'' he said. ``You'd much rather be meeting with
the staff and launching something rather than killing something.
But the show didn't have the support of advertisers, didn't have
the support of affiliates and didn't have support of the audience.
As I told somebody, one out of three would have been nice.''
   Gartner said he now has ``sort of finished the process'' of
layoffs that began after last year's efficiency appraisal. The
layoffs have involved approximately 400 news division employees.
   Gartner said the last round of layoffs, effective at year's end,
included a ``handful'' of permanent employees, along with 60-70
employees who had been hired on a temporary basis for election
coverage.
   NBC is closing its Houston bureau as of the end of the year,
dismissing six people there. A producer and office manager will
maintain an NBC office in Houston, but correspondent Dan Molina and
bureau chief Ray Cullen will be transferred to Los Angeles. NBC has
nine domestic bureaus, including Houston. It has offices in three
other cities.
   All three network news divisions have been laying off employees
for the past couple of years as new management has taken over and
reassessed costs.
</TEXT>
