<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignTV     09-12 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign TV,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Challengers Favor Free TV-Time Requirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A solid majority of political challengers but
less than one-third of incumbents say television and radio stations
should be required to give House and Senate candidates free air
time, says a report on the role of media in congressional campaigns.
   The report, by the nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics,
said a requirement that included more time for debates would make
an overall lid on campaign spending much more palatable, even to
incumbents.
   ``Beyond the 30-Second Spot'' was based on a survey of 141 House
and 40 Senate incumbents and challengers who ran in 1986. They were
asked how they used electronic media and how they might want to
change the laws affecting political broadcasting.
   Half of the 181 candidates surveyed spent more money on
commercial television than on direct mail, radio or newspaper ads;
only 12.7 percent of the candidates tried to buy air time longer
than 30 or 60 seconds.
   Among incumbents, 29.5 percent favored requiring broadcasters to
provide free media time, while 60.9 percent of challengers
supported the idea. Some 40 percent of the incumbents and 75
percent of the challengers said any free media arrangement should
include mandated debate time for congressional candidates.
   If Congress were to pass a free media requirement, the center
found, 54.9 percent of those surveyed said they would accept a
limit on overall campaign spending. That included 48 percent of the
incumbents running for re-election.
   Based on these and other findings, the center made a number of
recommendations aimed at providing free and lower-cost media
exposure to Senate and House candidates.
   ``No one of these changes can entirely replace the ubiquitous
30-second commercial, or drastically reduce the cost of
campaigns,'' the study said. ``But taken together, the center
believes that these proposals would make significant contributions
to the American electoral system.''
   First and foremost, the center said Congress should require
television stations to run two hours of special programming about
House races and two hours about Senate races each election season.
   Programs would have to be at least five minutes long. The time
could be turned over to candidates or the stations could produce
the material themselves. No station would have to cover all the
elections in its market.
   The center also recommended that the equal opportunities rule,
which forces broadcasters to give competing candidates comparable
air time, be changed to apply to only major party and strong
third-party candidates.
   If one candidate declines to debate, the center said, under some
circumstances the other should be given air time alone without
triggering equal-time rules.
   In addition, the center recommended that candidates receive 30
percent discounts on air time that cannot be pre-empted by
higher-paying advertisers. This was prompted by findings that
although candidates are entitled by law to discount rates, they
aren't using them.
   ``Candidates are inclined to pay higher rates to ensure that
their ads are not pre-empted,'' the study said. ``Overall, 54.2
percent of candidates preferred to purchase higher priced,
non-pre-emptible advertising time rather than lower cost,
pre-emptible time.''
</TEXT>
