<1ST_LINE>u p PM-DelawarePrimary 3rdLd-Writethru a0596 09-12 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delaware Primary, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0596,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Lieutenant Governor Claims Senate Primary Victory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with comment from state election
official, CORRECTS that state officials only admitted making
mistake and did not tell Woo he had won; Picks up 5th graf, `Sam
doesn't ...'; DELETES now-redundant 11th graf, `The unofficial
...'; ADDS 1 graf to conform to editing changes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo claimed victory today
in Delaware's Democratic Senate primary, saying state officials had
discovered vote counting errors that he says reversed the results
of the election.
   Challenger Samuel Beard had been declared the winner of
Saturday's primary. Woo had conceded the race.
   Paul T. Hart, adminsitrative director of the Department of
Elections for New Castle County, said today a keypunch operator
made a mistake that gave Beard 2,800 more votes than he received.
   ``When this correction is made, Woo will instead win by six
votes,'' Woo said in a press release.
   But Hart said, ``I have no idea who is ahead.''
   The unofficial tally had given Beard 22,418 votes to Woo's
19,624. The revised results would give Beard only 19,618 votes to
Woo's 19,624.
   The final numbers, however, could change because votes from nine
precincts still must be counted. Woo also said he believes
additional absentee ballots will be counted.
   ``I have no idea how it happened, but I am satisfied in my own
mind that it was human error,'' Hart said today.
   Beard campaign manager Nathan Siegel had no comment.
   ``Sam doesn't think it is appropriate until the results are
completed,'' he said. ``Sam wants to have the most accurate and
clear count there is.''
   The vote discrepancy came in the 23rd representative district in
New Castle County, where there about 280 registered Democrats. In
that district, however, Beard's total was tallied at 2,828 votes
when he actually received only 28 votes, elections officials said.
A recount is expected.
   The New Castle County Board of Elections meets tonight to count
ballots from the nine precincts. New Castle County includes the
city of Wilmington.
   The winner of the primary will run against incumbent Sen.
William Roth Jr., R-Del., in the November general election.
   Woo had conceded the race Saturday night, saying ``I always said
it was a tough way to earn a living.''
   Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the University of
Delaware, was elected lieutenant governor four years ago in his
first bid for elected office.
   The lieutenant governor, who will leave his post in January, had
been considered a shoo-in for re-election, but chose instead to run
for the Senate.
   Beard had been heavily outspent by Woo, a native of Shanghai,
China, who enjoyed the financial backing of Chinese-Americans from
across the nation.
   Beard, 49, had the backing of most Democratic organization
leaders and labor.
   Beard, who has served as chairman for job creation commissions
under the last four presidents, said his experience in public
service helped in the campaign.
   The Senate race was the only statewide competition on the
ballot. Roth, seeking a fourth six-year term, is running unopposed.
</TEXT>
