<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MeaslesOutbreak     09-12 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Measles Outbreak,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Hope To Keep Measles Confined To Falwell's University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNCHBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials immunized people in
Lynchburg and four surrounding counties Monday as they tried to
keep an outbreak of measles at the Rev. Jerry Falwell's Liberty
University from becoming a regional epidemic.
   ``We're trying now to keep it confined to the campus and keep it
from spreading to the community,'' said Dr. Joanna Harris, a state
Health Department official. ``We're hoping we're going to nip it in
the bud at this point.''
   With some 40 cases reported among students, faculty and people
who had visited the university, Ms. Harris estimated at least 200
more people will be sickened by rubeola measles.
   ``It's generally four times as high'' as the initial outbreak,
she said. Officials vaccinated 1,800 students, staff and faculty
over the weekend.
   Liberty University had not been quarantined, she said, but
people were advised not to go on campus until they have been
immunized.
   Free vaccinations were offered Monday at clinics in Lynchburg
and in the counties of Bedford, Campbell, Amherst and Appomattox.
   It was too soon to say how many people would be vaccinated.
   Health officials said people born before 1957, when
immunizations for the illness were first started, are generally
considered to be immune to rubeola measles.
   The disease strikes victims at first with a red rash that begins
on the face and chest and persists for about three days. The
disease can be fatal, according to the federal Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta.
   ``There were four people who died last year in the United States
out of 3,655 cases,'' Ms. Harris said.
   The disease apparently came to the university by a student who
had the measles, she said.
   The measles also apparently were spread to Falwell's Thomas Road
Baptist Church by an infected Liberty student, Ms. Harris said.
</TEXT>
