<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PlaneCrash     09-12 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighter Plane Crashes Into Hangars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL CAJON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An F-14 fighter jet crashed into a
hangar today at an airfield, setting a row of hangars ablaze and
injuring at least three people, police and witnesses said.
   Two pilots bailed out of the plane to safety, according to
witnesses, who said the plane then smashed upside down at Gillespie
Field.
   Three people were confirmed injured in the 10:18 a.m. crash,
KFMB radio in San Diego reported. A dozen ambulances were at the
scene, the station said.
   The San Diego Blood Bank was calling for donations, said
spokeswoman Lynn Stedd, adding that supplies were below safety
levels.
   ``We understand that at least one of the victims is bleeding
profusely,'' she said. ``We don't know what else to anticipate as
far as injuries are concerned.''
   An El Cajon police spokesman said the plane was an F-14, and
that further details weren't immediately available. A Navy
spokesman who didn't give his name said officials from the Naval
Air Station at Miramar were en route to the crash.
   ``The plane was inverted flying over our location,'' said one
witness who was across the street from Gillespie Field. ``It kept
going in lower and lower and lower. I told a guy, `That plane is in
trouble, it's going down.'''
   ``It slammed upside down right on to a hangar,'' said the man,
who didn't give his name.
   The airfield is on the northern outskirts of this San Diego
County city.
</TEXT>
