<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedicalWaste     09-12 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medical Waste,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Needle, Blood Vials Found On Madison Avenue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several used medical items were found on a
Manhattan sidewalk, and six boxes of a prescription antibiotic were
found on a playground, authorities said Monday.
   A used needle, syringe and three vials of blood were spotted by
a passerby, who called police Sunday night, said Jim Hart, a
spokesman for the Department of Sanitation.
   Doctors and medical labs are required by law to separate such
waste from regular garbage and dispose of it through special
private carters.
   Five doctors and two medical labs were listed at the address on
the Upper East Side where the items were found.
   The blood has not yet been tested, Hart said.
   The boxes on the playground on the west side of Manhattan
contained 10 packages each of the antibiotic Minocin, said Sgt.
Raymond O'Donnell, a police spokesman. The packages appeared to be
sample-size, he said.
   The passers-by who found the boxes Sunday brought them to police.
   ``Since the material has been washed up on the beaches, we have
seen an increase in reporting'' by citizens, Hart said.
   Medical waste has been found on sidewalks and in garbage bins
around the city this summer, and miles of beaches in New York and
New Jersey were closed for days after needles and other forms of
waste washed up.
   Last week, the first doctor was arrested in Manhattan on charges
of improperly disposing of medical waste.
   The growing problem of illegally disposed of medical waste
appears to stem from doctors or medical laboratories who do not
want to pay the added expense of using hauling companies that are
licensed to carry infectious waste, New York City Sanitation
Commissioner Brendan Sexton has said.
</TEXT>
