<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Syria-American 2ndLd-Writethru a0640 09-12 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Syria-American, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0640,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Engineer Turned Over to U.S. Embassy After Abduction In
Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to update with account from officials in
Washington. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``He said the American...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops today rescued an American
engineer who was abducted by gunmen in Lebanon, and turned him over
to the U.S. Embassy in Damascus, a source close to the Foreign
Ministry reported.
   In Washington, U.S. officials said Kenneth Wells, who works in
Saudi Arabia for Litton Industries, was taken captive in Lebanon
but overpowered his captors and escaped.
   The U.S. officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Wells was kidnapped Sunday as he was leaving his wedding reception.
They said his Lebanese bride was detained briefly.
   Wells subdued his abductors after several hours, reached a
Syrian army checkpoint and was escorted to Damascus, where he was
turned over to a U.S. Embassy official, the sources in Washington
said.
   The U.S. officials said Wells' mother reportedly lives in
Tennessee. According to one published report, Wells is 25 and his
wife, Samia, is 32. He is said to hold a black belt in karate.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman, who confirmed much of
the account of Wells' experience, expressed gratitude to Syrian
authorities for their assistance. He said the episode underscores
the dangers American citizens face in Lebanon, where nine Americans
are held hostage.
   In the Syrian capital, the U.S. Embassy refused comment.
   The source close to the Foreign Ministry, who also spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the American went to Lebanon to marry
a woman whose family lives in Baalbek.
   He said the American was kidnapped Sunday by unidentified gunmen
before he reached his fiancee's home. He said the man was found by
Syrian troops after an all night search.
   The American was freed and taken to Damascus, where Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa turned him over to U.S. charge d'affaires
John Craig, the source said.
   In Beirut, the Christian-run Voice of Lebanon radio station gave
a different account.
   The radio said a man identified as Keith Paul Weiss, 25, married
Nadia Sharafeddine, 22, in Baalbek and that three gunmen
intercepted the newlyweds a few hours after the wedding.
   The Voice of Lebanon said the bridegroom ``who excels in
karate'' overpowered the gunmen, who were armed with automatic
rifles, disarmed them and took refuge at a Syrian army post. The
Syrians then drove him to Damascus, the radio said.
   The discrepancies between the various reports could not be
reconciled immediately.
   The Sharafeddines are a well-known Shiite Moslem family in
Baalbek, a stronghold of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is an extremist Shiite group that is
believed to be an umbrella for various factions holding 18 foreign
hostages in Lebanon.
   The hostage held the longest is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
