<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Korten-Justice     09-12 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korten-Justice,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Spokesman Announces Resignation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Korten, the chief Justice Department
spokesman during former Attorney General Edwin Meese III's last
months in office, said Monday he is resigning.
   He will be replaced effective next week by Loye Miller, who is
press secretary and director of public affairs for the Department
of Education. Miller's boss, Education Secretary William Bennett,
is leaving office next week.
   Korten said he will do some writing for several months at the
Heritage Foundation, a conservative Washington think tank where
Meese now works, and hopes eventually to return to broadcasting,
where he worked before joining the government.
   Korten was a staunch defender of Meese throughout a 14-month
criminal investigation of the attorney general's stock holdings and
actions on behalf of longtime friend E. Robert Wallach, who is now
under indictment in the Wedtech scandal.
   The criminal probe of Meese by independent counsel James McKay
ended without prosecution, although McKay said Meese probably broke
federal conflict-of-interest and tax laws.
   Korten said in an interview that he will remain at the Justice
Department for three or four weeks to assist in the transition to a
new director of public affairs.
   Korten, who has been under fire in recent days from aides to
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh for a trip Korten took to Japan
at public expense, said he told Thornburgh in July that he intended
to leave the department shortly.
   Miller, 50, a former political writer for the Knight-Ridder and
Newhouse newspaper groups, has known Thornburgh for several years
and has been at the Education Department since June 1985.
   Korten, 40, who spent 11 years in radio and television news
before joining the Reagan administration, came to the Justice
Department in July 1985 as the deputy director of public affairs.
   In May, he became director after Meese fired chief spokesman
Terry Eastland. Korten worked at the Office of Personnel Management
before coming to the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
