<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SculptureGarden     09-12 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sculpture Garden,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3,000 Artists, Officials Open Minneapolis Sculpture Garden</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0650 to make it AMs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $12.8 million Minneapolis Sculpture
Garden, the nation's largest urban sculpture site, was called an
``artistic triumph'' by one official in its opening ceremony.
   About 3,000 artists, city and national officials and visitors
applauded as 10,000 pastel balloons rose from the 7.5-acre garden
and a high school band played on the 375-foot-long Irene Hixon
Whiteney bridge-sculpture in Saturday's ceremony.
   Claes Oldenburg of New York, the sculptor of the garden's
59-foot-long ``Spoonbridge and Cherry'' fountain, declared the
opening ``an epochal event.''
   The sculpture garden is the newest addition to the Minneapolis
park system's 170 facilities.
   It is one of the few U.S. sculpture gardens that is free and
open to the public year round.
   Walker director Martin Friedman and Park Superintendent David
Fisher officially opened the garden with giant scissors that
snipped a red ribbon tied between the garden's entrance portals, a
columnar sculpture by Chicago artist Martin Puryear.
   During the ceremony, Gov. Rudy Perpich said the garden was an
``artistic triumph'' that enhanced the cultural quality of life in
Minnesota ``with its unique blend of artistic vision, environmental
beauty, social generosity and professional optimism.''
   Artists admired each other's work and children climbed over the
artist-designed benches and patted Deborah Butterfield's bronze
horse, a sculpture that appears to be made of driftwood.
   ``Its really a neat place,'' said Rick Jabs of Richfield, adding
that he was especially impressed that children ``can touch the
sculpture.''
   Richard Koshalek, director of the Museum of Contemporary Art in
Los Angeles, said the garden contained an ``outstanding selection
of sculptures'' and was a model for other cities.
   Sculptor George Segal said the garden as an extraordinary place
to view sculpture and said its design and layout were ``serene,
classical, perfectly balanced.''
</TEXT>
