<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GirlSearch     09-12 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Girl Search,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clues Scarce In 7-Year-Old's Disappearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDLOTHIAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Monday they were baffled by
the disappearance of a 7-year-old girl who was discovered missing
from her bedroom Saturday.
   Authorities were trying to determine whether Jaclyn Dowaliby was
abducted by a relative, kidnapped, or had met with foul play.
Police said it was unlikely that she ran away.
   Jaclyn was last seen about 11 p.m. Friday when her mother,
Cindy, checked her bedroom. The girl's adoptive father, David
Dowaliby, discovered her missing at about 8 a.m. the next morning
when he checked her bedroom. Police said Dowaliby also discovered a
basement window in the house was broken and the front door of the
home was ajar.
   ``We haven't ruled out anything at this time, because we've just
got a lot of unanswered questions,'' said Capt. John Bittin of the
police force in this suburb south of Chicago.
   Bittin added, ``The fact that there was nothing disturbed in the
house, no signs of violent struggle, nobody heard anything, that
brings to mind ... questions, Bittin said.
   He said the case differs from a typical kidnapping. ``They're
not a wealthy family. There haven't been any calls or notes asking
for ransom,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, FBI agents have determined that the girl's imprisoned
father had nothing to do with the disappearance.
   James Guess, the child's natural father, was questioned Sunday
by FBI agents in Florida, where he is in prison, and expressed
shock about Jaclyn's disappearance, Bittin said.
   ``He was totally shocked, he was totally unaware of anything
that had happened,'' Bittin said. Based on statements from Guess,
the FBI has decided ``that he had nothing to do with it,'' the
captain said.
   Bittin said he did not know why Guess was imprisoned. A
spokesman for the FBI did not immediately return telephone calls.
   FBI agents planned interviews Monday with relatives of the
natural father.
   Also Monday, local and state police continued their foot-search
in wooded areas near the girl's home. A canine unit was used to
search a nearby field, but found no clues.
   He said there was no reason to suspect foul play ``other than
the fact that we haven't been able to locate her. Unfortunately,
the possibilty is always there for that ... but we don't have any
proof one way or the other.''
   Jaclyn was described by police as being about 4 feet tall and
weighing about 60 pounds. She has shoulder-length brown hair and
blue eyes.
</TEXT>
