<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoseaWilliams     09-12 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hosea Williams,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Recommends No Suspension For City Councilman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Councilman Hosea Williams need not be
suspended from office over his weapons indictment since the charge
does not involve his performance in office, a special panel
reported Monday to the governor.
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris appointed the panel last month after
Williams' indictment on a felony weapons charge, which stemmed from
an incident in March at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport.
   Security officers found a handgun in Williams' briefcase as he
passed through a checkpoint. The charge was later made a felony
after Williams was cited as a habitual violator; he has a string of
traffic violations.
   A 1984 state law provides for the governor to appoint a
three-member panel to investigate the cases of public officials
under indictment. The panel recommends whether suspension from
office is in order.
   Attorney General Michael Bowers previously said such a panel was
not required in Williams' case, since his indictment did not
involve his official duties. But Harris disagreed.
   The panel, composed of Bowers, Augusta City Councilman Gerald
Woods and Columbus City Councilman A.J. McClung, voted unanimously
Monday against recommending that Harris suspend Williams.
   Bowers said the panel found the indictment ``did not relate to
or adversely impact the administration of his office'' or the
rights and interests of the public.
   Williams, a veteran civil rights activist, has said he routinely
carries a gun for protection. He explained the airport incident by
saying he had removed the gun from his car and put it in his
briefcase, then forgot to leave it behind before heading for his
flight.
   At the time, Williams was cited and allowed to make his plane.
Clayton County officers later arrested Williams on the felony
charge.
</TEXT>
