<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrialProtest     09-12 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trial Protest,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Masked Women Interrupt Arraignment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine women dressed in black pulled
stockings over their faces in court Monday and began chanting,
claiming to invoke the presence of a murder victim at an
arraignment for the accused.
   ``Your action will come back to you. Every action will have
consequences,'' the women chanted, pointing at Alan Jose Reyes, 32,
of Turner Falls.
   Reyes' girlfriend, Virginia Ferrer, 27, was stabbed several
times in the heart in an alley outside her home while one of their
children reportedly watched. She died early Saturday.
   Reyes is charged in Greenfield District Court with murder,
assault and battery with a dangerous weapon and disorderly conduct.
   The women began chanting as soon as Reyes' case was announced.
Their stocking masks contained runs and holes outlined with what
appeared to be red nail polish.
   ``We will avenge Virginia's death,'' they said. ``Virginia is
here. You should have known Virginia is here. This is not that
man's first day in court.''
   A recess was called and police escorted the women outside. They
continued to chant until they reached the sidewalk, where they
began laughing hysterically. They refused to say if they were
members of a women's advocacy organization.
   ``We're all Virginia from Turners Falls,'' they said. ``We're
women. Virginia is not the only woman,'' they said.
   Reyes pleaded innocent before District Judge Edward J. Shea.
</TEXT>
