<DOCNO> AP880912-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Eastwood     09-12 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Eastwood,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clint Eastwood Donates Collection To Wesleyan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the movie character Dirty Harry,
Wesleyan University got its man.
   After three years of pursuing actor Clint Eastwood, the
Middletown university has scored a hit. Eastwood has agreed to
donate all film and documents relating to his professional acting,
producing and directing career to the Clint Eastwood Cinema
Collection at Wesleyan and the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
   The museum will hold the original prints of Eastwood's films,
starting with ``Play Misty for Me,'' the 1971 thriller which
Eastwood starred in and directed.
   Wesleyan's Cinema Archives will receive all other material that
Eastwood has been collecting and storing at Warner Brothers studios
in Hollywood.
   Jeanine Basinger, the archive's curator, said the collection is
likely to include scripts, photographs, correspondence and other
``working papers.'' She said the full contents of Eastwood's
collection won't be known until it is received at Wesleyan and
catalogued.
   Once the material arrives, Eastwood will join the likes of
directors Frank Capra and Elia Kazan with collections at Wesleyan.
   ``He's a unique American artist. He has made films that are
distinctively original,'' she said Monday, noting that the
university's film students have studied Eastwood films in the
classroom since 1971.
   The Wesleyan archives, created in 1985, also includes the
collection of actress Ingrid Bergman, as well as a collection of
films, papers from the Omnibus performing arts television show, and
a collection of American movie posters.
   Basinger said Eastwood has apparently saved everything stemming
from his career, including from the days when he was a regular on
the television show, ``Rawhide.'' She said Eastwood's collection
wasn't the result of ``star vanity, but from a serious,
professional career.''
   Eastwood told The New York Times that his relationship with the
Museum of Modern Art began in 1980, when it showed his ``Bronco
Billy'' in 1980 at the conclusion of week-long retrospective.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Myerson-Passes     09-12 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson-Passes,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bess Myerson Trial: Press Passes Are A Hot Ticket</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conspiracy trial of former beauty queen Bess
Myerson doesn't begin until Wednesday, but the rush to get press
credentials for the highly publicized divorce-fixing case began
early Monday, very early.
   William Cohen, a researcher for the Los Angeles Times, showed up
at 2 a.m. and found two guys already on line outside the courthouse.
   The early birds, recent graduates from Dartmouth and Columbia,
were holding a place for a reporter for the magazine Vanity Fair,
said Cohen.
   ``It was actually very funny,'' said Cohen, himself a recent
Columbia graduate. ``There we were in the middle of the night,
three Ivy League grads standing around telling jokes and waiting to
get in.''
   Within hours they were joined by a dozen more place-holders,
sketch artists, reporters and writers seeking the 19 remaining
seats allotted to the news media in the tiny courtroom where the
trial will be held.
   ``None of us slept well for two days over the weekend, worrying
about it,'' said Richard Tomlinson, a courtroom artist for WNYW-TV,
who got to the federal courthouse in lower Manhattan at 4:45 a.m.
   The trip downtown turned into a nightmare for Tomlinson, who got
stuck at an unattended subway exit that wasn't supposed to open
until 7 a.m. Eventually ``two subway workers came out of the dark
with lanterns'' and freed him.
   The object of the news media anxiety is what may be one of New
York's most sensational criminal trials in years.
   Miss Myerson, a former Miss America and one-time city cultural
affairs commissioner, is charged with giving a city job to the
daughter of the judge presiding over her boyfriend's divorce in a
bid to lighten his alimony and child support load.
   Jury selection is to begin Wednesday for the trial of Miss
Myerson; her boyfriend, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso; and the divorce
judge, former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel.
   The three are charged with mail fraud and conspiracy for an
alleged scheme to fix Capasso's 1985 divorce. Miss Myerson also is
charged with obstruction of justice.
   Seating is limited because no large courtroom was available at
the 31-story federal courthouse.
   ``The larger courtrooms had already been scheduled months in
advance for other trials,'' explained Clifford P. Kirsch, the chief
non-judicial administrator of the courthouse.
   Despite an informal request by reporters to find something
bigger, U.S. District Judge John Keenan elected to stay in his
regular courtroom, which only seats about 50 spectators.
   Kirsch set aside about 30 seats for the news media: 11 for the
resident courthouse press corps and the remaining 19 for artists
and reporters on a first-come, first-served basis.
   ``The judge made a combination of such strictures that it was
designed to limit all but the most determined,'' complained Daily
News artist Joe Papin, the fourth artist on line, who arrived at 6
a.m.
   There were seats for six artists, and Ruth Pollack of WPIX-TV
was the seventh artist on line.
   However, because ``I got there seconds after the sixth artist
and I was the last artist on line,'' officials made an exception
and gave her a pass.
   All of the passes were handed out by 9 a.m.
   Out of luck, and on the growing waiting list, were such news
organizations as USA Today, Cable News Network and National Public
Radio.
</TEXT>
