<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-Burton     09-12 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Burton,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Kept 18-Year Dossier on Congressman, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI kept an 18-year dossier on the
late Democratic Rep. Phillip Burton and furnished documents to
President Lyndon Johnson purporting to detail Burton's
``pro-communist record,'' the Oakland Tribune reported Monday.
   The newspaper said the FBI had furnished it with 231 pages of
files on Burton, some of them heavily censored, and withheld nearly
400 pages, in response to a Freedom of Information Act request
submitted 27 months ago.
   Burton represented San Francisco in the state Assembly from 1956
until his election to the U.S. House in 1964, and remained a
congressman until his death in 1983. The FBI files cover 1953 to
1971, the Tribune said.
   Among other things, the files show that the FBI tried to block
appointment of a Burton aide as San Francisco postmaster, kept
Director J. Edgar Hoover informed of details of Burton's
activities, and compiled unflattering information about the
congressman's family, the newspaper said.
   FBI spokesman Bill Carter said Monday he was unaware of the
files and could not comment but said the FBI has since come under
new guidelines.
   Now, ``if a member of Congress has committed or is conspiring to
commit some violation of the law, certainly we would have an
investigation,'' but not otherwise, Carter said.
   Assemblyman John Burton, the congressman's brother, said he had
not seen the files but called the report ``more proof of Hoover's
paranoia. He used to see Communists under his bed.''
   The files say Johnson inquired about Burton's background in 1964
and was sent a series of documents from the FBI the next year. The
documents referred repeatedly to Burton's association with the
National Lawyers' Guild, and criticized his attempt to scrap
loyalty oaths for lawmakers and his opposition to the House
Un-American Activities Committee, the Tribune said.
   Also in 1964, Burton traveled to Mississippi to observe the
search for three missing civil rights workers later found murdered.
Then-Assistant FBI Director Cartha DeLoach recommended that agents
on the scene receive Burton politely but tell him nothing about the
investigation, the newspaper said.
   A December 1965 memo from the FBI's San Francisco field office
recommended that, in light of Burton's ``very questionable
background,'' Hoover oppose appointment of the congressman's
administrative assistant, Lim P. Lee, as San Francisco's postmaster.
   The field office urged that damaging information on Lee be
forwarded to the White House. Lee was appointed, however, and
served as postmaster for 14 years.
   The dossier also cites instances in which Burton criticized
statements by Hoover.
   After Hoover in 1969 called the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
``the most notorious liar in America,'' Burton approached the FBI's
chief San Francisco agent at a party in a ``very belligerent
manner'' and said Hoover's statement had been ``off-base,'' the
agent said in a memo to Hoover.
   Also in 1969, the files quote Burton attacking as disparaging to
Chinese-Americans a statement by Hoover that some Chinese-Americans
``would assist Red China in supplying needed material (for
espionage) or promoting Red Chinese propaganda.''
   An unnamed FBI official said in a report that Burton was ``a
longtime apologist for Communist China,'' and recommended that the
FBI ``set him straight'' about the Communist ``menace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1649EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-NationalSecurity 1stLd-Writethru a0657 09-12 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-National Security, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Names National Security Panel Including Former Carter Adviser</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis spokesman comment, subbing 2 grafs for
7th graf pvs, Dukakis had</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush won endorsements
Monday from former national security advisers to Presidents Nixon,
Ford and Carter as he assembled a bipartisan team of advisers on
foreign policy and defense issues.
   Zbigniew Brzezinski, the most prominent Democrat on the
13-member panel, told reporters he was proud to have served Carter
but said Bush _ rather than Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis _
``can best fashion an effective bipartisan foreign policy.''
   Said Brzezinski: ``He is not a novice in that critical area of
public policy on which our national survival depends.''
   Bush took the occasion to accuse Dukakis of tending to rely on
the United Nations and other international bodies to resolve
foreign crises. ``We cannot abdicate our responsibility for
leadership,'' he said.
   The panel also includes Henry Kissinger, national security
adviser to Nixon and secretary of state under Ford, and Brent
Scowcroft, who was Ford's national security adviser.
   Others named to the largely Republican panel were former
Secretary of State Alexander Haig, former ambassador Anne
Armstrong, former White House chief of staff Howard Baker; Melvin
Laird and Donald Rumsfeld, former secretaries of defense; Sens.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., and Richard Lugar,
R-Ind.; former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, and retired Adm. Elmo R.
Zumwalt Jr., former chief of naval operations.
   Brzezinski's endorsement of Bush was ``not unexpected,'' said
Mark Gearan, a spokesman at Dukakis campaign headquarters in Boston.
   ``We will be watching to see whether Mr. Brzezinski will be
drafting speeches for George Bush on the foreign policy of Jimmy
Carter,'' said Gearan, alluding to repeated GOP attacks on Carter's
tenure.
   On Monday, Dukakis delivered the first of three major campaign
speeches this week that are intended to counter Republican
allegations that he is weak on defense and naive about foreign
affairs.
   ``The primary foreign policy objective of the Dukakis
administration can be stated very simply: to restore respect for
American leadership in a changing world,'' Dukakis told a campaign
rally in Philadelphia.
   He accused Bush of failed leadership in combating terrorism,
drug trafficking and U.S. deficits in world trade.
   Dukakis has no formal advisory panel of national security
experts for his campaign. Madeleine Albright has been his chief
foreign affairs adviser for the past year.
   In addition to Ms. Albright, who served in the Carter White
House and is a professor at Georgetown University, Dukakis receives
advice on those issues from Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., and a trio from the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard
University. They are Joseph Nye, Graham Allison and Albert
Carnesdale.
   Kissinger said in a statement he had ``read everything I could
find on foreign and national security policy uttered by Gov.
Dukakis _ which is admittedly a skimpy body of work.''
   ``I am convinced that his views on national security are
incompatible with a strong America, his approach to East-West
relations would undermine our ability to move the Soviet Union
toward more responsible behavior, and his view of international
affairs would keep us from shaping the new world decades of
dedication have brought into view,'' Kissinger said.
   Scowcroft told the same news conference that Dukakis ``is
without experience in foreign affairs, and his penchant for
multilateral diplomacy fails to recognize the vital role of dynamic
U.S. leadership in moving regional conflicts toward resolutions
compatible with U.S. interests.''
</TEXT>
