<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietHarvest     09-12 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Harvest,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Lowers Forecast of Soviet Grain Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects for this year's grain harvest in the
Soviet Union have deteriorated somewhat because of a drop in some
yields, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   The Soviet crop is now expected to produce about 205 million
metric tons, a reduction of 5 million tons from projections a month
ago, officials said. The lowered estimate was based primarily on
early yield results released by the Soviets and on the Sept. 7
disclosure on Moscow television that the grain harvest would be
less than expected.
   Reduced production estimates included barley, 47.5 million tons,
down 3 million tons from the August forecast; rye, 16.5 million
tons, down 1 million; and oats, 16.5 million, down 1 million.
   The Soviet Union also is expected to boost grain imports further
to about 27 million tons in 1988-89, an increase of 2 million tons
from indications last month but still short of the 32 million tons
imported in 1987-88.
   ``Over the past month, numerous reports have been received of
U.S.S.R. grain purchases, breaking the lull in Soviet grain buying
activity that had prevailed since last spring,'' the report said.
``The bulk of the recent purchases have been coarse grains (such as
corn), although reports have also indicated wheat sales by some of
the major suppliers.''
</TEXT>
