<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhoopingCranes     09-12 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whooping Cranes,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Provides Money For Whooping Cranes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation is on its way to President Reagan
providing money to buy the last privately held land on a Texas
island that is a wintering ground for the world's only surviving
flock of whooping cranes that breeds in the wild.
   The Interior Department appropriations bill, passed last week by
Congress, provides $5.5 million for the purchase of 5,017 acres at
the southern tip of Matagorda Island, officials say.
   The purchase will be the government's third and final
acquisition from the Texas Nature Conservancy, bringing the
federally owned tract on the Gulf Coast barrier island to 11,502
acres.
   With the growth of the flock over the past four decades, the
whooping cranes have had to search for new wintering grounds away
from their traditional winter home on nearby Aransas National
Wildlife Refuge.
   Bruce Thompson, in charge of Texas' non-game and endangered
species program, said as many as 150 whooping cranes are expected
to make the journey this fall from Northwest Territories, Canada,
to Texas. Last year, 132 cranes wintered around the Aransas refuge,
with two others ending up elsewhere in Texas.
   Another flock of about 20 cranes winters in New Mexico and
summers in Idaho, but Thompson said those cranes have not yet
reproduced in the wild. A flock of about 40 is kept in captivity at
the Patuxent Wildlife Refuge in Maryland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
