<HEAD>Quake Leaves 2,000 Homeless, Destroys 500 Structures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake followed by heavy rains
left 2,000 people homeless and destroyed 500 buildings in remote
northwestern Uganda, Radio Uganda reported Monday.
   No casualties were reported in the two-minute temblor that
struck Thursday night near Arua in West Nile province, the
government-run broadcast said. Arua, a rural area 210 miles
northwest of Kampala, is on the western arm of the Great Rift
Valley.
   However, the radio reported some crops and scores of mud hut
homes were destroyed in the two-hour downpour that followed the
earthquake. The station also hard-hit was Pajule, 6 miles west of
Arua and near the Zaire border.
   Radio Uganda did not indicate the severity of the temblor, and
further details were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
