<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina     09-12 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentine Unions Hold 24-hour General Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools, public buildings and
factories closed Monday across Argentina as the 3.5-million-member
organized labor movement held a 24-hour strike.
   The strike, set to end at midnight, was called to protest police
actions at an anti-government rally Friday in front of Government
House in which 113 people, including 37 policemen, were injured.
   Government officials said the police moved in Friday to stop
fighting between rival union groups. Labor leaders denied that and
accused the police of brutality.
   Monday's strike was the 13th organized by the General Labor
Confederation since the elected government of President Raul
Alfonsin was installed in December 1983, ending nearly eight years
of military rule.
   The union federation had rejected a government request to call
off the strike, and Alfonsin's centrist administration pledged over
the weekend to protect anyone who wanted to work Monday.
   No violence was reported.
   Guards were posted at public buildings. Supervisors ran the
subways in Buenos Aires and owners of taxis and inner-city buses
were encouraged to take shifts behind the wheel when most drivers
failed to show up for work.
   The General Labor Confederation, backed by the opposition
Peronist Party, organized last Friday's rally and an 8-hour general
strike to protest Alfonsin's economic policies.
   Inflation registered 440 percent over the last 12 months, with
unemployment and underemployment at a combined 14 percent, near
14-year highs. Real personal incomes have declined for three
straight years.
   The labor federation claims that an anti-inflation plan Alfonsin
implemented last month does not allow workers' wages to keep pace
with increases in the cost of living.
</TEXT>
