<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1807EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     09-12 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mortar Shells Fired at Parliament Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three mortar shells were fired Monday at
the parliament building, deepening the crisis caused by the
stalemate among Christians, Moslems and leftists in selecting a new
president.
   Hours later, House Speaker Hussein Husseini announced that
legislators would be summoned to meet Sept. 22 for another attempt
to elect a successor to Christian President Amin Gemayel.
   Police said there were no casualties from three 60mm mortar
shells that exploded at 6:45 a.m. around the two-story parliament
building, known as Villa Mansour. The building is in the no-man's
land between predominantly Moslem west Beirut and Christian east
Beirut.
   It was the first attack on Villa Mansour in two years.
   Police said one shell hit the entrance of Villa Mansour and the
other two exploded near army and police checkpoints guarding
approaches to the building.
   They said no group claimed responsibility and they did not know
if the attack was linked to the electoral deadlock.
   Right-wing Christians and Moslem and leftist factions backed by
Syria quickly blamed the others for the shelling.
   Legislators had met Aug. 18 in an attempt to elect a successor
to Gemayel, whose six-year term expires Sept. 23, but some
Christians boycotted the session and there was not a quorum,
meaning the selection could not proceed.
   Under the constitution, the president cannot seek a second
consecutive term.
   The boycotting Christians opposed the main candidate,
Syrian-backed former President Suleiman Franjieh, a Maronite
Christian.
   By tradition, Lebanon's president is a Christian, the prime
minister a Sunni Moslem and the speaker of the House a Shiite
Moslem.
   Failure to elect a new president would leave a political vacuum
that many fear could reignite the civil war that has been mostly
dormant for 18 months.
   It could not be determined if Husseini's announcement of a new
electoral session indicated an agreement between Moslems and
Christians on a consensus candidate.
   Husseini said the Sept. 22 session will be held in the old
parliament building, in the Moslem sector's battle-scarred Place de
l'Etoile.
   Legislators have used Villa Mansour for parliamentary sessions
since they were forced out of the Place de l'Etoile in 1976, in the
early days of the civil war.
   Husseini did not say if he changed the venue for the session
because of Monday's mortar attack.
   The Syrians continue to support Franjieh, 78, president from
1970 to 1976.
   Raymond Edde, a Maronite Christian who has been living in
self-imposed exile in Paris since 1976, announced his candidacy
shortly after Husseini set the date for the new session.
   Parliament Secretary Ihsan Abu Khalil said Edde announced his
candidacy in a telephone call to Husseini from Paris.
   Edde, 73, fled to France after three assassination attempts
against him.
   He has been the front-runner among the two dozen presidential
aspirants, including Franjieh, in recent public opinion polls.
   Rightist Christians claim that Franjieh would turn Lebanon into
a Syrian satellite.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000
military personnel in eastern and northern provinces and west and
south Beirut.
   Franjieh's Moslem and leftist backers say the United States and
Israel prevented his election because he advocates an unconditional
withdrawal by the Israelis from their self-designated ``security
zone'' in southern Lebanon.
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982 and established the buffer zone
after withdrawing most of its army in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-EPAResearch     09-12 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPA Research,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Urges EPA to Focus on Preventing Pollution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency must focus
on preventing pollution instead of concentrating on cleaning up
existing problems with an ``end of pipe'' strategy, a report
provided Monday recommended.
   To help carry through such a change, the agency's research
budget should be increased by about $375 million a year _ roughly
doubled _ said a committee of the agency's Science Advisory Board
in the report.
   The study was made available by agency officials Monday after an
article about it appeared in The Boston Globe.
   The committee was responding to a request for advice from EPA
Administrator Lee M. Thomas, who, the report said, ``sensed that
EPA's immediate regulatory needs were driving its research and
development efforts, while longer-term research equally important
to achieving EPA's overall risk reduction goals was being
neglected.''
   Al Alm, former deputy administrator of EPA and chairman of the
high-level advisory committee, said in an interview that Thomas was
correct.
   ``The problem EPA has is it's spending most of its R&D dollars
just putting out legislative fires,'' Alm said, referring to
research and development money. ``One of its major problems is to
look ahead, to anticipate problems.''
   ``Obviously you need technical support for the regulations (but)
... that has driven virtually all the long-term research away,'' he
said.
   The report said that in the 1970s, efforts to control
automobile, industrial and wastewater pollution using ``federally
mandated end-of-pipe controls were sensible, targeted, relatively
efficient and reasonably cost effective.''
   Though cleanups have been predicated on the notion that ``the
polluter pays,'' and those controls will still be important,
strategy must change, the report argued.
   ``For one thing, we are discovering environmental contamination
in our homes _ e.g., radon _ and in the statosphere _ e.g.,
chlorofluorocarbons _ that are not emitted by `pipes' in the
traditional sense,'' the report said.
   For another thing, end-of-pipe control has too often shifted
pollution from one place to another, for example, from water to air
for toxic pollutants removed from sewage streams by aeration
techniques.
   ``Whenever possible, environmental protection efforts first
should be aimed at minimizing the amount of wastes or pollutants
generated. Thus waste reduction at its source _ for example,
through product design changes, industrial process changes or
material substitution _ should be a primary objective,'' the report
said.
   Alm said he believed many businesses would welcome a vigorous
program of ``technology transfer'' led by EPA _ a program to show
them how their processes could be changed to generate less waste.
   ``The private sector has ... an incentive through liability
questions,'' Alm said.
   To help keep the need for long-term research in view, EPA should
convert the position of assistant administrator for research and
development from a presidential appointment to a career job, the
report argued.
   In the 18 years for EPA's existence, no one has held the job for
more than three years, and ``no leader ... has stayed at the agency
long enough to implement a sustained, long-term research
strategy,'' it said.
   Ecological research should get more emphasis, having taken a
back seat to research to support regulations aimed at protecting
human health, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
