<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-American, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Syria Helps Free American Engineer Kidnapped In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throuout to UPDATE with radio report and Syrian source.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American engineer who was kidnapped in
Lebanon overpowered his captors and escaped to Damascus on Monday
with the help of Syrian troops, Lebanon radio and U.S. officials
said.
   A source close to the Foreign Ministry confirmed the American
was delivered to the U.S. Embassy, but he said the engineer was
rescued by Syrian troops who found where he was being held in
Lebanon and overpowered the kidnappers.
   The discrepencies in the reports could not immediately be
reconciled.
   All three reports said the engineer was abducted Sunday by
unidentified gunmen in east Lebanon after he married a Lebanese
woman.
   The U.S. Embassy in Damascus refused to comment on the story,
but officials in Washington identified the engineer as Kenneth
Wells and said he works in Saudi Arabia for Litton Industries.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Wells
was taken captive in Lebanon as he was leaving his wedding
reception. They said his Lebanese bride was detained briefly.
   Wells subdued his abductors after several hours, reached a
Syrian army checkpoint and was escorted to Damascus, where he was
turned over to a U.S. Embassy official, the officials in Washington
said.
   The officials said Wells' mother reportedly lives in Tennessee.
According to one published report, Wells is 25 and his wife, Samia,
is 32. He is said to hold a black belt in karate.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman, who confirmed much of
the account of Wells' experience, expressed gratitude to Syrian
authorities for their assistance. He said the episode underscores
the dangers American citizens face in Lebanon, where nine Americans
are held hostage.
   The Voice of Lebanon, which is run by right-wing Christian
militias, said the bridegroom ``who excels in karate'' subdued
three gunmen, who were armed with automatic rifles, disarmed them
and took refuge at a Syrian army post. The Syrians then drove him
to Damascus, the radio said. The gunmen intercepted the newlyweds a
few hours after the wedding, the radio said.
   The Syrian source, who also demanded anonymity, said Wells
traveled to Lebanon and married Nadia Haydar Sharafeddine, a girl,
whose family lives in Baalbek. He said Wells was kidnapped after
the wedding near his bride's home.
   After a long search, Syrian troops located the couple, freed
them from the gunmen and took them to Damascus, where Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa turned them over to U.S. Charge
d'Affaires John Craig, the source said.
   The Sharafeddines are a well-known Shiite Moslem family in
Baalbek, a stronghold of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is an extremist Shiite group that is
believed to be an umbrella for various factions holding 18 foreign
hostages in Lebanon.
   The hostage held the longest is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
