<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-12 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Dump Heavy Rain On Northern Alabama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell Monday on Alabama and showers and thunderstorms
were scattered over broad sections of the nation.
   An area of strong thunderstorms dumped over 4.5 inches of rain
over sections of northern Alabama. Two inches of rain fell in 30
minutes at Crestwood, near Birmingham, and on the east edge of
Birmingham more than three quarters of an inch of rain fell in 20
minutes.
   Kimberly, Ala., had street flooding and many intersections were
under water after 4.25 inches of rain fell during the morning.
   Sections of the central Rockies and the Intermountain region
west of the central Rockies had their first measurable snowfall of
the season.
   In Colorado, several locations along the Front Range received at
least a half an inch of snow. At elevations above 10,000 feet,
Kenosha Pass had 4 inches of snow, and 10 inches of snow at Mount
Evans closed the road from Echo Lake to the summit of Mount Evans.
   Snow also was reported above 7,000 feet over sections of
southern Utah.
   Early in the day, Utah had high wind with gusts to 77 mph at
Centerville.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the Ohio Valley,
the Tennessee Valley, the lower Mississippi Valley, the western
Gulf Coast and Florida.
   A possible tornado caused some damage near a shopping mall on
the west side of Indianapolis during the afternoon. No injuries
were reported, police said.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered over New Mexico,
eastern Colorado, northern Arizona and south-central Nebraska.
   In the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 2.14 inches of rain fell at
Huntsville, Ala., with 1.93 inches at Chicago's O'Hare airport.
   Missoula, Mont., posted a record low Monday of 28 degrees, and
Pocatello, Idaho, tied its low temperature record for the date of
30.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Laramie and Rawlins, Wyo., to 96 at Altus Air Force
Base, Okla. Monday morning's low in the 48 contiguous states was 23
degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
for Lower Michigan, the lower Great Lakes, sections of the Ohio
Valley and the middle Atlantic Coast states, with showers over New
England and New York state. Scattered showers and thunderstorms
also were forecast over Iowa and northern Missouri, the central
Rockies and the Florida Peninsula, with snow showers at higher
elevations of the central Rockies.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted for sections of the central
Rockies; in the 60s in the northern Rockies, the remainder of the
central Rockies, the middle Missouri Valley, Iowa, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes and northern Maine; in
the 90s from central Texas across the lower Mississippi Valley to
the southern Atlantic Coast, and in the desert Southwest and inland
valleys of California and Oregon; and in the 70s and 80s for the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
