<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0712 09-12 0954</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0712,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pledges `Stealth' Support, Hears Some Boos</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: to UPDATE with adviser's comments and put Dukakis support of
Stealth in perspective, EDITS lede and ADDS new 2nd graf, and
INSERTS two grafs after 6th pvs, Many supporters...in minority,
picking up 7th pvs, Earlier in...foreign trade; EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, trying to
counter Republican attacks on his defense views, made an unusual
pledge of support Monday for the Stealth bomber but ran into boos
from workers at a plant where engines for the airplane are
manufactured.
   A Dukakis adviser said afterward he believed there was no
difference between his position and that of GOP rival George Bush
on the bomber.
   Dukakis visited the large General Electric plant outside
Cincinnati after a stop in Philadelphia where he charged that Bush
was ``unforgivably wrong'' in the Iran-Contra affair and questioned
whether his opponent has ``the steadiness required in the Oval
Office.''
   Beginning a campaign week devoted largely to defense and foreign
policy matters, Dukakis got cheers but also boos and chants of
``Bush, Bush'' from some in the crowd of 1,000 when he spoke inside
the GE plant. He stood in front of military and commercial jet
engines and referred to the Stealth bomber, the radar-evading
aircraft that has been shrouded in secrecy during planning and
early stages of production.
   ``That bomber was started by a Democratic administration; it was
supported by the Democrats in Congress, and it's going to be
completed under my administration,'' said Dukakis, who was
accompanied by Ohio Sen. John Glenn.
   Dukakis' speech was not interrupted by the protesters, thanks in
part to a booming amplification system that allowed him to speak
easily over the shouts.
   Many supporters in the crowd chanted ``Duke, Duke'' to help
drown out the dissenters. Those booing were in a minority.
   Dukakis' unqualified statement of support for the Stealth bomber
appeared to go beyond earlier campaign statements that he supported
continued research of the project. Dukakis issues adviser James
Steinberg said Dukakis was committed to deployment of the aircraft
provided ``it is affordable and it works,'' and said that did not
represent a change in position.
   ``He says we need it and he intends to deploy it,'' Steinberg
said. He asserted ``I don't believe there's a difference'' between
the positions of Bush and Dukakis on the Stealth.
   Earlier in Philadelphia, Dukakis said that as vice president
Bush had produced only failure in combating drugs, cracking down on
international terrorism and dealing with the imbalance in foreign
trade.
   ``In each of these three areas, George Bush has failed,''
Dukakis said. ``No wonder he doesn't want to debate.''
   Bush's representatives agreed to a tentative schedule for two
debates in recent days, half the four meetings Dukakis had sought.
   The Democratic presidential candidate delivered the first of
what is to be three defense and national security addresses this
week to an invited audience of 200 union members and other
supporters in Philadelphia.
   Dukakis has been stung by weeks of criticism from Bush and the
Republicans, who have painted him as weak on defense issues and in
opposition to a range of new weapons systems, including virtually
all proposals for new land-based nuclear weapons. Press secretary
Dayton Duncan said Dukakis' visit to the GE plant was aimed at
showing that Dukakis ``is for the Stealth bomber, despite what his
opponent has said.''
   In his Philadelphia speech, Dukakis continued the tougher, more
aggressive stance against Bush that he first displayed last week in
Texas, although he provided few new specifics about his own
national security views.
   He sharpened his now-familiar attack on Bush for keeping silent
when President Reagan agreed to sell missiles to Iran in exchange
for the release of U.S. hostages in Lebanon.
   ``I don't question George Bush's patriotism, even though these
days he seems to be questioning mine,'' Dukakis said. ``Not for a
minute. But does this man, a man who would encourage the president
of the United States to undermine American interests and prestige
by selling arms to Iran have the judgment and the steadiness
required in the Oval Office?''
   The reference to patriotism was a response to Bush's repeated
digs at Dukakis for vetoing a state bill aimed to requiring public
school teachers to lead their classes in reciting the Pledge of
Allegiance. Dukakis says he was advised the bill was
unconstitutional.
   But Dukakis bungled the patriotism line Monday, saying: ``I
don't question George Bush's terrorism.'' He quickly corrected
himself.
   Dukakis focused his criticism of Bush on three areas he said
were crucial to national security, and heaped scorn on Dan Quayle,
the GOP vice presidential candidate, as unqualifed to oversee the
government's anti-drug efforts as Bush had.
   ``I want to beat our foreign competitors; he (Bush) is willing
to settle for second place,'' Dukakis said. ``I want to crack down
on terrorism; he knuckled under to the Ayatollah. I want a real war
against drugs; his answer to drug kingpins like (Panamanian Gen.
Manuel Antonio) Noriega is J. Danforth Quayle.''
   Dukakis questioned why the Reagan administration proposed sharp
cuts in federal aid to state and local drug agencies while imports
of illicit narcotics were soaring.
   He demanded that Bush explain why the government had friendly
dealings with Noriega, despite allegations the Panamanian leader
was involved in drug trafficking, and accused the administration of
``blocking a congressional investigation into when and why and how
much we paid Noriega.''
   Quayle, campaigning in Michigan, said Dukakis ``obviously
doesn't know what he's talking about.'' He said the Democrat
``quite obviously doesn't believe that tough law enforcement
provides a deterrent,'' and he reiterated the ticket's call for the
death penalty for drug ``kingpins.''
</TEXT>
