<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Cisneros     09-12 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cisneros,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Says He Won't Run For Fifth Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Henry Cisneros, a leading
Hispanic politician who once was considered a potential vice
presidential candidate, said Monday he's been in public service
long enough and won't seek a fifth term.
   ``It's been work and it's been fun. Mostly, it's been the most
engrossing and fulfilling thing I've ever done,'' said Cisneros,
41, whose term expires next spring.
   ``Basically, I've been at it for 14 years _ eight years as mayor
and six as council member. That's a long time to go at full
throttle,'' he said. ``Our country believes that eight years in a
high office should be enough to get a job done.
   ``Presidents serve eight years. Governors serve eight years. And
eight years is a good round number for a mayor, especially this
one,'' he said.
   Democratic presidential candidate Walter Mondale interviewed
Cisneros in 1984 about possibly running on his ticket. Cisneros
also has been mentioned frequently as a possible Cabinet-level
appointee.
   Last year, Cisneros said he would not seek a statewide office
because he wanted to devote time to San Antonio projects and to his
son, John Paul Anthony, who was born with a congenital heart defect
and with stomach abnormalities.
   Earlier this year, Cisneros, a former president of the National
League of Cities, turned down an offer to make a keynote address to
the Democratic National Convention.
   Cisneros, who has met Pope John Paul II and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, was approached earlier this year by several San
Antonio businessmen about the prospect of forming a firm to handle
business investments.
   The mayor's salary is less than $5,000 and Cisneros, with two
adolescent daughters and an ill infant, had supplemented that
income with lectures, columns and speaking engagements.
   Cisneros said he needs a different job because his two daughters
are approaching college age and because the medical expenses for
his son are sure to increase.
   ``Today is a little sad for me. It has to be,'' Cisneros said.
``But I expect to wake up tomorrow morning, ready to make the most
of the next eight months, same pace, same energy, same devotion to
the city until midnight of the day before the next mayor takes
office.''
   During his tenure, the bilingual, charismatic mayor helped
attract numerous conventions and businesses to the city, including
Sea World of Texas, the largest marine life theme park in the world.
   Cisneros, who won his last two elections overwhelmingly, also
helped attract numerous Hispanics to the polls, said Bob
Brischetto, executive director of the Southwest Voter Research
Institute.
   ``He certainly has the charisma to turn out the Hispanic vote,
and I think the city contest without him is going to be a different
contest,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1916EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Africa     09-12 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Africa,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Africa's Economic Plight Worsens, U.N. Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Africa is facing huge debts, lagging food
production and a soaring infant mortality rate despite broad
economic and social reforms, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar said Monday.
   The U.N. chief, speaking at the opening of a two-week review of
the U.N. Africa Recovery Program, gave a grim prognosis for the
continent.
   Among the signs of distress he cited:
   _Infant and child mortality rates are rising, and are projected
to reach 50 million in the period 1985-2000. In every other world
region, infant and child mortality is rapidly decreasing.
   _By the year 2010, Africa's debt will be more than 280 percent
of its total export income.
   _Per capita income on the continent fell 2 percent in 1986 and
2.2 percent in 1987, and today is lower than it was in 1980.
   _Agricultural production improved by 3.8 percent in 1986 but
only 1.1 percent in 1987, despite agricultural policy reforms.
   Perez de Cuellar's report marks the midway point of the
1986-1990 Africa Recovery Program, the result of a special General
Assembly session in May 1986, the first such session to focus on
one continent.
   The program was aimed at helping reverse Africa's economic
decline, but external problems have blocked substantial progress,
Perez de Cuellar said.
   He said three key problems are Africa's depressed export
earnings, the cost of repaying its debt and insufficient financing.
   ``Every day that passes, the debt burden of African countries
becomes even more excruciating,'' said Adebayo Adedeji, U.N.
undersecretary-general.
   Although Africa paid almost $1 billion a year to the
International Monetary Fund in loan costs in 1986 and 1987,
resources fell, exports credit declined and loans from the private
sector were minor, the U.N. chief's report said.
   Africa's debt burden ``has become one of the most important
factors constraining recovery and development on the continent, and
unless urgent action is taken, the situation will worse,'' said
Perez de Cuellar.
   Africa's total external debt is estimated by the U.N. Economic
Commission for Africa at $218 billion by the end of 1987, almost
triple the continent's export earnings.
   A slump in commodity prices has further hurt Africa's economy.
Particulary damaging are the sluggish markets for oil, minerals,
cocoa, coffee, and tea.
   These problems largely canceled out any gain that might have
been produced by the ``courageous and commendable'' sacrifices of
some African governments, such as adopting steep currency
devaluations, cutting budget deficits and an turning over some
public sector functions to the private sector.
   ``In many countries such measures involve social costs and
political risks,'' Perez de Cuellar noted.
   Most African nations have embarked on economic restructuring
programs, about 30 percent of them with the backing of the IMF and
World Bank.
   ``Most countries are giving greater priority to channeling
resources to agriculture, to improving incentives for farmers, to
making provision for food security and to combating drought and
decertification,'' the secretary-general said.
   Perez de Cuellar urged African nations to continue these
restructuring programs, but cautioned them to ensure that ``the
most vulnerable groups in society are protected from adverse
consequences.''
   Donor countries should show their support for these reforms by
increasing their aid, he said.
   Perez de Cuellar called on industrialized nations to reduce
their agricultural subsidies on products competing with African
commodities.
   ``African efforts to pursue and deepen the reform process cannot
be sustained indefinitely in the face of an adverse external
environment and without increased support from the international
community,'' the secretary-general said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran     09-12 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran's Parliament Approves 18 Ministers, Rejects Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Parliament approved 18 ministers
Monday in a vote of confidence for Prime Minister Hussein Musavi's
government, but rejected three, including Revolutionary Guards
Minister Mohsen Rafiqdoust, Tehran Radio said.
   The two-day debate exposed the deep divisions in the Tehran
hierarchy that had largely been masked by the need for unity during
the 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   The veto on Rafiqdoust underscored the anger over disastrous
battlefield defeats suffered by Iran before it abruptly accepted a
year-old United Nations-sponsored cease-fire July 18. These
setbacks had been blamed on the Revolutionary Guards.
   Iran and Iraq began observing a truce Aug. 20 and started
U.N.-mediated peace talks in Geneva five days later.
   The parliamentary debate, which Musavi announced in July, opened
Sunday amid a deepening rift between hardline revolutionaries
demanding economic isolationism and tight state control of the
economy and rivals, such as House Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, who
seek to open up oil-rich Iran in the postwar era.
   Several deputies attacked hardliner Musavi's economic policies,
while radical legislators loyal to the premier defended his
administration.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, gave few details of Monday's
session.
   But the radio said the 11 ministers of the 21-member Cabinet who
were cross-examined by the 270-member Majlis, or parliament,
included Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, Oil Minister
Alireza Aqazadeh, Heavy Industry Minister Behzad Nabavi and
Rafiqdoust.
   Besides Rafiqdoust, Education and Training Minister Kazem Akrami
and Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development Abbas Zali also
received a no-confidence vote.
   Musavi will have to choose three new ministers to replace them.
   The fact that other close allies of Musavi won the vote of
confidence indicated that a head-on clash between radicals and
conservatives over Iran's postwar economic policy has been averted,
at least for now.
   Musavi, prime minister for seven years, warned Sunday that a
vote of no confidence in his Cabinet would seriously hamper Iran's
postwar recovery.
   Musavi, 46, submitted his resignation to President Ali Khamenei
on Sept. 5, saying he believed at least eight of his ministers
faced no-confidence votes.
   Khamenei rejected the resignation and Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, the 88-year-old revolutionary patriarch, publicly rebuked
Musavi for making the surprise move at such a critical juncture
while Iran was negotiating a peace settlement with Iraq.
   Musavi retracted his resignation, but complained of
``difficulties in the decision-making process in the executive,''
an apparent sideswipe at his rivals, Khamenei and Rafsanjani.
   Khomeini's intervention put off any major political crisis in
Iran. But analysts believe the end of the war will bring profound
changes in Iran and that Musavi could be among the political
casualties.
   Musavi reportedly opposed a truce. He opposes allowing foreign
multinationals back into Iran to help with the massive task of
reconstruction. Rafsanjani and Khamenei favor a more moderate
course and ending Iran's self-imposed isolation.
   Khamenei on Monday opened Tehran's 14th international trade
fair, in which 36 countries were participating.
   Some, like France, were taking part for the first time since the
1979 Islamic revolution toppled the late, pro-Western Shah Mohammad
Reza Pahlavi.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, said other foreign participants included the Soviet Union,
Argentina, Australia, Switzerland, West Germany, Ireland, Sweden,
Japan and South Korea.
   IRNA quoted Commerce Minister Abdulhussein Vahaji as stressing
that Iran welcomes foreign technological assistance for
reconstruction projects and said Iran now seeks to expand
commercial links with the rest of the world.
   Some Western analysts have estimated that Iran's postwar
reconstruction could cost $40 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
