<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Crash,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airliner Crashes, All Seven Aboard Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ecuadorean domestic airliner crashed
Monday shortly after taking off from a jungle airport, killing all
seven crew members, the Civil Aviation press office said.
   The agency said the craft, belonging to the domestic airline
TAME, was carrying no passengers when it took off from an airstrip
at Lago Agrio, an oil town in Ecuador's Amazon jungle, 105 miles
northeast of Quito.
   The plane crashed at 2:29 p.m. (3:29 p.m. EDT) and the dead
included three flight attendants, the press office said.
   A press statement said the plane, an Electra with capacity for
97 passengers, was still low in the air when it tipped sideways,
plunged to the ground and burst into flames.
   The plane's destination was Quito, according to the Civil
Aviation office. TAME, a military-run commercial airline, serves
cities within Ecuador.
   It was the second air crash in less than a week in Ecuador. Last
Thursday a bimotor plane slammed into shrimp ponds on Ecuador's
Pacific coast, killing all 10 people aboard.
</TEXT>
