<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     09-12 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Wound Seven Palestinians, Strengthen Security Over New Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded seven
Palestinians in clashes Monday, hospital officials said. The army
bolstered security throughout the occupied lands to head off
violence during the two-day Jewish New Year.
   In Hebron on the West Bank, merchants said they would set up a
militia of about 25 Palestinian guards to replace the city's
Palestinian police officers, most of whom quit on orders from
underground uprising leaders, municipal secretary Hathem Bakri
reported.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, troop gunfire hit three
Palestinian teen-agers, including a 14-year-old boy who was
seriously wounded in the abdomen, acording to hospital officials.
   In the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya and Shati refugee camps, troops
fired on stone-throwing youths, wounding four, other hospital
officials reported.
   The army confirmed one casualty and said it was checking the
others.
   Elsewhere, youths blockaded streets in Gaza City, set tires
ablaze and hurled stones at Israeli settlers' cars, witnesses said.
   At least 264 Palestinians and six Israelis have died since
violence began on Dec. 8 in lands Israel seized from Jordan and
Egypt in the 1967 Mideast war.
   The army freed 75 Palestinians jailed without trial in a Negev
desert prison camp. An army spokesman said it was a humanitarian
gesture on the occasion of Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year.
   That brought to 150 the number of Palestinians freed over the
holiday, which began at sundown Sunday and lasts through sundown
Tuesday.
   About 2,500 Palestinians are jailed without trial at the desert
tent prison at Ketziot, about five miles from the Egyptian border.
   Bakri said Hebron's new Palestinian guard was the first of its
kind to be set up in the occupied territories and would be financed
by Hebron business people, many of whom suffered break-ins after
most city policemen resigned.
   ``The purpose is to guard markets and businesses because there
have been a lot of robberies, costing merchants hundreds of
thousands of dollars. We need such a body and it was formed on
popular demand,'' Bakri said in an interview.
   He said the guards would carry knives, clubs and walkie-talkies,
but that Israeli authorities would not let them carry guns.
   Uprising leaders have ordered all Palestinians who work for the
Israeli military government in the occupied territories, including
police, to quit their jobs.
   The army reinforced patrols and set up checkpoints on main
highways throughout the occupied lands.
   Troops searched Palestinian cars at roadblocks outside Jericho
and the Kalandia refugee camp in the West Bank. Police spokesman
Rafi Levy reported extra troops deployed in Arab areas of
Jerusalem, but said no clashes occurred.
   In one incident, a Jewish settler fired in the air after his
vehicle was stoned in Gaza City, but no one was injured, witnesses
said.
   Dozens of supporters of the left-wing Progressive List for
Peace, a mixed Arab-Jewish party that holds two seats in the
120-member Israeli parliament, demonstrated outside the northern
West Bank town of Qalqilya to protest last week's army raid in
which more than 200 Palestinian activists were arrested.
   Demonstrators carried placards calling on soldiers to refuse
service in the occupied lands, Israel television said.
   Secular Israelis meanwhile gathered throughout Israel for
picnics in beaches and backyards Monday to mark the Jewish New
Year, while observant Jews symbolically cast off their sins by
throwing the contents of their pockets into springs and streams.
   Mainly because of the Palestinian uprising, police deployed
thousands of officers in Israeli cities and urged residents to be
on the lookout for suspicious objects.
   At the Ein Gedi nature reserve, attendance was down markedly
from last year, apparently because many Israelis shied away from
the swing through the West Bank necessary to reach the Dead Sea.
   But hotels in the northern port city of Haifa were fully booked,
and 120,000 visitors were expected at the nearby Carmel Park over
the holiday.
   Tens of thousands of Israelis flocked to synagogues to listen to
rams' horns, or ``shofars,'' heralding the new year 5749. Rosh
Hashana is both a joyous and solemn holiday during which Jews begin
a 10-day period of atonement for sins of the previous year.
   Most shops and restaurants were closed, all public transporation
was halted, and the normally bustling centers of Tel Aviv and
Jerusalem were deserted.
</TEXT>
