<2ND_LINE>AM-F-14 Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0665,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Injured When Unmanned Jet Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with authorities now saying five injured,
adds identities and conditions, background and details.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos GO1, GO3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL CAJON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An F-14 fighter jet crashed upside down
into a hangar at a suburban airfield Monday and exploded after two
crewmen ejected. The fliers and three people on the ground were
injured, officals said.
   ``It just dropped,'' eyewitness Glenn Janes said of the plane.
``It was a sea of flame after that. ... But I didn't hear any
screams for help.''
   The jet from Miramar Naval Air Station in San Diego crashed into
the hangar at Gillespie Field on the northern edge of El Cajon, 15
miles east of downtown San Diego, officials said.
   The blaze destroyed the hangar and an attached extension, but
spared a nearby restaurant. At least six cars and three or four
planes parked on the ground were burned.
   The $35 million F-14, the fighter jet glamorized in the movie
``Top Gun,'' experienced mechanical problems and the two crewmen
tried to guide it to the runway at Gillespie before bailing out,
Navy and civilian police officials said.
   The jet did not carry any ordnance, they said.
   ``The pilot was trying to get it to hit the airport runway,''
steering clear of the residential and business areas surrounding
the airfield, El Cajon police Lt. Bill McClurg said.
   The Navy crewmen and three people in or near the hangar were
injured, McClurg said.
   Lt. j.g. Randall L. Furtado was listed in critical condition at
Sharp Memorial Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Laurie Pooley.
Another victim, William Grant, also was in critical condition, she
said.
   Lt. Cmdr. Jim Barnett, the pilot, was in stable condition at
Mercy Hospital with bruises and fractures, a hospital spokeswoman
said.
   Brian Jollis, a 40-year-old helicopter mechanic, was listed in
critical condition with burns over 35 percent of his body, said
Sheri Smith, a spokeswoman at UC San Diego Medical Center. A second
person hospitalized at UCSD, Bill Eulrich, 39, suffered smoke
inhalation and was listed in fair condition, Smith said.
   The pilots were returning to Miramar after a training mission
when they reported problems with the hydraulic system, which
controls the plane's flaps and other stabilizing equipment, said
Capt. Gary Hughes, commanding officer of NAS Miramar.
</TEXT>
