<DOCNO> AP880912-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0751 09-12 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0751,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede SECAUCUS, N.J.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Disputes McCarthyism Claim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with comments on McCarthyism allegation,
ethnic coalition dismissals; and statement from Dukakis aide.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, trying to turn back charges of
``McCarthyism,'' scorned presidential rival Michael Dukakis anew
Monday as a liberal Democrat and ``a card-carrying member'' of the
American Civil Liberties Union.
   Bush did not did not directly answer Dukakis' charge that
Republicans were attacking his patriotism, using the tactics of the
late-Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy.
   Speaking to a crowd of several thousand people at a shopping
center rally, Bush said: ``Recently, the governor of Massachusetts
accused me of McCarthyism.
   ``And it was suggested that when I said he is a card-carrying
member of the ACLU that that was McCarthyism; when I say he's a
liberal, that it's unfair.''
   ``No, he's that (Dukakis a member of the ACLU),'' Bush said.
``He says's he's that. He's that. I am the vice president of the
United States of America, a partner in (the) administration that
has turned this economy around, that has put America back to work,
that has strengthened our national security and that has enhanced
the peace.''
   Bush made no mention at the rally that five more members of an
ethnic coalition supporting his campaign had resigned under fire.
   However, Bush told reporters: ``Nobody's giving in. These people
left of their own volition. We're not accusing anybody of anything.
   ``We're getting into a very peculiar deal where some people are
accusing people. I don't like it a bit.''
   Earlier, in New Jersey, Bush challenged his opponent to say
whether he supported the Reagan administration on military issues
ranging from the American invasion of Grenada to the U.S. attack
against Moammar Gadhafi's Libya.
   ``If my opponent can't answer yes to all these important
questions, then I would submit to you that he has veered outside
the bipartisan mainstream, the vital consensus that has been at the
heart of America's national security for many, many years,'' Bush
said.
   On the other hand, Bush said, if Dukakis should answer ``yes''
then ``the people are entitled to know why he flip-flopped. And,
perhaps most important of all, how will we know he won't change his
positions again.''
   Returning to the campaign trail after a weekend in Washington,
Bush hammered Dukakis on defense and economic issues while courting
Cuban-American votes in New Jersey.
   ``I have just been told that my opponent is ending his so-called
`Stealth' candidacy,'' Bush said, quoting his own description of
Dukakis' campaign. He commented during a tour of Goya Foods, which
bills itself as the nation's largest privately owned Hispanic firm.
   Bush asked if Dukakis still regarded the Strategic Defense
Initiative as a fantasy, as he once said, and whether Dukakis was
willing to admit ``that your support for a nuclear freeze was a
mistake.''
   Before touring the plant in Secaucus, Bush raised some of the
same questions in a Union City, N.J., speech before a flag-waving
Cuban-American audience of upwards of 1,000 people.
   Beginning the day, Bush announced formation of a national
security advisory task force whose 13 members include former
Secretaries of State Henry A. Kissinger and Alexander M. Haig,
former Defense Secretaries Melvin Laird and Donald Rumsfeld, and
Zbigniew Brzezinski, who was national security adviser to Jimmy
Carter.
   Brzezinski, joining Bush at a Washington news conference, said
that of the two candidates for president, Bush ``is not a novice in
that critical area of public policy on which our national survival
depends.''
   Bush told his Cuban-American audience: ``I take great personal
pride in the fact that three of my grandchildren are half Mexican,
are Hispanic. You see, my family is doubly blessed. We have both
cultures in my family.''
   Referring to the invasion of Grenada, which at the time was
strengthening its ties with Cuba, and the bombing of Libya, Bush
said:
   ``And I will really admit that I am having trouble pinning down
the liberal governor of Massachusetts on his defense. He's all over
the field. So my question of the day: Does he support the attack on
Gadhafi that has resulted in less international terror and does he
support the attack on Grenada that has given those people the
freedom and democracy that sometimes we take for granted?''
   Dukakis foreign policy adviser James Steinberg said Dukakis
supported the invasion of Grenada for the purpose of rescuing
students, if their lives were threatened. He said the Reagan
administration's motivation to invade was ``clearly more than'' a
desire to rescue the students.
   Steinberg said ``there was legitimate basis for taking some
action against Libya,'' including action against terrorist camps,
but not bombing the tent where Gadhafi was believed to be. ``What
he does not support is the targeting of a head of state,''
Steinberg said.
</TEXT>
