<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru a0720 09-12 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Injures Eight in Belfast</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New info grafs 1-10 UPDATING with news agency saying IRA
responsible for taxi bombing; bomb defused in Armagh; Thatcher
statement. PICK up 7th pvs bgng: The taxi bombing ... ; ADDS two
grafs on British-Irish meeting.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge bomb placed in a taxi
blew up outside City Hall on Monday, injuring eight people who did
not have enough time to flee after a telephoned warning, police
said.
   Earlier Monday, two bombs set by guerrillas of the Irish
Republican Army badly damaged the home of Sir Kenneth Bloomfield,
head of Northern Ireland's civil service. Bloomfield, 57, his wife
and a son were not injured but were treated for shock.
   The blasts ripped holes in the brick house and shattered windows
in neary homes.
   A third bomb near the house was defused by British army experts,
police said.
   Police said that in Armagh, 35 miles southwest of Belfast,
demolitions experts defused a 500-pound bomb found near the
Drumsill Hotel.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said the IRA
claimed responsibility for the blast outside City Hall that
shattered shop and office windows over a large area of downtown
Belfast. The agency did not say how it obtained its information on
the claim of responsibility.
   Police said two of the injured were in serious condition.
   The outlawed IRA had carried out a car bombing on Aug. 24 only
150 yards from the site of Monday's blast. Last month's explosion
caused more than $6.75 million in damage.
   In a statement, the IRA claimed responsibility for the
Bloomfield house attack in Helen's Bay, County Down, on the eastern
outskirts of Belfast, and said other civil servants in Northern
Ireland should resign their posts.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, in Perth Scotland,
said, ``This is the first time we have had a direct bomb attack on
civil servants working in the Northern Ireland Office and it is a
matter of great concern to us. It just shows the IRA are now after
civilians.''
   The taxi bombing stirred concern that the IRA might be returning
to the ``commercial war'' of the 1970s that devastated the city
center. The mainly Roman Catholic organization is fighting to drive
the British from the Protestant-majority province and unite it with
the Catholic Irish Republic.
   The bomb went off between two office buildings in Donegall
Square, about 70 yards from City Hall. It was planted inside a
black taxi parked in a cab rank.
   A police spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
practice, said that 11 minutes before the explosion a telephoned
warning was made to the Irish News newspaper. The spokesman said it
was very short warning time.
   Forty bus drivers were taking their break in a nearby cafeteria
minutes before the bomb went off.
   ``A policeman ran in and shouted that a bomb had been planted
outside,'' said a driver, who refused to give his name. ``Most of
us managed to get away but some of my colleagues were hit by flying
glass.''
   A second driver, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said
he had parked his bus and the passengers got off seconds before the
bomb exploded.
   ``I saw at least three drivers stagger up the road injured from
flying glass. One of them looked in quite a bad way and they were
all suffering from shock,'' he said.
   ``All I can remember is the force of the blast ... I have heard
explosions before but this one sounded like a really big one,'' he
said.
   Police swiftly sealed off the area to keep hundreds of people
still leaving their offices from getting near the site, as
shattered windows continued to drop shards of glass onto the
sidewalks.
   British and Irish officials are scheduled to meet Tuesday under
terms of the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement that give the Irish
government a consultative role in the British province.
   The meeting was requested by Irish Prime Minister Charles
Haughey to discuss the worsening security situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
