<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti 2ndLd-Writethru   09-12 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0748,0950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Leader Says Church Massacre Return To Duvalier Era</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with six claiming participation
in massacre; PICKS up 8th pvs: `This act...' Minor editing
throughout to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Six people claimed in a radio
broadcast Monday that they took part in a massacre at a Roman
Catholic church that left at least five dead and 77 wounded, and
warned that the slaughter ``was child's play.''
   The five men and one woman later appeared on Tele-Haiti, the
country's only private television station. In both broadcasts the
six said the bloody attack Sunday was aimed at Rev. Jean-Bertrand
Aristide, the church pastor and a critic of the military government.
   One of the men said in the Radio Metropole interview, broadcast
Monday evening, that ``the people committed the massacre.
   ``We were after Father Aristide; what you saw yesterday was
child's play. In whatever parish Father Aristide is accepted, a
heap of corpses will attend that Mass,'' the man said.
   None of the six was identified.
   Richard Widmaier, manager of Radio Metropole, said the group
came to the station Monday afternoon and claimed participation in
the massacre at the church and the stoning later Sunday of two
other radio stations and the headquarters of two opposition leaders.
   During the television appearance, one of the men said the
slaughter at St. Jean Bosco Church was motivated by an internal
struggle between Aristide and another priest, but they did not
elaborate.
   Two dozen men with guns and machetes burst into the church
during a morning Mass in the La Saline slum and shot, stabbed and
slashed terrified parishioners, witnesses said.
   Witnesses said at least a dozen people were killed. Aristide
escaped unhurt and went into hiding.
   Doctors at the general hospital of the state university reported
five bodies were in the hospital morgue and 77 parishioners were
hospitalized.
   Among those injured were a woman and her infant _ both skewered
by the same steel pike while the baby girl was in her mother's
womb. An operation saved mother and child.
   Franck Romain, mayor of Port-au-Prince, said Aristide was
``justly punished.''
   But Arnold Antonin, head of the National Network for the Defense
of Human Rights, compared it to attacks on civilians that occurred
during the rule of dictator Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier and his
son, Jean-Claude.
   ``This act is unprecedented in our history,'' Antonin said.
``Even Papa Doc did not dare do such a thing _ penetrate the holy
precincts of a church and, after massacring unarmed worshipers,
burn it down.''
   Dr. Gerard Blot, who took part in surgery that saved the baby
and mother, told Radio Haiti-Inter the sharpened metal rod
penetrated the woman below the heart and wounded the baby.
   He said 10 others required emergency surgery, one for a bullet
wound and nine who were stabbed by skewers, a common homemade
weapon in Haiti.
   The rest suffered from various injuries, having been shot,
bludgeoned, trampled or slashed.
   Witnesses speaking on condition of anonymity said Monday they
spotted Port-au-Prince city hall employees among the assailants,
but did not identify them. Witnesses said police and soldiers
watched the attack but did nothing to stop it.
   Romain, a former army colonel and police chief during the
29-year Duvalier era, denied the charge.
   ``If (city) employees were involved ... I don't see how I am
concerned ... I am not an anarchist, I am not someone who preaches
violence and who sends people out to die as Aristide has always
done,'' Romain said.
   ``Father Aristide has always preached violence ... He who sows
the wind, reaps the storm,'' Radio Metropole quoted Romain as
saying.
   Aristide, one of the most popular figures among the poor masses
in this Caribbean nation, regularly has preached against army
atrocities and has led his supporters in street demonstrations.
   Aristide has been the target of several assassination attempts
since Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy came to power as head of a three-man
junta on Feb. 7, 1986, the day Jean-Claude Duvalier fled into exile
in France.
   Romain, Port-au-Prince mayor until Duvalier's ouster, returned
to that office in army-run elections in January and remained after
Namphy ousted civilian President Leslie Manigat in a military coup
in June. Namphy was head of the military under the Duvalier regime.
   The mayor was a member of a firing squad in the Nov. 12, 1964,
execution of two survivors of ``Young Haiti,'' a group of
U.S.-based anti-Duvalier activists who invaded the country. Romain
personally shot and killed two group members.
   ``On Sunday, (the forces of law and order) stood by ... and let
a massacre take place,'' Antonin said. The radio reports said
police and soldiers looked on from an army compound across the
street as 300 assailants stoned the church.
   A smaller group of men armed with machetes, sticks and guns then
entered the church and began attacking worshipers.
   In Washington, State Department spokeman Charles Redman
condemned the police behavior.
   ``In spite of the fact that all of these attacks occurred in
close proximity to various police and military installations, no
actions were taken by the competent authorites to intervene while
the attack were taking place,'' Redman said Monday.
   Manigat, who lives in the United States, denounced the incident
as the work of Namphy's secret police.
   ``Brute force is the principal instrument of those who now
control the country,'' Manigat said from his home in Maryland. ``It
is the same killers of the Duvalier time organizing the new
terror.''
</TEXT>
