<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay-Stroessner     09-12 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay-Stroessner,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Returns To Work, Quieting Illness Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Stroessner returned
to his desk Monday, ending a 12-day absence that generated a wave
of rumors that he had undergone surgery and was gravely ill.
   Gen. Stroessner, 75, was undergoing a complete medical
examination in preparation for an October visit to Taiwan, said
Juan Jose Benitez Rickmann, undersecretary for information, in
explaining the president's unusual absence.
   Stroessner, who has ruled this South American nation of 3.8
million inhabitants since a 1954 coup, arrived at the Presidential
Palace at 10 a.m. and met with his ministers for the interior,
foreign relations, industry and treasury, Benitez Rickmann told The
Associated Press.
   The president's absence sparked a rumor, circulating initially
in diplomatic circles, that he had undergone prostrate surgery on
Aug. 31 at Asuncion's Social Security Hospital. Hospital officials
refused to comment on the rumor.
   Other rumors indicated that Stroessner was gravely ill. A
Mendoza, Argentina radio station interrupted programming on
Saturday to report, without citing the source of its information,
that the president had died. Benitez Rickmann described the report
as ``false and irresponsible.''
</TEXT>
