<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Philippines     09-12 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Philippines,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manglapus Meeting U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippines Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus,
that country's chief negotiator in deadlocked negotiations over the
future of strategic U.S. bases in the islands, is to meet here
Tuesday with senior Reagan administration officials.
   State Department and Philippine Embassy officials said
Manglapus, who arrived in the United States during the weekend,
would talk with Gaston Sigur, assistant secretary of state for
Asian and Pacific affairs, followed by meetings with Secretary of
State George Shultz, Deputy Secretary John C. Whitehead and Defense
Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   On Wednesday, Manglapus was scheduled to open a series of talks
with congressional leaders, and on Friday he was to speak at a
meeting in the State Department of the U.S.-Asia Institute.
   Proposed payments of hundreds of millions of dollars a year
separated the two governments when Manglapus in late July suspended
an ongoing review in Manila of future U.S. use of Clark Field air
base, Subic Bay naval station and four smaller installations in the
Philippines.
   A report from Manila said the Philippines had insisted on a $1.2
billion annual U.S. payment for use of the bases after the current
agreement expires in 1991. Various reports said the United States,
now paying about $180 million a year, offered substantial increases
that, however, fell far below the reported demand.
   U.S. officials also continued to object to describing U.S. aid
payments to the Philippines as compensation or rent for the bases,
maintaining the arrangement was part of a defense package with many
mutual advantages. They also said the breakoff of the talks was
temporary. The Philippines side called it an indefinite breakoff
because of what Manglapus described as an inflexible U.S. position.
   Manglapus became well known in Washington when he lived here in
exile during the administration of ousted President Ferdinand
Marcos before returning to Manila to join President Corazon
Aquino's government. He planned to attend the U.N. General Assembly
starting next week and to meet again with Shultz on Sept. 30 in New
York, the State Department said.
</TEXT>
