<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DropoutPayoffs     09-12 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dropout Payoffs,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial School Dropout Program Revised</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE SILVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial program that paid
potential dropouts to go to class has been revised this year
because of negative attention it generated, school officials said
Monday.
   Red Bank High School received national attention last year when
it began paying problem students $5 a day, or $25 a week, to attend
classes regularly, be punctual, do their homework and behave
themselves.
   ``It was picked up by the media as `Oh, my God, you're paying
kids to go to school,''' said Principal Robert Nogueira. He said
the concept was viewed as ``almost un-American.''
   Critics said the program was unfair because it paid some
students to achieve what were minimal requirements for the rest,
and violated the ideal of education being an end in itself.
   Officials denied the students were being paid to study. Instead,
they said they were getting ``needs-based'' subsidies for improving
their academic performance and changing their behavior.
   National television crews came to the school, students were
interviewed on the radio and newspapers reported on the program.
   ``There seemed to be a lot of hoopla going on about how we were
doing it,'' said Robert Lock, a work placement coordinator at the
school who helped draft this year's program. ``The attention being
paid to it was taking away from our time rather than being with the
young people.''
   This year potential dropouts will be paid $4 a day for attending
a one-hour program outside regular class hours, school officials
said.
   During the hour, which may be before or after classes, they will
receive tutoring and help with homework, get counseling on their
attitude toward school, and prepare for the state high school
proficiency tests. The test is required in New Jersey to receive a
diploma.
   ``This is fairer because the student has to come in the hour
before or the hour after school, which is a good commitment to
make,'' Lock said. ``We think it will accomplish similar goals but
not attract the type of attention the other (program) seemed to
attract.''
   Students will be required to complete the program requirements
five days in a row to receive the all-or-nothing weekly payment.
   The revised program will be trimmed back considerably, with the
budget slashed from $108,000 to $50,000, Nogueira said. The funding
comes from a federal grant under the Job Training and Partnership
Act.
   Nogueira said less money was budgeted because not all those
eligible can be persuaded to participate. Last year, for example,
only 48 of 130 targeted students took part.
   An analysis also found the program is not appropriate for
students with especially high absentee rates or disciplinary
problems, Lock said.
   Despite the controversy, officials said the program was a
success. At the end of the school year, 70 percent of the 48
participants had passed the high school proficiency test.
   ``We're not suggesting this is the way for everyone to go but we
do know financial incentives are part of our culture,'' Nogueira
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
