<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-McFarland     09-12 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-McFarland,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychologist, Consultant To `Mister Rogers' Show Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORGAN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret B. McFarland, the child psychologist
children's television show host Fred Rogers described as ``the most
major influence in my professional life,'' died Monday after a long
illness. She was 83.
   Highly regarded and recognized in the fields of child
development, education and psychology, Miss McFarland co-founded
the Arsenal Family and Children's Center with Dr. Benjamin Spock
and Erik Erikson in 1953 and served as its director until 1971.
   She helped establish the department of child development and
child care within the psychiatry department of University of
Pittsburgh's School of Medicine in the early 1950s.
   ``She was so other-directed that when you were in her presence
you felt you were important,'' said Rogers, host of ``Mister
Rogers' Neighborhood.'' The show is produced at WQED-TV, a
Pittsburgh public television station.
   Miss McFarland earned master's and doctorate degrees at Columbia
University in 1928 and 1938. She was an associate professor of
psychology in Columbia's psychiatry department from 1951 through
1975 and became associate professor emeritus in 1976. The
department is now part of the university's school of social work.
   She later became a consultant for Rogers' television show,
reviewing scripts and song lyrics.
</TEXT>
