<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Cuba 1stLd-Writethru a0742 09-12 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Cuba, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Expels Cuban Ambassador, Embassy Third Secretary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with news reports that Cuban feared
assassination squad, one person wounded. PICK up 3rd pvs: Foreign
Office Minister.... INSERTS 6 grafs after 16th pvs, `On arrival at
...' with more details from media reports of incident. Pick up 17th
pvs: Britain has strict...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Monday ordered Cuba's ambassador and
third secretary to leave the country because of a shooting incident
involving the junior diplomat, the Foreign Ministry announced.
   No casualties were reported officially and police gave few
details about gunshots at a building in central London and the
arrest of Third Secretary Carlos Manuel Medina Perez.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, quoted a
witness as saying one person, who was not identified, was wounded.
   The Daily Mail said Medina Perez opened fire because he believed
he was being trailed by an assassination squad. It did not give
attribution for its report.
   Foreign Office Minister Timothy Eggar told Cuban Ambassador
Oscar Fernandez-Mell that he and Medina Perez must leave Britain by
midnight Tuesday.
   A Vietnamese diplomat left Britain Sunday, expelled for
brandishing a handgun during a demonstration earlier this month by
refugees outside the Vietnamese Embassy.
   Britain moved quickly against the Cubans.
   A Foreign Office statement said: ``We understand from the police
that at about 4:30 p.m. (11:30 a.m. EDT) today (Monday) an incident
occurred in Sussex Gardens, London, W2, when a number of shots were
fired by a man subsequently identified as a third secretary at the
Cuban Embassy.
   ``Senor Perez has indicated to the police that he fired the
shots fearing for his own safety.''
   The statement reported ``Mr. Eggar said that this incident could
not under any circumstances be justified. The British government
would not tolerate the use of firearms by diplomats. Mr. Eggar said
that the ambassador must bear the responsibility for this grave
development.
   ``The only appropriate response was that he must insist that the
ambassador and Senor Perez should leave the United Kingdom as soon
as possible, but at the latest by midnight tomorrow.''
   Fernandez-Mell, summoned to the Foreign Office by Eggar, said
before going into the meeting, ``I don't know what happened. There
was some trouble in the hall of a man's house. Some men attacked
him (Medina Perez). But I don't know anything about a gun. It was
just a little problem.''
   The ambassador made no comment when he left after a 20-minute
meeting.
   Eggar, speaking to reporters later, said he told the ambassador
``behavior of the kind that went on this afternoon was simply not
acceptable.''
   Police headquarters at Scotland Yard made only a brief report.
   It said police were summoned when there were reports of shots
being fired and when they arrived, ``a foreign male surrendered
himself and a gun and he was immediately arrested.
   ``It is alleged he fired a number of rounds at persons nearby
who immediately dispersed.''
   ``On arrival at Paddington Green police station the man claimed
he was entitled to full diplomatic privilege and once this was
established he was released,'' the police report said.
   Press Association and the Daily Mail gave these accounts:
   The newspaper said Medina Perez drew a gun as he stepped from
his car outside a building where the Cuban Embassy has an apartment
in Sussex Gardens, believing men in another auto were about to open
fire.
   ``He fired at the group, who were thought to be Arab or
Hispanic,'' the Daily Mail said. ``The men scattered and the envoy
fired at one as he ran near a passing bus .... The men escaped and
the Cuban fled into the block of flats (apartments) ... and
barricaded himself in the official ... apartment.''
   It said a Diplomatic Protection Squad arrived from Scotland Yard
and cordoned off the area.
   Two police officers negotiated with the Cuban diplomat from an
adjacent balcony and used a mirror on a pole to look into the
apartment to see if any other gunmen were inside, according to the
Daily Mail.
   Press Association said Medina Perez fired up to five shots at a
car containing four people. It quoted an unidentified witness as
saying she saw the four run away, with one holding a blood-soaked
handkerchief to his head.
   Britain has strict gun laws and most police officers do not
carry firearms.
   The issue of diplomats possessing weapons became extremely
sensitive after the killing of a policewoman by a gunman firing
from inside the Libyan Embassy during a protest demonstration
outside the embassy in April 1984. After a police siege, the
embassy was closed and diplomatic relations with Libya were severed.
   Vietnamese Third Secretary Khang Than Nhan was expelled and left
Sunday after he was accused of brandishing a gun during a
demonstration by Vietnamese refugees at the Vietnamese Embassy on
Sept. 4.
   The Vietnamese ambassador first turned over a toy gun, the
Foreign Office said, but later returned with a real gun and
apologized for the incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
