<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--DiamondMurder ADV25-2Takes   09-12 0942</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Diamond Murder, ADV 25-2 Takes,0963</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note Sept. 26 trial date in 33rd graf, ``The Rivaltas .. .,''
which is 11th graf of first add.</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ Stringent security on the one hand and a trusting
openness on the other mark the dealing in New York's exotic Diamond
District. Barbara Mangiameli was an outsider who proved remarkably
successful in that environment _ until that day when she was
murdered and the $500,000 in diamonds she had been carrying
disappeared. It's a story worthy of a movie plot.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Manhattan's tradition-bound Diamond District,
Barbara Mangiameli was different _ a young Italian-American
Catholic woman in an industry dominated by Jewish men, an outsider
who went to school for the expertise more often passed down through
families.
   But it is not Barbara Mangiameli's success in the diamond
business that its denizens will remember.
   Mangiameli, 33, disappeared Feb. 4 along with more than $500,000
in diamonds, the day after a proposed sale fell through. In June,
her body was found in the Hudson River; she had been bludgeoned to
death. Only one of the six missing jewels has been recovered.
   ``She was just an innocent victim,'' says Laura Hruska,
executive director of the Diamond & Jewelry Association Inc. ``The
lesson that has to be learned from this is that ... you have to
take care of yourself, you have to take every precaution.''
   Aside from Mangiameli's death, there have been three other
murders this year in the block of midtown bounded by 46th and 47th
streets and Fifth and Sixth avenues, which is the Diamond
District's heart. That's high for a business area, says a detective.
   A walk down 47th Street, where gold-filled windows front onto
rooms crowded with jewelry-laden counters, suggests the business's
inherent risk: Gems are easily portable, readily negotiable, highly
valuable things. Danger, says one dealer, is ``an occupational
hazard.''
   But some say something is wrong when a young, relatively
inexperienced, unprotected woman is allowed to carry half a million
dollars worth of jewels to an unknown prospective buyer. As is
customary in the industry, Mangiameli only had to sign memos to
receive the diamonds on consignment from a broker with whom she'd
done business before.
   ``This was an enormous deal and way beyond Barbara's league,''
says Debra Shapiro, Mangiameli's friend from childhood. ``If things
aren't changed it can happen again and it will happen again.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Born in Brooklyn and raised on Long Island, Mangiameli earned a
two-year associate's degree in business and went to work in
advertising for more than seven years. Slim, athletic, with long
dark brown hair, she is remembered by friends and associates as
sincere, kind, family-oriented.
   In 1986, she decided to go into the jewelry business.
   ``She was always interested in things like archaeology and gems
and stones and physics,'' Shapiro says.
   Mangiameli started out selling what are called ``findings'' _
jewelry parts and raw metal. When her interest turned to diamonds
she entered the Gemological Institute of America in June 1987, to
learn what are known in the trade as the four C's _ color, clarity,
carat weight and cut. She emerged an accredited expert in the
quality of diamonds and other precious stones.
   She had met a broker, Charles Fischler, who says he became her
``mentor in the diamond business.'' He describes her as a woman of
``simple elegance,'' one who wore little makeup or jewelry. Her
eye, he says, was on the top.
   If so, she was in the right place: Last year, 80 percent of the
$3.4 billion in non-industrial diamonds that entered the United
States came into New York.
   Much of the actual diamond dealing is conducted in secure
offices or in bourses like the Diamond Dealers Club on West 47th
Street. There, amid high-tech security and state-of-the-art
business conveniences backed by three computer systems, men in long
beards lean across narrow tables littered with pieces of white
waxed paper. Tweezers in hand and loupe to eye, they trade tiny
crystals potentially worth millions of dollars.
   It is a business based in trust. Deals are sealed and stones
change hands on just a handshake and the words ``mazel and brucha''
_ Yiddish for ``luck and blessing.'' A date of payment is agreed
upon, a memo is signed. Should one side renege, the dispute goes to
the club's arbitration.
   Though she started out in sales, and earned money doing
free-lance deals during and after her student days, Mangiameli
apparently decided she did not belong in this part of the industry.
When she disappeared, she had worked several times on a free-lance
basis verifying gems at Christie's, the auctioneers. She was also
interviewing for a full-time job in diamond merchandising at
Tiffany & Co.
   The women who do make their living dealing in the Diamond
District know well the rules of this exotic world, where some very
Orthodox men will put a stone on the counter for them to pick up,
rather than risk touching a woman to whom they aren't married.
   They are also well acquainted with its dangers.
   Barbara Laufer Shapiro, 35, runs the retail and wholesale
jewelry exchange started by her father. Two years ago, her husband,
Henry, 35, left the store to meet someone who owed him money. He
was carrying about $6,000 worth of jewelry, his wife said.
   Henry Shapiro's body was found in February 1987, in a Queens
swamp. He had been shot four times, in the head and chest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--DiamondMurder ADV25-1stAdd   09-12 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Diamond Murder, ADV 25-1st Add,0913</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: and chest.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   For most of Barbara Mangiameli's short time in the business, she
was not confronted by the dangers. While in school, she began to do
free-lance sales, first of finished jewelry, later of actual gems.
   As time went on, Fischler said, she began to ask for larger and
more important stones for clients. She continued to free-lance
after graduating in December, and on Feb. 1, Fischler says,
Mangiameli called and said she had a prospective buyer for
investment-quality diamonds.
   At about 5:30 p.m. on Feb. 3, Fischler says, he put Mangiameli
in a taxi. She was to deliver an engagement ring to a customer at 6
p.m. and then meet a diplomat from a Third World nation who was
supposedly interested in the diamonds.
   The meeting had been arranged through two Italian brothers who
were friends of Mangiameli's. Fischler says she didn't seem overly
excited. He had given her stones worth as much as $250,000 before.
   When he'd heard nothing by midnight, Fischler said, he called
Mangiameli's apartment and she told him the meeting had been
canceled at the last minute. Fischler and Mangiameli agreed to meet
at noon the next day, when she would return the diamonds and hand
over $3,500 from the sale of the engagement ring.
   She called an associate of the broker's around 11:30 a.m. and
said she was on her way. She was last reported seen shortly after
noon in the vestibule of her Upper East Side building.
   No one has been charged in Mangiameli's death or the theft of
the diamonds.
   But authorities say the brothers, Fausto and Raoul Rivalta, were
arrested on April 11 and charged with interstate transportation of
stolen property _ one of the stones _ and are suspects in
Mangiameli's disappearance.
   When Mangiameli's body was found June 9, the medical examiner's
office said she had not been dead for very long, ``certainly ...
not months.'' But that estimate later was rescinded because of the
water temperature and other variables, according to office
spokeswoman Ellen Borakove.
   Now, Borakove says, ``We're still not prepared to give any
information out on the timing of the death.''
   The Rivaltas have been held without bail since their arrest and
face trial Sept. 26 in Manhattan federal court.
   The federal complaint against the pair alleges that two weeks
after Mangiameli disappeared, Fausto Rivalta sold a pear-shaped
diamond at a Florida pawnshop for $14,000. An appraiser identified
it as one of the six missing gems.
   Both brothers gave separate videotaped statements to the
Manhattan district attorney's office in March saying they did not
buy diamonds shown to them on Feb. 2 by Mangiameli.
   Debra Shapiro says that Fausto _ who lived in the same apartment
building as Mangiameli _ described himself as an interior designer.
Assistant U.S. Attorney J. Gilmore Childers says that at the time
of his arrest, Fausto, 33, was on probation on a burglary charge in
New York and had been arrested several times in Italy, mostly for
``theft-related'' crimes.
   Shapiro and Fischler say they never met Raoul Rivalta, whom
Mangiameli described to Fischler as a vice president of the
brokerage Bear Stearns & Co. Inc. In an affidavit dated April 28,
Raoul, 48, described himself as ``on leave of absence'' from the
firm.
   But the company's personnel director, Steve Lacoff, said Raoul
started as a security guard in April 1984 and worked his way up to
the post of clerk in the international operations department. He
said he was fired Feb. 26 for failing to return from vacation.
   Some people in the Diamond District say Mangiameli was wrong to
carry diamonds to meet someone she didn't know. Yet many dealers
and brokers carry jewels around, and danger is widely regarded as
inevitable in a business that deals daily in some of the world's
most precious objects.
   The district contains a heavy presence of uniformed and
undercover police and private security guards, but it isn't always
enough. Recent deaths include that of a man who was thrown to the
ground and struck his head on the sidewalk during a mugging in June.
   At one end of the spectrum are Colombian criminals who squirt
their prey with ketchup and commit robbery while the hapless victim
is trying to clean it up. ``Sometimes they end up with $100,000
score and sometimes they end up with someone's lunch,'' says
Detective James Kennedy of the Midtown North Precinct.
   Then there are the Soviet emigres who work a more sophisticated
con, finding it easier to set up a deal and get a foot inside the
door of a jewelry business than ``the average black kid from
Brooklyn,'' he says.
   In such an environment, it can take just one mistake to become a
casualty. Fischler says Mangiameli was ``smart, maybe a little
naive and that's why she got conned. But nobody's perfect.''
   In the Diamond District, danger ``is an occupational hazard in
the sense that there'll always be someone who'll try and put a scam
on you,'' says Henry Shapiro's widow, Barbara. She too carries
jewels _ and takes a different route home every night.
   But, she says, ``you can't go to work every day thinking that
someone is out to kill you, because then you may as well just stay
in bed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
