<DOCNO> AP880912-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV25   09-12 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 25,0779</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pianist-arranger Luther Henderson, one of the
members of the original cast back for a revival of ``Ain't
Misbehavin','' thinks the Fats Waller musical is even better than
when it opened 10 years ago.
   And that original production was good enough to lead to
successful Broadway revues of music by Eubie Blake (``Eubie'') and
Duke Ellington (``Sophisticated Ladies'').
   Other members of the original Broadway cast _ Nell Carter,
Armelia McQueen, Charlaine Woodard, Andre De Shields and Ken Page _
are at the Ambassador Theater, again singing songs that the late
composer-pianist-singer Fats Waller made into hits. Henderson sits
in for Waller at the upright piano.
   ``There have been many extraordinarily good casts,'' Henderson
says. ``But none of them generate the kind of electricity that this
group does. This show has taken on a deeper dimension. I don't know
if that's visible to everybody. The singers are doing the same
thing they did before and as great as it was, it seems to be better
now. I think I'm playing better now.
   ``What we were attempting, and I think we do, is to capture, be
custodians of and illuminate the spirit of Fats Waller,'' Henderson
says. ``We're not just giving lip service to songs like `T'ain't
Nobody's Biz-ness If I Do' and his saying, `One never know, do
one.' It's for fun.''
   One song, ``Black and Blue,'' isn't intended to be funny, but
sometimes the audience laughs as the song begins. The laughter
trails off as they realize it's serious.
   ``All of a sudden, Fats, who's telling everybody your feet's too
big and this man is fat and greasy and being the buffoon _ for
which he got a lot of flack in his lifetime _ decides to create a
very strong protest song,'' Henderson says. ``People have been
having such a good time they can't believe right away he's not
kidding.''
   ``Ain't Misbehavin''' has been touring, drawing audiences
steadily over 10 years, with different casts. Leonard Oxley and
Billy McDaniels, who've done the show often, currently play piano
on Tuesday nights and Wednesday matinees, when Henderson is off.
   Henderson confesses that he really doesn't play like Fats
Waller, ``except in certain things.''
   ``I use some of his stride piano idioms,'' he says. ``Stride is
`oom pah,' a rhythmic background effect, like a band. Fats was
exuberant and he showed it in his percussiveness. He was able to do
stride with his left hand and play other stuff up in the right hand.
   ``In the late 1930s and early 1940s the art of stride piano
playing, and boogie-woogie, were incredible. I can tell you they
are very difficult to do.''
   Henderson was hired as arranger when ``Ain't Misbehavin'''
started as a musical revue at the off-Broadway Manhattan Theater
Club. ``The orchestra is built around the piano,'' he says. ``Fats
never had a band. He called it Fats Waller and his rhythm. He used
a drummer, bassist and sometimes a guitarist.'' Later, Henderson
reluctantly agreed to play on-stage piano as well.
   Henderson, a Juilliard School graduate, decided early in life to
concentrate on arranging instead of composing or performing. He was
intimidated by the great jazz pianists then working. ``I always
tell people I was frightened by Art Tatum at an early age,'' he
says. ``Then Oscar Peterson came along.''
   He composed the music for an off-Broadway musical comedy,
``Crystal Tree.'' ``I'm not a bad composer,'' he says, ``but that's
something you can't do offhand. You have to do it every day; it's
not a part-time job.''
   When he arranges, Henderson says, he starts with pinning down
what is to be communicated. ``When I get a job like `Miss Teen
U.S.A.' for TV, I don't need to go into that depth. I just
generally do because that's how I got brought up. When I get these
gigs, I work twice as hard as anybody else.''
   Henderson recently arranged two albums, of Dixieland and
Gershwin music, for the Canadian Brass. ``There is nothing in those
two hours of music that is improvised and they say Dixieland should
be improvised.
   ``I think I was successful. It's the essence of what Dixieland
might have been if they'd all had the technique these boys have
got. I strive for that _ the essence _ a lot.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Libya-ManmadeRiver ADV18   09-12 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Libya-Manmade River, ADV 18,0879</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Libya Pushes Gadhafi's Dream of Making a Desert Green</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BREGA, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite sagging oil revenues, Libya is
pushing ahead with Col. Moammar Gadhafi's dream of piping fresh
water from deep under the Sahara Desert to the shores of Tripoli
and other thirsty coastal areas.
   Gadhafi maintains his Great Manmade River Project will transform
a nation that is 95 percent desert into a ``Garden of Eden'' abloom
in fruits, vegetables and grain.
   One underpinning of the project is U.S. technology, reportedly
in place before January 1986, when the Reagan administration
ordered American companies to stop doing business in Libya on
grounds that Libyans were behind terrorism aimed at Americans and
other Westerners.
   Gadhafi, riding in a beat-up Range Rover behind Bedouins on
horses, came here Aug. 26, 1986, to inaugurate the factory that
makes the concrete-and-steel pipes for the ``river.'' Since then,
about 280 miles of the planned 12,500-mile pipeline have been laid
in a trench cut through sand and underlying rock.
   The first stage, estimated to cost $4.5 billion, calls for 1,180
miles of pipeline to carry half a billion gallons of fresh water
daily from wells in east central Libya to a reservoir at Ajdabiya
near the coast on the Gulf of Sidra for distribution to areas near
Sirte and Benghazi.
   In 1986, officials predicted the first stage would be completed
in 1989. But factory manager Osman Jaouda estimated recently it
would be finished in 1991.
   The South Korean construction company Dong-Ah is cranking out
the pipes and digging through the desert to lay them down. Jaouda
said the Koreans' inexperience with desert terrain and weather
caused the delay.
   ``It's not (a problem of) financing,'' said Jaouda.
   With current lower market prices, Libya's oil revenue is sharply
down from the boom years of the late 1970s and early '80s. In 1980,
oil revenue was $22 billion; by 1987, it had plunged to $6.6
billion.
   Diplomatic and business sources in Tripoli say Libya has cut
back drastically on such projects as highway, school and hospital
construction and is concentrating its resources on its oil
industry, the military and the Great Manmade River.
   ``Every single Libyan is waiting for water,'' Jaouda said,
leading a tour for foreign journalists flown on a government plane
from Tripoli to Benghazi to see the project.
   The pipeline's first part slices through bleak terrain, broken
only occasionally by brush and date palms near oases, where camels
and goats graze.
   Gadhafi comes to the desert frequently to check on progress,
Jaouda said.
   The U.S. order against American operations in Libya caused a few
hectic months without consultants but did not delay the project,
Jaouda claimed.
   The firm of Root and Brown Inc. of Houston, Texas, turned over
its duties to its subsidiary in England, and Britons and Canadians
have taken the place of the estimated 300 Americans who were
working on the project, Jaouda said.
   He added that the first water to flow will irrigate 247,000
acres of farmland near the Mediterranean city of Benghazi, Libya's
second largest city.
   Other stages call for water to be tapped from wells in central
west Libya and be delivered to Tripoli and for a pipeline to
connect the Libyan capital, Tripoli, with Sirte. Eventually a
pipeline is to run out to wells in Kufra, deep in the south, and
the final phase will pipe water as far east as Tobruk, near the
border with Egypt.
   Jaouda declined to give even the roughest estimate for
completion of the entire project but that contracts will be awarded
for stage two by the end of this year, a few months behind an
earlier timetable.
   Businessmen and technicians here, including those who have
worked on irrigation projects, express doubts that the project will
guarantee that Libya can grow all it needs to eat.
   They cite the competing demands by major cities, where most of
Libya's population lives, for more and better drinking water. They
predict political pressures will dictate that more and more water
transported by the pipeline will be diverted from agricultural to
urban use.
   They also say that the project is counting on enthusiastic
cooperation from farmers to see that the irrigated land is most
efficiently farmed. But they add that state cooperative farms
generally yield much less than possible because the workers won't
make any more profit if they work harder or better.
   As an example, a European construction executive, who is
directing a small-scale irrigation project in the desert, said the
project failed because the farmers preferred to put in their extra
work into private lands, not the state-run irrigated fields.
   Jaouda said water from the project will be used for both state
and private lands.
   He estimated that the Great Manmade River's water, pumped up
from natural wells 1,150 feet below the ground, will last 50 years.
   The pipe segments, each weighing 72 tons, and measuring 23 feet
long and 13 feet in diameter, will probably outlast the water, he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
