<1ST_LINE>s i BC-China-Soviet-People ADV18   09-12 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Soviet-People, ADV 18,0578</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Soviets Coming Back to China and Welcome Is Warm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-China-Soviet Border, b0798</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANZHOULI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Crying Deer Restaurant on
Sino-Soviet Road, chef Sun Zhaomin cracks a toothless grin and runs
to the back to grab two plates of his famous salad.
   ``Soviet friends, you've returned,'' he shouts. ``Soviet
friends, we welcome you.''
   Andrev Vedernikov and Vadim Evdokimov, railway workers in this
town on the Soviet border, have come back for another meal.
   Down the street, at the International Guest House, members of
the Soviet Friendship Delegation from Zabaikalsk dance the night
away with their counterparts from the Manzhouli Sino-Soviet
Friendship Committee.
   At the close of the evening, under revolving green and red disco
lights, Xue Guiyuan, a Chinese trade official, waxes melodramatic.
   ``Two great nations are becoming friends again,'' he says. ``Two
peoples are moving closer together.''
   On train No. 390, heading east from Manzhouli, Ira Shamrett, 48,
and her son, Kostya, 19, are off to see relatives in Harbin, the
provincial capital of China's Heilongjiang province.
   ``We come from Siberia,'' announces Mrs. Shamrett in rusty
Chinese, learned in the five years she spent in Harbin as a
youngster. ``It's been more than 30 years since I saw my brother.''
   ``I hope to learn about kung-fu,'' said her son. ``It's becoming
very popular back home.''
   Just as trade has blossomed between China and the Soviet Union,
so have contacts between Chinese and Soviets. Since last year,
China has allowed Soviets to return to its border provinces to
visit relatives who stayed after relations between the two
countries deteriorated in the late 1950s. The Soviets have done the
same for Chinese with family in Siberia and Soviet Central Asia.
   Both countries also have dropped visa requirements for
businessmen.
   Vedernikov, 30, and Evdokimov, 29, who work on Soviet freight
trains between Manzhouli and Zabaikalsk, studied Chinese for five
years at the Chita Pedagological Institute, about 180 miles from
the Chinese border.
   Now they handle freight and mail, which have both increased
markedly as trade between the countries rises.
   ``I had a choice between a job as a teacher or work on this
train,'' said Evdokimov, speaking a mixture of Chinese and English.
``The job is boring, but I wanted to see China. It fascinates me
strongly.''
   Vedernikov hopes to parlay his excellent Chinese into a job as a
businessmen.
   ``I was trained to be a translator, but when I finished school
in 1980 things were still bad between our countries so there were
no jobs. Now there's much possibility,'' he said.
   The two men said they were impressed at the economic growth in
China, especially at the relative abundance of vegetables and
consumer goods. They also noted the increasing number of private
businesses, of which the Crying Deer is one.
   ``Private or cooperative businesses in the Soviet Union are just
beginning, but here they've been going on for about five years
now,'' said Vedernikov. ``I think they can teach us very much.''
   Sun, a 61-year-old former member of China's famed Eighth Route
Army and regarded as the best chef in town, agrees.
   ``I say open the borders wide and we'll show them how to make
money,'' he said. ``That would be a twist.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
