<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   09-12 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,0660</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Cop,'' ``batteries not included.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Cop'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS, $89.95; Beta, $29.95; Rated
R)
   
   Sgt. Lloyd Hopkins is the kind of cop who wears his profession
on his chest in big red letters. He's a COP. He makes his own rules
and breaks others and he doesn't care who he has to whack in order
to rid the world of bad guys and scum.
   All this makes Sgt. Lloyd Hopkins (James Woods) infinitely more
dangerous than Jack the Ripper.
   He's a married man who thinks nothing of giving a hooker a
whirl, and a father who tells his small daughter bedtime stories
about his violent escapades. In the understatement of the video
year, his wife tells him he's a very sick man, and she takes the
kid and leaves him.
   Hopkins doesn't have time to brood about crimes of the heart;
he's hot on the heels of a serial killer.
   Hopkins is the one man who thinks a serial killer is involved in
the obscene murder of a young woman. He's convinced she is the 15th
victim of the same murderer and becomes obsessed in the hunt.
   Charles Durning puts in a good performance as Hopkins' buddy and
superior, and Charles Haid of TV's ``Hill Street Blues'' is fine as
a sleazy, homosexual cop on the take.
   But Lesley Ann Warren's feminist poet, the killer's secret love
object, sets the women's movement back 50 years. She's a whimpering
idiot who chainsmokes her way into a dangerous situation.
   Woods, who co-produced the movie with director James B. Harris,
is in just about every scene. With his squirrelly look and staccato
sentences, he's fairly convincing as a cop about to implode.
   Much of the plot is predictable, and uneven editing leaves major
holes in the story. The R rating is well deserved for a screenful
of blood and guts.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``batteries not included'' (MCA Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95;
Rated PG)
   
   One more whimsical fantasy from the Steven Spielberg factory _
maybe one too many.
   Hume Cronyn and Jessica Tandy head a cast of oddly assorted
characters holding out against a ruthless developer who wants to
buy them out of their crumbling New York tenement so he can build a
skyscraper. When they say no, the creep hires a thug to destroy the
place.
   Enter the cutest little creatures from outer space you ever saw
_ flying saucers with eyes, arms and legs who reproduce, eat pieces
of coffee pots and frying pans, and _ most important _ fix things.
Things like broken windows, watches, doors and, eventually, the
entire building.
   They also fix broken hearts and minds, sparking a romance
between two of the characters, helping Cronyn and Tandy patch up
their marriage, and rehabilitating a washed-up prize fighter who
hasn't done anything in years but watch TV commercials.
   The special effects are fun for a while, and kids will put up
with the ridiculous plot, but grownups are likely to gag on the
treacly sentimentality. There's also a fair amount of bashing and
burning, which could prove upsetting for very young children.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
