<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   09-12 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Folk Songs, Children's Melodies, Jazz Tunes, And Others ...''
(Antilles-New Directions) _ Michal Urbaniak
   
   Not at all the hodgepodge of styles suggested by the title,
Michal Urbaniak's ``Folk Songs, Children's Melodies, Jazz Tunes,
And Others ...'' is amazing, wild and beautiful music that should
not be missed.
   Urbaniak is a Polish-born violinist who has recorded in many
styles. This collection, 10 duets with pianist Vladislav Sendecki,
is hard to pin a label on, but it sure sounds good.
   The album gets off to a manic, joyful start with two songs that
kick like a pair of size 20 boots. By the time ``Munchkins'' and
``Toy's Corner'' are over, listeners might find themselves gasping
for air and begging for a break in the action.
   Urbaniak and Sendecki deliver that in ``September's,'' a
meditative piece that leads off a series of slower, more relaxed
songs that are always compelling. But on ``Waltz,'' the second song
on Side 2, it's off to the races again as the pace picks up before
winding down with the jazzy finale called ``Montag.''
   Urbaniak's music usually is heavily into electronics, but this
album is all acoustic. And there's never a dull moment.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Greatest Hits'' (RCA) _ The Judds
   
   On the back cover of this, their obligatory greatest-hits album,
Naomi and Wynonna Judd tell us about ``the four shortest years of
our lives,'' since they shopped their homemade demos around and
landed themselves a record deal.
   No, it doesn't seem like four years, but it has been. And this
``best-of'' package stands as testimony to the fact that The Judds,
the much publicized red-headed mother-daughter duo, can no longer
be taken as a novelty act or a curiosity. Naomi and Wynonna have
made a harmonious place for themselves in 1980s country music.
   Nine of the 10 selections here have been released before on The
Judds' three studio albums. The big hits are present and accounted
for: ``Why Not Me,'' ``Mama He's Crazy,'' ``Girls Night Out.''
   ``Why Not Me'' opens the collection and sets the tone; it's a
proud, no-nonsense song sung by two proud, no-nonsense women. The
Judds know who they are, and they know what they want _ love,
happiness, respect.
   The lone new track is their current hit, ``Give a Little Love,''
which continues their proud tradition with a bluesy, soulful
approach.
   Like most greatest-hits packages, The Judds give old fans all
their favorites in one place, while giving the uninitiated a
freshman course in Judds 101.
   One minor complaint: They should have included their 1987
country cover of ``Don't Be Cruel.'' Elvis, wherever he is these
days, would have been proud.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Open All Night'' (Elektra) _ Georgia Satellites
   
   When the Georgia Satellites get their sentence in rock history
books, it will surely mention ``Keep Your Hands to Yourself,'' the
hard-rocking tale of sexual frustration that brightened radio
airwaves in 1986.
   Trouble is, that was on their debut album. ``Open All Night'' is
the Satellites' second album and, predictably, lightning doesn't
strike twice.
   The good news about ``Open All Night'' is that the Satellites
didn't tear out their hair trying to rewrite their hit. They also
don't pretend to be anything other than what they are, a raunchy
guitar army trying to fill a void left by the absence of the
Rolling Stones.
   The bad news is the cupboard is nearly bare. For all the
inspired bashing and banging, only a few songs truly stand out.
There are two cover tunes on Side 1, which usually signals a lack
of inspiration.
   Both Jerry Lee Lewis' ``Whole Lotta Shakin''' and the Beatles'
``Don't Pass Me By'' are given typical raucous workouts. But it's
daunting _ and maybe dangerous _ to try and top the Killer, and
there are reasons why ``Don't Pass Me By'' is one of the most
obscure Beatle songs.
   ``Sheila'' is the standout tune on the album, and that's an
original. The rockers tend to blur together on the second side,
until the record ends strongly with the bluesy ``Hand to Mouth,''
featuring excellent guitar by Rick Richards and the piano of guest
Ian McLagan.
   Along with assorted girlfriends and roadies, the band thanks on
the album cover ``Mr. Chuck Berry and Mr. Jack Daniels.'' That says
about as much as you need to know about the Georgia Satellites'
music.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
