<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--AbusedArt ADV23-25   09-12 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Abused Art, ADV 23-25,0892</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept 23-25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Faded, Scarred Rothko Murals on Display</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late abstract expressionist Mark
Rothko said he was less interested in color and form than in
expressing human emotions.
   Now, as Harvard University displays a colossal series of Rothko
murals, the consequences of the artist's philosophy _ as well as
years of neglect _ have become clear.
   The three murals, some 500 square feet of oil and acrylic on
canvas, have badly faded in the sunlight during the 16 years they
hung in a Harvard dining room, so much so that they actually have
changed color. They also suffered rips, scratches and splatters
caused by bumping chairs and spilled food. On one panel is scrawled
the name Alan C.
   The institution for years was criticized for what was believed
to be its mishandling of the paintings, particularly from devotees
of the so-called New York School of modern artists, co-founded by
Rothko before World War II.
   A new study conducted by Harvard scholars has turned up two
prime culprits: the artist and Harvard University. Rothko
contributed to the demise of the works by using a highly unstable
paint _ lithol red _ to form the background of all three murals.
Harvard made matters worse by failing to protect the canvases from
sunlight and careless visitors.
   ``Harvard has gotten so much bad press about the Rothkos that we
didn't feel it would matter if we said again, `they're in tough
shape,''' said Marjorie Cohn, head conservator at Harvard.
   The color used by Rothko has a reputation as a ``fugitive
pigment'' and its fleeting existence on Rothko's canvas explains
why.
   The artist apparently had no idea in 1962 when he completed the
paintings that the color was susceptible to fading. His attitude
toward the subject was revealed in a conversation related by
Elizabeth Jones, head conservator of Harvard's Fogg Art Museum in
the late 1960s:
   ``I said, `What kind of paint do you use?''' Jones recalled in a
telephone interview. ``He said, `I use oil paint and if I run out I
go downstairs to the Woolworths and buy whatever's there.' He
should have known better.''
   The five-and-dime paint wasn't up to the conditions in the
sun-filled penthouse suite in Harvard Square that housed the murals
from 1963 until 1979 when, scratched, scuffed and faded, they were
removed to a vault.
   A wine-dark crimson, chosen in honor of Harvard, formed the
background color of the murals. On two panels, the color faded to a
dull, denim blue _ nearly Yale blue. And to make matters worse, the
color faded unevenly, ruining the intended uniformity of background
that made the room vibrate with color.
   ``It was like walking into a medieval cathedral at sunset,''
said Jones, who helped unroll and mount the paintings when they
arrived at Harvard.
   The paintings are on display at Harvard's Sackler museum through
Oct. 2. They are arranged in the same configuration as their
original setting in the university's Holyoke Center but are now far
from any direct sunlight.
   ``If (Rothko) could see the extent to which these particular
color relations had been so drastically altered he would most
likely disown the paintings,'' said Harvard associate art Professor
Anna Chave, a Rothko expert. ``I think they're relics, basically.
They're artifacts.''
   The paintings still have value, in Chave's view, much the way
Leonardo's ``The Last Supper'' can move a viewer despite extensive
deterioration.
   ``They were allowed to be exposed to an incredible amount of
light in their original installation and that's why they faded so
drastically,'' Chave said. ``No one was doing anything about it.
Harvard really did not pay attention to what was happening.''
   John Coolidge, former director of the Fogg and one of those
directly involved in promoting Rothko's donation of the murals to
Harvard, places most of the blame on the artist. ``Rothko was
passionate to create a room, but he had not the slightest idea what
was involved,'' Coolidge said. Meanwhile, Harvard officials, he
said, were loathe to ``question the quality of his technique. ...
We were certainly unprepared for the speed with which they went.''
   Rothko was contacted once about the fading of the murals, Chave
said. He rejected a proposal to varnish the canvases to protect
them. In 1970, at age 67, Rothko committed suicide, 57 years after
he came to the United States from the Soviet Union. After his
death, confusion and controversy over control of Rothko's estate
complicated any decision about the Harvard paintings.
   Since then, another, even larger set of murals at the Rothko
Chapel in Houston has had to undergo treatment because a chemical
used in their varnish reacted with the atmosphere to create white
splotches on black paint.
   But Dana Cranmer, former conservator of the Rothko foundation,
said Rothko is only one of many modern artists whose works have
fallen victim to decay. ``Because of the emphasis on this it does
look like Rothko's the only bad boy in town,'' Cranmer said.
``Willem De Kooning used mayonnaise on his paintings. Longevity is
low on the totem pole.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept 23-25</NOTE>
