<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Starr ADV23-25   09-12 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Starr, ADV 23-25,0714</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept 23-25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Brenda Believes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISSA M. VECCHIONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the title of her current hit single, Brenda
K. Starr says she still believes stardom will be hers.
   ``I believe in myself, but I know it takes time,'' says the
21-year-old singer, whose first hit single, ``I Still Believe'' has
climbed the charts to the Top 40.
   She recently talked about her career in an interview at the
offices of MCA Records. She compared herself to a long list of
contemporary artists, including Janet Jackson, Anita Baker and
Diana Ross, before actually calling herself a ``young Donna
Summer.''
   Starr has been heavily influenced by rhythm and blues and Latin
sounds, and she likes her music to have those elements.
   However, she doesn't like to be compared to other young artists
such as Tiffany or Debbie Gibson. She says they're too ``pure.''
She prefers being thought of as sexier.
   ``I'm a romantic,'' Starr said.
   Her self-titled LP contains the popular love ballad, ``I Still
Believe,'' as well as more upbeat tracks, including the hit ``What
You See Is What You Get.'' Most of these danceable tunes portray
love and happiness, with one pop tune that warns against drunken
driving.
   Born Brenda Kaplan on Manhattan's Upper West Side, she took the
last name Starr because ``that's what I've always wanted to be, a
star.''
   She started singing in choirs in grammar and junior high school.
``They always had choirs that you could join as a hobby, so I took
singing because I felt it was fun,'' she said.
   Starr dropped out of high school to put out her first album, ``I
Want Your Love,'' on Mirage Records. She later realized a lot more
than singing was involved in the music business and that there was
a lot more to life than singing, so she went back to school to get
her diploma.
   Her first big break came when she appeared in the movie ``Beat
Street,'' a 1984 dance film, as an auditioning singer. She also
co-wrote the songs ``Shadows of the Night'' and ``Vicious Beat''
for the movie's soundtrack.
   Her other appearances were with an all-girl breakdancing group
called The Dynamic Dolls. They once performed in Washington for
President and Mrs. Reagan.
   Though her father, Harvey Kaplan, who sang with the pop group
Spiral Staircase, was in the music business, he wasn't her main
influence.
   ``My father didn't influence me, my mother influenced me,''
Starr said. ``She always told me I would be successful and if I
wanted to do something I could do it. My father? I was happy that
he was my dad and he had a record out, but I wanted to show him
that I could do just as he could so he would be proud of me. Now
I'm doing it for me.''
   Starr spends a lot of time on the road touring. After meetings
with managers, voice lessons and family visits to New York, she
enjoys returning to the tranquility of her new home in North
Bergen, N.J., where she's writing songs for an upcoming album.
   What's does Starr see in her future?
   ``I want to be married by 24 and have a baby by 25,'' said the
singer, who already has names picked out for the five children she
wants. ``They'll be my audience in case there's not enough of one.
I want to be like my mom, who had seven. It's like camp.''
   Another movie apperance isn't on her agenda, though.
   ``I've been asked to do movies but haven't taken anyone up on
their offer because I'm so into my music right now,'' she said.
``I'm trying to concentrate on my shows and do a good performance
so people can enjoy me and say, `I'm going to go out and buy that
album.'''
   Asked about doing television, Starr perked up and said with a
big smile, ``I want to do the Cosby Show. I want to meet Bill
Cosby.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept 23-25</NOTE>
