<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilRecords     09-12 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Records,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Lists Oil Industry Records And Trivia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the first dry hole to ``Big Bertha,'' the
world's most productive drill bit, the records, trivia and history
that give the ``oil bidness'' its unique, colorful character have
been chronicled by an industry trade journal.
   ``Drilling Magazine,'' updating a list it first ran five years
ago, is giving its 20,000 readers _ primarily well-site operators _
some targets to shoot for and records to brag about.
   ``It's sort of the oil industry's Guinness Book,'' says Editor
Mike Killalea, who compiled the facts appearing in the current
issue of the bi-monthly magazine. ``I'm very much interested in the
curiosity and the oddball. While penetration rates and footage
distances are incredible, they don't grip the imagination.''
   So besides records like the deepest, first and most productive
well, the magazine's list includes such items as how the term
``derrick'' got its name, where the first dry hole was drilled and
the strangest well blowout.
   The U.S. oil industry is generally given a birth year of 1859
with the discovery of crude in Venango County, Pa., on land owned
by the Watson & Brewer Lumber Co. The well generally is known as
the Drake Discovery Well, so named for Edwin Drake, president of
Seneca Oil of New Haven, Conn., the well owner.
   But what's less well-known is the first dry hole, in neighboring
Warren County, Pa. It also carries the distinction of the world's
second oil well, started four days after the Drake Well. More
dubious, it's the first well in which oil tools got stuck.
   Magazine editors also have decided the strangest well blowout
occurred in April 1, 1984, in Texas' Palo Pinto County, when the
Mitchell Lease No. 1 well blew and was shut quickly as a safety
precaution. The next day, however, an explosion two miles away was
blamed on the shut well. Apparently pressure built up and traveled
along a layer of rock and salt 250 feet underground until surfacing
two miles away.
   The term ``derrick,'' by the way, is named after a famous
English hangman who skillfully practiced his trade around 1600. He
was so notorious that his name was applied to anything that was
hoisted or lifted. And in oil, a derrick is the structure that
lifts pipe in and out of the hole.
   New entries to the record book include:
   _The deepest water-depth oil discovery in the Gulf of Mexico: a
13,600-foot hole in 3,560 feet of water 55 miles east of the
Mississippi River delta.
   _The deepest water-depth drilling in the world: 7,520 feet, Gulf
of Mexico, Nov. 5, 1987. The hole reached 17,430 feet before the
drillship was moved Feb. 16, 1988.
   _The most productive drill bit: ``Big Bertha,'' a 17{-inch bit
manufactured by Houston-based Hycalog, drilled 18,016 feet in 16
runs in five North Sea wells with no repair between wells. The bit,
used in 1987 and this year, made more holes in the North Sea than
any other single bit. And its mark of going through more than
30,000 cubic feet of rock could make it the most productive single
drill bit of all time.
   U.S. state deep-drilling marks on the books include a well of
20,335 feet in Alaska, set in 1979; 22,712 in California, reached
in 1987; Louisiana's 25,703 feet in 1980; 29,670 feet in Texas in
1982; and 31,441 feet in 1974 in Oklahoma, which used to be the
world's deepest and may be again.
   A 40,000-foot well being drilled in the Soviet Union, cited five
years ago as the world's deepest, since then has caved in,
according to unidentified sources quoted by Drilling Magazine.
   ``Glasnost or no glasnost, it's not the easiest thing to find
out,'' Killalea says. ``I ultimately did discover that the well
caved in a year and a half ago. So they don't have that claim (of
the world's deepest) any more.''
   Killalea says he called the Soviet Embassy in Washington for
confirmation and was told to send a letter.
   ``They were very nice and told me they would get back to me,''
he says. ``I'm waiting to hear from them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Japan-Trade     09-12 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Declines In August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus fell 3.9 percent in August
over a year ago and 31 percent from the previous month, the Finance
Ministry announced Monday.
   The surplus in Japan's international trade fell to $4.94 billion
from $5.15 billion in August 1987 and $7.16 billion in July.
   In July the surplus had ended a streak of 15 consecutive months
of declines to grow by 3.1 percent over the previous year's level.
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States declined by 12.7
percent in August over the previous year to $3.25 billion, the
ministry said.
   ``Looking at the overall trend, the volume and value of imports
are growing and cutting into (Japan's) surplus. The government is
also stimulating domestic demand'' in an attempt to curtail its
overseas trade surplus, said a Finance Ministry official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Imports surged by 27.3 percent on a dollar basis from the
previous year's level to a record $15.86 billion for August, the
ministry said.
   Exports rose 18.2 percent in August from the previous year's
figure to $20.80 billion, but declined 10.2 percent from $23.15
billion in July.
   In measuring exports, officials pegged the dollar at 133.13 yen,
compared with 150.83 yen one year earlier and 131.31 yen in July,
while imports were determined at an exchange rate of 133.12 yen to
the dollar, in contrast with 150.83 yen in August 1987 and 131.40
yen last month.
   The ministry said Japan's trade surplus with the United States
declined in part because of major hikes in imports of U.S. food in
August.
   Imports of fish soared by 105.3 percent, while those of meat
rose by 99.6 percent, the ministry reported. Imports of nonferrous
metals also increased, growing by 140.4 percent over the previous
year, it said.
   Japan measures its trade on a customs-clearance basis, which
includes freight and insurance costs in imports but not in exports.
If those costs were included in both categories, Japan's trade
surplus would be higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
