<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Nissan,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford, Nissan Announce Joint Venture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. today announced a joint
venture to produce minivans with Nissan Motor Co. Ltd. at Ford's
truck plant in northeastern Ohio.
   Ford Vice Chairman Harold A. Poling told a news conference at
Ford's headquarters that the No. 2 U.S. automaker would invest $900
million to expand the plant.
   Simila announcements were made at the plant site in Avon Lake,
Ohio and in Toyko, where Nissan is based.
   Poling said about 1,300 new jobs will be created by the project,
bringing to 2,800 the number of people employed at the plant, which
now builds and paints bodies for Ford's Econoline van and Club
Wagon models.
   Poling said he didn't know how much money Nissan was planning to
spend on the project about 15 miles west of Cleveland.
   He said construction at the plant would begin within six weeks,
and production of the new vehicle would begin in the fall of 1991
for the 1992 model year. The size of the plant will more than
double from 1 million square feet to 2.2 million square feet.
   Poling called the minivan market ``the growth phenomenon of this
decade's truck market.'' He estimated production of the new van to
be about 130,000 a year.
   ``I don't know any other state that will have received this kind
of commitment from two major Japanese auto companies,'' Ohio Gov.
Richard Celeste said Sunday, referring to Nissan and Honda Motor
Co. Ltd., which has factories in Marysville, Ohio.
   Celeste was in Tokyo for today's announcement.
</TEXT>
