<DOCNO> AP880912-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Textiles     09-12 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Textiles,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Concerned By U.S. Senate Approval Of Textile Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said
Monday it hopes President Reagan vetoes the textile and apparel
trade bill sanctioned by the U.S. Senate last week.
   European External Relations Commissioner Willy de Clercq said
that the bill, if signed into law, would ``inevitably lead to the
collapse'' of the Multifiber Agreement, which regulates world trade
in textiles.
   De Clercq also claimed it would ``seriously jeopardize'' the
Uruguay round of international trade negotiations in which trade
representatives are attempting to improve the global trade system,
including easing trade barriers between countries.
   The U.S. Senate approved draft legislation Friday that would put
limits on U.S. imports of textiles, apparel and shoes. The vote was
too short, however, to override an expected veto by President
Reagan. The measure must also be approved by the U.S. House of
Representatives before being sent to Reagan.
   De Clercq said that the Senate's move ``can only add to existing
uncertainty in world trade'' because it came soon after last
month's enactment of the U.S. trade bill which the European
commission considers to be protectionist.
   De Clercq said that he hoped the U.S. administration's
opposition to the bill would be maintained and that President
Reagan would veto the draft law.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater already said President
Reagan would veto the bill if it reaches his desk. Reagan vetoed an
earlier version of the textile trade bill last year after it was
passed by the House of Representatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
