<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Macmillan     09-12 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Book Publisher Agrees to Buyout By New York Investment Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishing giant Macmillan Inc., target of
unwanted takeover offers for four months, said today that it will
be bought by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. in a
cash deal that values the company at $2.36 billion.
   The announcement came after reports surfaced that Macmillan
officials had negotiated this weekend with Kohlberg Kravis, a
private partnership that has helped other large companies thwart
unwelcome takeovers.
   Kohlberg Kravis specializes in leveraged buyouts, in which a
company is acquired through mostly borrowed money repaid from the
target company's profits or asset sales.
   Macmillan said in a brief announcement that Kolhberg Kravis had
formed a subsidiary to begin a tender offer of $85 cash per share
for up to 26.1 million shares of the company, or 94 percent of the
total. The offer values the company's 27.76 million shares at about
$2.36 billion.
   The announcement was the latest twist in a takeover battle waged
since May for Macmillan, a large New York-based publishing concern
and leading supplier of college textbooks. The company owns other
operations that range from the Berlitz foreign language training
program to Katharine Gibbs clerical schools.
   A group headed by British publisher Robert Maxwell had been
attempting to buy Macmillan and last week offered to raise its
$80-a-share offer to $84 a share. A group headed by Texas investor
Robert Bass has offered $75 a share.
   The company had spurned offers from both and sought to
restructure itself to thwart a takeover by selling the information
division.
   The Bass group, which owns about 9.2 percent of Macmillan's
shares, had successfully challenged the move in court, but the
company said today that because of the planned acquisition by
Kohlberg Kravis it is scrapping the restructuring plan.
   Rumors that Macmillan had enlisted the help of Kohlberg Kravis
helped boost the price of the company's stock Friday by $3.62{ to
$83.87{ in composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
   In early trading today Macmillan rose to $84.62{.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
