<DOCNO> AP880912-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CaterpillarTalks     09-12 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caterpillar Talks,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Workers at Caterpillar Vote to Authorize Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the United Auto Workers union
voted overwhelmingly to authorize a strike against Caterpillar Inc.
if necessary, but a UAW official said today the move is routine
during contract negotiations.
   The members of UAW Local 974, which represents some 10,000
Caterpillar workers in the Peoria area, voted Sunday in favor of
allowing their negotiators to call a strike if it is deemed
necessary, said Stan Valentine, assistant director of the local's
community action program.
   ``It passed our local by a tremendous amount, by like 95
percent,'' Valentine said.
   UAW members who work for Deere & Co. also voted overwhelmingly
over the weekend to authorize their negotiators to call a strike if
necessary, said Bill Casstevens, the UAW's secretary-treasurer in
Detroit.
   Members of the UAW, which represents 13,500 active Deere workers
and 3,500 laid-off workers, voted 95 percent in favor of the strike
authorization, he said.
   Deere officials and union negotiators began contract talks on
Aug. 3 and were scheduled to resume talks this week.
   Valentine, of the Caterpillar local, said strike-authorization
votes are ``something that's customarily done'' during contract
talks.
   ``It gives the bargainers an edge knowing their people are
backing them,'' Valentine said. ``It does give our bargainers the
feeling that people are behind them and gives them the
authorization to call a strike if things don't work out and the
talks break down.''
   Valentine said Local 974 represents about half of Caterpillar's
UAW workers nationwide. He said other locals also took
strike-authorization votes, but that he wasn't certain of the
results.
   Contract talks were continuing, Valentine said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
