<DOCNO> AP880912-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Winnebagos Bjt   09-12 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Winnebagos, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi Corp. To Market U.S. Winnebago RVs in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnebagos, those behemoths of America's wide-open
spaces, were launched in the home of the compact car on Monday with
the blessings of the Japanese government.
   With a logo suggesting Japan's forested mountains and blue
lakes, the venture announced between Mitsubishi Corp. and Winnebago
Industries Inc. of Forest City, Iowa, had the glitz of professional
marketing.
   Mitsubishi coined the slogan Mobilie _ mobile plus ``ie,'' the
word for home in Japanese _ to try to sell the 122 million Japanese
on the American concept of family-style recreational vehicles as a
way to enjoy their country's scenery.
   The Japanese government is seeking to cut Japan's $60 billion
annual trade surplus with the United States by encouraging more
imports of American goods into Japan.
   Lauding the linkup were U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William
Verity, Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad and Hajime Tamura, the powerful
Japanese minister of international trade and industry.
   Tamura, one of the top political figures in Japan, came to the
lavish party Mitsubishi threw at a former imperial mansion, and he
drew a public pledge from company President Shinroku Morohashi to
go all-out to sell Winnebagos.
   ``If a Japanese trading house like Mitsubishi starts a
full-fledged program, it will succeed without fail,'' Tamura said,
asking Morohashi to shake hands with Verity and ``pledge to make an
all-out effort to succeed.''
   With a smile, Morohashi obliged.
   Verity commented: ``With Mitsubishi marketing this product, I
predict that this will be an immediate success.''
   The commerce secretary is here leading executives of 25 U.S.
consumer-products companies on a mission to penetrate the big but
difficult Japanese market. Their slogan is ``Market Japan _ with
America's best,'' and the products include jewelry, pet foods,
furniture, sailboats, power boats and sporting goods.
   The party for Winnebago was the centerpiece of the weeklong
mission, and the guests included members of the Diet, Japan's
parliament, as well as Iowa government officials.
   Morohashi said his company regarded the motor home as ``one of
the great achievements'' of American industry and predicted it will
be a success as more leisure time encourages the Japanese to do
more things outdoors.
   ``The market is very promising for the future,'' he said.
   Only in Japan could such a symbol of American gigantism be
launched in a room where the decor included bonsai _ the purposely
stunted trees that are a symbol of the miniaturism of this country
of small cars and narrow roads.
   Gasoline costs almost $3.50 a gallon in Japan, and previous
attempts to market Japanese-made camper vans have fizzled because
of the expense of fuel and lack of campgrounds for them. But Japan
is richer now, and Mitsubishi says legislation will encourage the
spread of campgrounds.
   Winnebago Vice President Gerald Boman, who had four of his
smaller RV models on display outside the mansion, said the
30-year-old company now exports only 0.5 percent of the 12,000 to
14,000 units produced annually.
   Boman hoped the Mitsubishi marketing will help increase exports
to about 10 percent of production, all of which takes place in Iowa.
   ``America has learned much from the Japanese, especially in
motor manufacturing,'' he said. ``Now we hope to share with the
Japanese people what we learned in our own experience in the
leisure industry.''
   The governor, who grew up in Forest City, Iowa, where Winnebago
is headquartered, expressed delight at the opening to Japan's
market.
   ``This is a very major step forward by American industry and we
are very proud that a company based in Iowa is leading the way here
in Japan,'' Branstad said.
   As the party ended Boman was asked how he felt to have such
lavish promotion and government backing. ``It's a great
relationship,'' he said, ``and this has been a fantastic trip.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880912-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv13   09-12 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 13 ,0600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday, Sept. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>America's Open? Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next time you hear your congressman defend
trade protection through quotas, higher tariffs or ``buy America''
programs, you might consider asking him the cost.
   It is through this sort of question that patriotic fervor, which
some people think doesn't cost a cent, confronts the individual
budgets of American households.
   Good or bad, trade protection is costly, forcing up the prices
of domestic and imported goods by amounts that might surprise most
people. By one estimate, it costs every man, woman and child in
America an average of $270 a year.
   That estimate, by economist Gary Hufbauer of Georgetown
University, is based on his calculation of a total cost per year of
$65 billion, or nearly double the tab as recently as 1980.
   How could that be, ask Americans who believe that the American
economy is as remarkably open to foreigners as foreign markets are
closed to Americans?
   Charles Oliver, who studied the matter for the Citizens For A
Sound Economy Foundation, concluded that it isn't so, that
``contrary to popular belief, the United States has become more
protectionist over the last decade.''
   He says that 35 percent of all U.S. manufactured goods were
protected by some form of trade barrier in 1986, compared with just
8 percent in 1975. The result, he says, is that Americans are
paying through the nose.
   In addition to raiding consuumers' pockets, he says trade
barriers invite other countries to retaliate against American
industries.
   He cites two incidents as examples:
   _When the United States imposed tariffs on Canadian cedar in
1986, Canada responded with restrictions on American computers and
grains.
   _When the United States placed restrictions on $50 million worth
of Chinese textiles in 1983, Beijing cancelled American wheat
contracts worth $699 million.
   The United States maintains tariffs in excess of 20 percent on
light trucks, ceramic tile, cedar shingles, fruit juice, footwear
and clothing, among other goods. In some instances, quotas are
added to tariffs.
   There are service restrictions as well. Oliver notes that the
domestic air travel market is reserved for domestic airlines, and
that only U.S.-registered ships are allowed to carry passengers and
cargo between U.S.ports.
   In fact, the International Monetary Fund in 1987 ranked the
United States as no better than average in its amount of protected
trade.
   The cost of trade protection is often obscured by other issues,
mainly the preservation of jobs. But Oliver cites a study made last
year that shows more jobs were lost than created by protection of
the textile industry.
   That study shows protectionist measures did indeed save about
46,000 textile jobs _ at an alleged cost of $220,000 each _ but
that 52,440 jobs were destroyed in retailing, transportation and
other import-dependent areas.
   Such examples, Oliver indicates, are among the more publicized.
But, he observes, hidden away in various regulatory areas are many
lesser known limitations that inexorably add to the cost of living
in the United States.
   In insurance, for example, a common barrier forces foreign firms
to pay higher state fees for licenses. Some state regulations
require these companies to invest premiums within the United States.
   What it amounts to, says Oliver, is that before politicians try
to raise trade barriers they should consider the costs of those
already on the books, including the net cost of jobs lost.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday, Sept. 13.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
