<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished slightly higher Monday in
sluggish trading on the London Stock Exchange, with the market
lacking a motivating force to spur it into action.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 6.2
points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,744.6 at the close of trading.
   The index rose as much as 9.3 points in early trading, but then
fell back to show a gain of just 3.8 points just before the 11:30
a.m. (local time) release of British reports on producer prices and
retail sales in August. The figures were in line with market
expectations and didn't alter share prices.
   Volume was light, with just 213.2 million shares changing hands,
down from 380.6 million on Friday.
   Some market watchers said traders were awaiting several key
economic reports from the United States and Britain later this
week. Others said the market remained stalled due to a lack of
interest in committing funds to the market.
   ``It's a stalemate,'' said Charles Larkum, stocks analyst at
James Capel and Co., adding that ``there's an intellectual feeling
that the market is cheap but a gut feeling that prices are going
down.''
</TEXT>
