<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-12 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gold Plunges, Dollar Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undermined by weakening oil prices, gold fell
sharply Monday in volatile European trading.
   Gold finished $7.55 an ounce lower in London after plunging
$11.50 an ounce in Zurich, where trading ended early because of a
holiday.
   The dollar was mixed at the end of extremely quiet trading as
market players sat on their positions before the release of U.S.
trade figures for July from the Commerce Department in Washington.
   Zurich traders said the plunge in gold prices, which began in
New York on Friday, caught them completely by surprise.
   ``I hate to admit it, but we're tending weaker, psychologically,
if not fundamentally,'' said one Zurich trader.
   Weaker prices for oil and other commodities have calmed fears of
inflation. That has dampened demand for gold, which investors
historically have used as a hedge against inflation.
   But traders said trading activity was limited, although they
reported good demand at lower prices around $417.
   In New York, financial activity was expected to be muted through
Tuesday because of Rosh Hashana, the Jewish new year holiday, and
traders said they anticipated the lull would keep the market a bit
thinner than usual.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $419.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $426.80 bid late Friday.
   In Zurich, gold was quoted at $418 when the market closed early,
down from $429.50 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.60 to close at $419.18.
   Silver bullion also fell sharply on the London market where the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.41 a troy ounce,
compared with $6.63 Friday.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar inched up earlier in
the day for no particular reason, but was knocked back by
intervention by the West German central bank when it rose above
1.8500 marks.
   Dealers said they expect the dollar to stay in its current range
until the July trade report Wednesday.
   ``We have a serious case of the trade figure scenario,'' said
David Deacon, senior dealer at EBC-Amro bank in London. In recent
months, foreign exchange trading has stalled in the days before a
trade balance report.
   Market expectations are for a monthly trade gap of between $11
billion and $12 billion, compared with $12.54 billion in June.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6958 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6980 late Friday
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Friday:
1.8453 West German marks, down from 1.8490; 1.5535 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5620; 6.2775 French francs, down from 6.2865; 2.0817
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0835; 1,378.50 Italian lire, down from
1,379.50; 1.2395 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar edged up 0.47 yen to close at 133.42 yen. Later, in London,
the dollar was quoted at 133.50 yen.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
