<1ST_LINE>r f BC-USSprint     09-12 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US Sprint,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Sprint Operating Losses To Decline Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   US Sprint Communication Co.'s operating
losses in the third quarter of 1988 should be sharply reduced from
the $165 million it lost in the same period of last year and the
$112 million lost in the second quarter of this year, William
Esrey, United Telecommunications Inc. president and chief executive
officer, said Monday.
   Esrey said that based on results in July and August, US Sprint
is expected to have pre-tax losses of no more than $35 million in
the quarter ending Sept. 30.
   The long-distance telephone service is operated as a partnership
of United Telecom and GTE Corp. They now own equal amounts, but
United Telecom will purchase an additional 30.1 percent interest
for more than $600 million in January 1989.
   Esrey said factors contributing to the improved performance were
continued growth in net revenue and improved control of expenses.
He said the correction of billing system problems which adversely
affected results in previous periods was a major factor.
   Moving customer traffic from leased lines and microwave
facilities onto US Sprint's new fiber-optics network also
contributed to operating efficiency, he said.
   ``While much work remains to be done, we are very pleased with
the recent progress we have made,'' Esrey said. ``US Sprint is now
in position to exceed our internal short-term objectives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
