<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-12 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed Ahead of USDA Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade in light, uneventful trading
ahead of the Agriculture Department's new crop production report.
   Most soybean futures contracts were sharply lower, wheat was
higher and corn was narrowly mixed.
   ``It was real quiet,'' said Cathy Leow, assistant vice president
for grain futures trading at Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in
New York.
   She attributed most of the trading to position-balancing before
the report, adding that a flurry of selling in the soybean trading
pit minutes before the close ``doesn't mean a heck of a lot. It all
depends on what the USDA says.''
   Traders generally expected the government to again reduce its
corn and soybean harvest projections because of drought damage to
the crops, analysts said.
   But at least one private grain analyst, Conrad Leslie of
Chicago, had predicted only very slight reductions from the USDA's
August harvest projections of 4.48 billion bushels of corn and 1.47
billion bushels of soybeans.
   The new estimates, released after the close of trading, were
4.46 billion bushels of corn, or about 37 percent less than last
year's harvest; 1.47 billion bushels of soybeans, or about 23
percent less than last year's crop; and 1.81 billion bushels of
wheat, or about 14 percent less than last year's crop. The wheat
estimate compares with the August USDA estimate of 1.82 billion
bushels.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.02{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents lower to \ cent higher with September at $2.86 a bushel; oats
were \ cent lower to 4\ cents higher with September at $2.66 a
bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with
September at $8.70 a bushel.
</TEXT>
