<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Armtek-MarkIV 1stLd-Writethru   09-12 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armtek-Mark IV, 1st Ld-Writethru,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armtek Board Agrees To $561 Million Buyout By Mark IV</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one new graf after 8th graf pvs ``Mark IV filed suit
..'' to ADD that legal action will be dropped. Picks up 9th graf
pvs ``Formerly the ..''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armtek Corp. on Monday accepted a
sweetened $561.2 million buyout offer from its once-hostile suitor
Mark IV Industries Inc., ending a brief battle for the auto parts
maker.
   Under the agreement, which was approved unanimously by Armtek's
board of directors, the Mark IV subsidiary MIV Acquisition Inc.
will pay $46 a share for all 12.2 million common shares
outstanding, $2 a share higher than its previous offer.
   ``It's a great price,'' said Donald F. DeScenza, an analyst with
Nomura Securities Inc. in New York. ``Before this takeover fight
began, the (Armtek stock) price was in the low $30s.
   ``It's being taken over at a price 50 percent above what the
market valued the stock at.''
   The bidding for Armtek began earlier this summer with a
$40-a-share offer from Mark IV. It was raised to $44 a share on
Aug. 17.
   Neither Armtek Chairman Frank R. O'Keefe Jr. nor any of the
company's board members would comment on the merger, according to
Armtek spokesman Bob Jones.
   Merger talks had been anything but friendly. After Mark IV made
its first offer, the board directed company officials to explore
all options, including recapitalization and possible third-party
buyers.
   Mark IV filed suit against Armtek at the end of last month
charging Armtek misued a variety of anti-takeover measures. Armtek
had accused Mark IV of violating disclosure requirements of federal
securities laws.
   Jones said all legal action will be dropped as a result of the
merger agreement.
   Formerly the Armstrong Rubber Co., New Haven-based Armtek makes
plastics and specialty chemicals used in the automotive and other
industries and employs 8,000 people worldwide. It sold the
Armstrong Tire Co. to the Pirelli Group for $197 million earlier
this year.
   Mark IV, based in West Amherst, N.Y., manufactures aerospace and
defense, professional audio and information productions, and
technical products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
