<DOCNO> AP880912-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WorldBank-IFC     09-12 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-IFC,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Developing Countries Reported Turning to Private Sector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the Third World is turning from state
industries to private enterprise as a source of growth, the
International Finance Corporation, private sector affiliate of the
World Bank, said Monday.
   The Washington-based lending institution in its 1988 report
described this as ``a historic change'' in the global investment
climate, and said it offers ``good prospects for accelerated and
sustainable growth'' in developing countries.
   ``In most developing countries ... governments have come to rely
ever more on private enterprise as an `engine of growth','' said
the IFC report.
   The corporation, owned by 133 World Bank member countries,
reported a record of 95 new investments totaling $1.3 billion for
the year ended last June 30, an increase of 38 percent over the
previous year.
   The investments helped fuel projects worth more than $5 billion
in 449 companies in 78 developing countries, the report said.
   Investment approvals increased in every area of the world, with
the largest increase over the previous year, 73 percent, registered
in Africa south of the Sahara desert, the report said.
</TEXT>
