<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-12 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases in New York, Gold Hardly Changed After Plunging in
Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened marginally Monday in light
trading, reflecting what money brokers called their reluctance to
speculate in advance of the government's market-jolting monthly
trade deficit reports.
   Gold ended barely changed in the United States after a wild day
in which precious metals prices tracked the volatile oil market.
Republic National Bank in New York quoted gold at $421.35 a troy
ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, down 10 cents from Friday.
   Currency traders said the dollar's behavior typified a pattern
that has emerged in days just prior to the Commerce Department's
merchandise trade deficit reports, which have the potential of
setting off sharp selloffs or rallies in the financial markets. The
July deficit figures are due Wednesday.
   ``The dollar stayed in a narrow range today and essentially went
nowhere,'' said Stuart Yannalfo, senior foreign exchange trader at
Refco Inc., a New York commodities futures concern. ``Everybody's
waiting for that trade number.''
   The consensus among foreign-exchange houses is for a July
deficit of between $11 billion and $12 billion, compared with
$12.54 billion in June. But the unpredictability of these numbers
has made many traders reluctant to take risky positions in dollars
until after the report is issued.
   In Tokyo, the dollar edged up 0.47 yen to close at 133.42 yen.
Later in London, the dollar was quoted at 133.50 yen. By the time
trading concluded in New York, the dollar weakened to 133.35 yen,
off from 133.61 yen Friday.
   The dollar gained against the British pound in London, where
sterling was quoted at $1.6958 vs. $1.6980 Friday. Later in New
York, the pound strengthened a bit to $1.6974, more expensive than
the $1.6970 price Friday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. levels late Friday
included: 1.8465 West German marks, down from 1.8493; 1.5540 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5617; 1.2367 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2396; 6.2815 French francs, down from 6.2890; and 1,378.85
Italian lire, down from 1,382.125.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Friday:
1.8453 West German marks, down from 1.8490; 1.5535 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5620; 6.2775 French francs, down from 6.2865; 2.0817
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0835; 1,378.50 Italian lire, down from
1,379.50; and 1.2395 Canadian dolars, unchanged.
   Traders were more active in the gold market, which has weakened
recently because of speculation about a renewed oil-price war.
Prices plunged in Europe but rebounded in New York, tracking the
path of energy futures.
   Cheaper energy prices could partly erase the effects of
inflation, historically a key reason that investors buy gold.
   ``For the last couple of weeks, the price of gold and precious
metals have been following the oil market,'' said Joanne Nagelhout,
a marketing analyst at A-Mark precious metals, a large trading
concern in Los Angeles. ``Oil went down under $13 a barrel and
rallied back up over $14. Gold did the same thing. The market has
not stabilized.''
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
closed at $421.20, unchanged from Friday, when prices closed
sharply lower.
   In London, gold plunged to $419.25, down from $426.80 late
Friday; in Zurich, gold fell to $418, down from $429.50 Friday; and
in Hong Kong gold fell to $419.18 from $424.78 Friday.
   Silver followed a similar pattern, ending largely unchanged in
the United States after plunging abroad. Silver eased .3 cent to
$6.437 a troy ounce on the Comex. In London, silver fell to $6.41,
down from $6.63 Friday.
</TEXT>
