<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Ford-Nissan Bjt   09-12 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford-Nissan, Bjt,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford-Nissan To Make '92 Minivan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., which holds just less
than a fourth of the fast-growing minivan market with its Aerostar,
announced plans Monday to join with Nissan Motor Corp. to make a
minivan in northeastern Ohio.
   The project, which is to deliver the new vehicles to showroom
floors in three years, will involve a $1 billion Ford investment,
about 90 percent of which is to be spent at Ford's van plant in
Avon Lake, Ohio, company vice chairman Harold Poling said at a news
conference.
   The factory, which paints and assembles bodies for Econoline and
Club Wagon vans, will double in size to 2.2 million square feet and
will employ another 1,300 people, bringing total employment to
nearly 2,800.
   Ford spokesman Jay Meisenhelder said the company first would
draw employees from a pool of laid-off Ford workers before hiring
people new to the company.
   Preparation of the plant site will begin later this month or
early October, Poling said.
   Yoshio Arakawa, a Nissan director, told a news conference in
Tokyo that Nissan's investment in the venture would be small by
comparison to Ford's.
   ``Our basic responsibility is development so our investment is
going to be rather small,'' Arakawa told reporters.
   Arakawa said Nissan will take over the design and engineering of
the new multi-purpose vehicle and supply parts provided by its
manufacturing subsidiary, the Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. in
Smyrna, Tenn.
   Ford will assemble and provide most of the components of the new
minivan. About 75 percent of the components in the new vehicle will
be made in North America, Poling said.
   The venture would be the third formed by the two companies. In
1969, Ford and Nissan joined with Mazda Motor Corp. in the Japan
Automatic Transmission Co. Ford sold its share to Nissan in 1984.
More recently, Ford and Nissan agreed to market versions of each
other's utility vehicles in Australia.
   Ford and Mazda a year ago began assembly of two cars at a plant
in Flat Rock, Mich., south of Detroit. Ford owns 25 percent of
Mazda.
   The newest project, Poling said, ``will give us an additional
vehicle in a market niche that has grown from 5 percent (of the
total truck market) in 1984 to 12 percent in 1987 and is projected
at 18 (percent) to 19 percent for the 1993 model year.''
   Poling said only styling work has been completed so far on the
new minivan, which is expected to be in production in the fall of
1991 for the 1992 model year. About 130,000 of the vehicles are
expected to be produced annually, a relatively small number
considering the size of the work force.
   The new minivan will be a more passenger-oriented vehicle than
the minivan that Ford sells now _ the Aerostar, which has cargo and
trailer-hauling capabilities.
   The Aerostar held 22 percent of the compact van market during
the first eight months of this year. General Motors Corp. and
Chrysler Corp. also produce minivans along with Toyota Motor Corp.,
Mitsubishi and Volkswagen. But the imports hold just 4 percent of
the minivan market.
   ``I think it's a great deal for Ford,'' said auto analyst
Maryann Keller of Furman Selz Mager Deietz and Birney of New York
City. ``Ford has a marvelous way of working with Japanese partners
to find products that are of mutual interest and mutual benefit to
both parties.
   ``That's something GM has never been able to do ...'' she added.
``Chrysler is still struggling to find its way with Mitsubishi.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
