<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AgeeNamed     09-12 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Agee Named,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agee Adds President Title At M-K</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By QUANE KENYON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The directors of Morrison-Knudsen Corp. on
Monday elected William M. Agee president in addition to his titles
of chairman and chief executive officer.
   The company also announced the resignation of William Deasy, 51,
who was the worldwide engineering, construction and shipbuilding
company's chief executive officer until Agee took over last month.
   M-K said Deasy, who was corporate president, chief operating
officer and a director, resigned effective immediately, ``to
develop other business opportunities.''
   Agee also announced other changes in senior management, which he
said were aimed at strengthening management and streamlining
operations control. M-K also started a new $45 million stock
incentive plan for salaried employees.
   Agee, who had been on M-K's board of directors a total of 11
years, was elected chief executive last month after the company
showed a large net loss in 1987 and also in the second quarter of
this year.
   Agee, a Boise native, was chief executive officer of the Bendix
Corp., when he led an ill-fated takeover battle that eventually saw
him resign. One of the appointments announced Monday was a former
Bendix and Allied Signal executive, Donald R. Kayser, 57.
   Kayser is the new executive vice president, chief financial
officer and a director.
   Under a new reporting structure approved by the board, the
corporation's shipbuilding, mining and real estate development
operations now will report directly to Agee. The real estate
venture, EmKay Development, is in the late stages of divestiture,
and has been the source of the bulk of the red ink reported
recently.
   The board also accepted immediate resignations from G.W.
Gilfillan, 50, executive vice president and a director, and James
B. Greene, vice president of communications and planning.
</TEXT>
