<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-12 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Expected To Drop On New Harvest Forecast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's new crop-production estimates, only slightly
lower than predictions made a month ago, surprised many grain
market analysts and should trigger a drop in corn and soybean
futures prices, experts said Monday.
   Grain and soybean futures settled mixed Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade in light trading ahead of the Agriculture
Department's report. Soybeans were lower, wheat was higher and corn
futures were mixed.
   On other markets, energy futures finished higher in a volatile
session; precious metals were lower; livestock and meat futures
were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated slightly.
   The USDA estimated 1988 U.S. corn production at 4.46 billion
bushels, compared with its August estimate of 4.48 billion bushels.
The agency pegged the soybean crop at 1.47 bilion bushels,
virtually unchanged from last month. And the USDA predicted a wheat
harvest of 1.81 billion bushels, compared with August's estimate of
1.82 billion.
   Although the numbers reflect severe drought damage and represent
sharp reductions from last year's harvest _ 37 percent less corn,
23 percent fewer soybeans and 14 percent less wheat _ they were
more optimistic than the market had anticipated and so were
expected to exert downward pressure on prices, especially in
soybeans and corn.
   ``I think corn will be down 3 to 4 cents, beans 10 cents or so,
maybe even more,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Other traders said soybean futures prices could drop as much as
20 cents a bushel at Tuesday's opening.
   Cathy Leow, vice president of grain futures trading with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York, said spot-market sales of
corn and soybeans linked to the advancing harvest already were
weakening the futures markets.
   ``Between the numbers and the harvest, it probably means the
market's not going higher in the short run,'' she said. ``We may
just move sideways for a while. We won't go higher, we won't go
lower, we'll trade in a range.''
   For the wheat market, which has shown some vigor recently on
expectations of rising export demand, the USDA report also had some
bullish news.
   The government reduced its projection for 1988-89 Soviet grain
production by 5 million metric tons to 205 million and raised its
projected Soviet grain imports estimate to 27 million metric tons
from 25 million.
   The USDA also reduced its projection for the Canadian wheat
harvest by 2.6 million metric tons to 15.4 million.
   But Lespinasse said wheat prices still could decline Tuesday in
sympathy with corn and soybeans.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 2\ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in September at $4.02\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to
{ cent higher with September at $2.86 a bushel; oats were 2 cents
lower to 3 cents higher with September at $2.61 a bushel; soybeans
were 11{ cents lower to { cent higher with September at $8.70{ a
bushel.
   Crude oil futures touched two-year lows below $14 a barrel on
selling tied to the glut of oil caused by OPEC overproduction, then
rallied late in the session to finish well above Friday's closing
levels.
   Shahrokh Nikkah, vice president in charge of energy futures at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York, attributed the dramatic
turnaround on the New York Mercantile Exchange to two announcements
from Saudi Arabia, a major OPEC member.
   He said Saudi Arabia asked its fellow members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and also non-OPEC oil
producers to show some restraint in their production.
   The Saudis also formally denied a rumor that they opposed
calling a meeting of OPEC's pricing committee to discuss the
overproduction problem, he said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 26 cents to 38 cents
higher with October at $14.49 a barrel; heating oil was .56 cent to
.81 cent higher with October at 41.68 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .56 cent to 1.10 cents higher with October at 42.62
cents a gallon.
   Precious metals futures finished slighty lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange but well above the day's lows.
   Gold settled 30 cents to $1.60 lower with October at $422.80 a
troy ounce; silver was .30 cent to 1.2 cents lower with September
at $6.437 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .60 cent lower to .12 cent higher with October
at 69.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .10
cent higher with September at 79.65 cents a pound; hogs were .13
cent lower to .20 cent higher with October at 37.92 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
February at 47.27 cents a pound.
   The contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
stock index on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange settled .60 point
lower at 266.15.
</TEXT>
