<1ST_LINE>r f AM-InsiderTrading-Karcher     09-12 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading-Karcher,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Son of Carl's Jr. Hamburger Founder Ordered to Pay $10,500</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Thomason and Bruns cq in final graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of the founder of the Carl's Jr.
hamburger chain was ordered Monday to repay $10,500 as part of a
federal insider trading suit against him and 15 other relatives and
company officers.
   Carl Leo Karcher was ordered to give up the amount he avoided in
losses by acting on inside information to sell debt securities in
Carl Karcher Enterprises Inc. in 1984.
   In ordering the penalty, U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie
declined to impose treble damages, as had been requested by the
Securities and Exchange Commission, which filed the insider-trading
civil suit. The judge issued a permanent injunction barring Karcher
from future insider trades.
   The case continues against other defendants, including Carl's
Jr. founder Carl N. Karcher, his brother, and various of their
spouses and children.
   The SEC case holds that Karchers, their in-laws and one
non-family official of the West Coast hamburger chain acted on
confidential, advance notice of an unfavorable earnings report to
sell securities and avoid potential losses in October 1984. They
are accused of avoiding losses totaling $300,000, and treble
damages could bring a total judgment against them to over $1
million.
   The attorney for Carl Leo Karcher claimed that Monday's ruling
represented a partial victory for his client, who maintained he
didn't know he had broken any laws by selling Karcher debentures in
October 1984. In refusing to impose treble damages, the judge in
essence found Karcher hadn't committed an egregious violation of
securities law, the attorney said.
   ``It indicates to me that the judge concluded that he was not a
willful violator of the law,'' Armstrong said. ``We're disappointed
the court found there was a violation because (Karcher) did believe
he had the right to sell.''
   The SEC will attempt to find the buyer of the securities and
give him the money assessed Karcher, Armstrong said. The defendant,
who was a vice president of Anaheim-based Karcher Enterprises at
the time of the trades, presently operates a string of 16 Carl's
Jr. franchises in the Palm Springs and Yuma, Ariz., areas.
   The SEC case, filed in April, revolves around trading
irregularities uncovered in random computer checks by the National
Association of Securities Dealers.
   It shook many in Orange County, where the elder Karcher, who
appears in folksy commercials for the 450-outlet hamburger chain,
is regarded as an American success story and social benefactor.
   The 1984 losses were attributed by some to a business downturn
following the Olympic Games, and have since been reversed. The
company made a $16 million profit on sales of $369 million in 1987.
   In Monday's case, Karcher didn't contest the facts of the case:
That he put in an order to his broker to sell 75 debentures, a form
of corporate debt, the morning of Oct. 19. That afternoon, after
being told by a company official such a sale was improper because
it was based on an unreleased earnings report, he ordered the sale
stopped. But 50 of the debentures had been sold.
   Named in the SEC civil suit, in addition to Carl Leo Karcher and
his father, Carl N. Karcher, are the elder Karcher's brother,
Donald F. Karcher, president and chief operating officer the
Karcher Enterprises, and Alvin DeShano, a vice president.
   Also Carl N. Karcher's son, Jerome; daughters, Barbara
Karcher-Garrett, Margaret J. LeVecke, Catherine Karcher-Everly and
her husband, Daniel; and Carl N. Karcher's son-in-law, Donald E.
Fergus Jr.
   Also Donald F. Karcher's daughter, Doneta Ann Thomason and her
husband, David; and Mrs. Dorothy Karcher's sister, Rosemary Bruns,
and her husband, William.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
