<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ApplePrices     09-12 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apple Prices,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apple Computer Hikes Product Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. announced price
increases Monday for some of its personal computers, external
drives, monitors, printers and expansion kits.
   The price hikes result from rising component costs and changing
global market conditions, according to Charles Boesenberg, Apple
USA senior vice president of sales and marketing.
   ``To continue fulfilling the increasingly high demand for our
products, we are required to pursue more costly channels for
dynamic random access memory (DRAM) acquisition, thereby increasing
the component costs of our products,'' Boesenberg said.
   The two biggest price jumps, at 29 percent each, are in the
Macintosh II, increasing to $4,869 from $3,769, and the LaserWriter
IINT Controller Card, up to $2,699 from $2,099.
   The Apple IIGS rises 15 percent to $1,149 from $999. The price
of the Macintosh Plus remains unchanged at $1,799.
   Company spokeswoman Carleen LeVasseur said Apple's dramatic
growth during the past year has forced the company to place orders
for DRAMs with new vendors and to trade at premium prices on the
spot market.
   This has proven more expensive for the company than purchasing
components from Apple's traditional sources, she said, noting the
shortage of DRAMs is expected to continue well into the next year.
</TEXT>
