<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CelestialSeasonings     09-12 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Celestial Seasonings,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vestar Capital Partners Agrees to Acquire Celestial Seasonings
from Kraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vestar Capital Partners, Inc. said Monday
it has agreed to acquire Celestial Seasonings, a leading specialty
herbal tea company, in a management buyout from Kraft, Inc.
   Terms of the transaction were not disclosed and completion of
the buyout is expected by early November. An earlier agreement by
the Illinois-based Kraft to sell Celestial to Thomas J. Lipton,
Inc., has been abandoned.
   ``In view of continuing uncertainties that have delayed the sale
of the assets of Celestial Seasonings to Thomas J. Lipton Inc., the
agreement between Kraft and Lipton has been terminated,'' Kraft
said in a statement from its headquarters in Glenview, Ill.
   The new deal was a victory for R.C. Bigelow Inc., another maker
of herbal teas, which filed a federal lawsuit in June seeking to
block Lipton's acquisition of Celestial Seasonings.
   Bigelow, based in Norwalk, Conn., maintained that the merger
would violate antitrust laws by uniting the nation's two largest
sellers of herbal tea.
   New owners of the company will include Vestar Capital Partners,
a New York private investment firm, and members of Celestial
Seasonings' management, including Barnet M. Feinblum, who will
continue as president and chief executive officer and assume
responsibilities of chairman of the board when the transaction is
completed.
   Celestial virtually created the herbal tea business in the 1970s
and today its sales account for more than half of the market with
their Sleepytime, Lemon Zinger, Mandarin Orange and other herbal
teas.
   Vestar Capital Partners is a private investment firm
specializing in organizing and investing its capital in management
leveraged buyouts and recapitalizations. Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. is providing financing for the transaction.
</TEXT>
