<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Obit-Moore     09-12 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Moore,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ambassador To Ireland, W.R. Grace Board Member Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John D.J. Moore, a one-time New York City
official who was ambassador to Ireland in the Nixon administration
and director emeritus of W.R. Grace & Co., died of bone cancer
Monday at the age of 77, the company said.
   Moore had been diagnosed as having bone cancer six months ago,
but remained active until about a week ago, said Fred Bona, a
spokesman for Grace. He died at his midtown Manhattan home.
   He was with Grace, a diversified chemical company, from 1946 to
1969 and became corporate vice president, serving in Peru,
Washington and the New York headquarters.
   Then-Vice President Richard Nixon had Moore accompany him to
South America in 1958 and to the Soviet Union in 1959.
   As president, Nixon appointed Moore ambassador to Ireland in
1969. Moore served six years, the longest tenure of any U.S.
ambassador to Ireland.
   Moore negotiated an aviation agreement that ended 20 years of
the United States trying to get landing rights in Dublin. He also
established the Mary Ball Washington Chair of American Studies at
the National University of Ireland.
   In 1976 he rejoined Grace as a member of its board. He retired
at the age of 75 but remained a director emeritus and a consultant
to the company.
   He is survived by a brother, Richard A. Moore, who was a special
counsel to Nixon.
   A Mass will be performed Wednesday at St. Vincent Ferrer Roman
Catholic Church. He will be buried in Dublin alongside his wife and
daughter.
</TEXT>
