<HEAD>Company Reports $30 Million Loss For Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. said
Monday it lost $30.5 million in its first fiscal quarter due to a
one-time pre-tax restructuring charge of $16.6 million and poor
sales of mainframe computers.
   ``Although our semiconductor operations experienced strong
demand and modest growth in the seasonally slow first quarter,
pressures on the Information Systems Group continue to affect the
company's operating performance,'' said Charles E. Sporck,
president and chief executive officer.
   The company's stock closed down 25 cents a share at $9.12{ on
the New York Stock Exchange before the earnings report was released.
   For the three months ended Aug. 28, National Semiconductor lost
$30.5 million, or 31 cents per share, on sales of $649.4 million,
compared with earnings of $13.5 million, or 10 cents per share, on
sales of $517.6 million for the same period a year earlier.
   Sporck said sales of mainframe computers were hurt by both
slowing of demand and continued pricing pressure. The computers are
made by Japan's Hitachi Ltd. to the specifications of National's
National Advanced Systems unit.
   ``The outlook for the semiconductor group is strong,'' Sporck
said. ``We anticipate continued growth in components sales for the
second quarter.''
   He said the restructuring within the Information Systems Group
will enable it to improve its operating performance.
</TEXT>
