<HEAD>Ford, Hyundai Boost 1989 Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for Ford Motor Co.'s 1989 cars and trucks will increase
an average of 2.6 percent and Hyundai Motor America's subcompact
Excel will go up 2.8 percent over comparably equipped 1988 models,
the companies said Monday.
   The No. 2 U.S. automaker and the South Korean car producer said
in separate statements that higher material and labor costs
contributed to the price changes.
   Some of Ford's sticker price increases for the '89 model year
are caused by additional standard equipment on some models, company
spokesman Dave Krupp said.
   For example, the Mustang LX convertible which sold for $13,702
during the 1988 model year will sell for $14,140 in the 1989 model
year. Krupp said some equipment listed as optional on the 1988
models will be standard on 1989 models.
   The company said the largest percentage jump, more than 5
percent, was in the price of its 1989 Crown Victoria standard
station wagon. Its 1988 price of $15,311 will jump to $16,208 in
1989, a combination of higher pricing and optional equipment
becoming standard, Krupp said.
   Meantime, Hyundai said the 1989 suggested retail prices for the
Excel will range from $5,499 for the three-door hatchback to $6,949
for the five-door GL hatchback, up $104 and $204 respectively.
</TEXT>
