<2ND_LINE>AM-Manville,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manville Reaches Accord With Insurance Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. has reached an agreement with
American Centennial Insurance Co. in another settlement over
insurance disputes stemming from damage claims filed by former
asbestos workers, Manville officials announced Monday.
   Terms of the agreement provide for three payments by American
Centennial, of Wilmington, Del., totaling $3.4 million, and will
cover all of Manville's claims against the insurer for policies
covering the periods from July 1, 1980 to July 1, 1981, and from
July 1982 to July 1983, Manville said in a news release.
   The settlement is conditional upon final court orders approving
the settlement and the Bankruptcy Court's order confirming
Manville's plan of reorganization, the release said.
   A fairness hearing on the settlement and on other recently
announced asbestos-related insurance settlements will be held on
Sept. 28 in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York City.
   The settlement ultimately will go into the Asbestos Property
Damage Trust established under Manville's reorganization plan.
   Manville has now reached settlements providing for payments
totaling nearly $845 million with numerous other insurers.
   The Manville plan requires insurance funding of $615 million in
present value to fund a trust for compensating asbestos disease
sufferers, the release said, with insurance proceeds in excess of
the $615 million passing through to the Asbestos Property Damage
Trust.
   Manville filed for bankruptcy protection on Aug. 26, 1982, when
more than 400 asbestos-related lawsuits were being filed agaisnt
the company each month.
   A proposed reorganization plan was confirmed by the bankruptcy
court in December 1986, but it cannot be consummated until all
appeals are exhausted.
</TEXT>
