<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CBOT-Globex     09-12 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBOT-Globex,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Of Trade Opposes Merc's Electronic Trading System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade has urged regulators
not to approve a rival commodities exchange's electronic network
for 24-hour global trading of financial futures and options, on the
grounds the system could lead to abuse and would be hard to operate.
   The CBOT sent a 51-page letter dated Sept. 6 to the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission urging the commission to turn down the
electronic venture, planned by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and
Reuters Holdings PLC.
   The 12{-year deal, which requires government approval, calls for
the Globex network to begin operating next summer.
   It would link investors in North America, Europe and Asia via an
electronic system for trading futures and options contracts on
currency futures, including the British pound, the West German
mark, the Swiss franc, the Japanese yen and Eurodollar time
deposits.
   The system would operate during hours when the Chicago
Mercantile's trading floor is closed.
   CBOT President Thomas R. Donovan raised a number of issues in
the letter to the commission, ranging from the way contracts are
normally traded in the pit to the possibility of fraud.
   ``The Globex proposal marks a complete departure from the
centralized, open outcry markets which ensure the sort of honest
and efficient price discovery which Congress has mandated,''
Donovan wrote in the letter. ``In effect, Globex is an off-exchange
market.
   ``The Globex proposal is inherently susceptible to manipulation,
prearranged trading and other abuses,'' his letter said.
   ``Moreover, the CME's application is incomplete because it fails
to address a variety of compliance, enforcement and liability
issues including the applicability of foreign laws to the operation
of Globex terminals located abroad.
   ``Finally, a host of unresolved financial and operational
concerns, particularly in the wake of the October stock market
decline, render final action on this unprecedented proposal
altogether inappropriate,'' Donovan wrote.
   Reuters, the news and market information concern, will provide
the technical expertise for Globex. The Mercantile Exchange, a
pioneer in the creation of financial futures and options, will
provide the main market for the system.
   Futures and options allow investors to bet on the future
performance of commoditiesm, currencies and financial instruments
such as stocks and bonds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
