<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GeneralMills     09-12 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Mills,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Mills Reports Record First-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. said Monday it nearly
quadrupled its first quarter net earnings compared with the same
period last year, due largely to profits on the sale of its Talbots
and Eddie Bauer clothing outlets.
   General Mills reported net income of $289.9 million, or $3.53
per share, in the three months ended Aug. 28, compared with net
income of $77.2 million, or 87 cents per share, in the first
quarter of 1987.
   The 1988 figures included a $199.1 million gain from
discontinued operations. The sales of Talbots and Eddie Bauer,
completed during the first quarter, generated an after-tax profit
of $220.6 million, the company said.
   The gain was reduced by establishment of a $21.5 million reserve
for the disposition of the company's York's cafeterias and other
adjustments to previously discontinued operations. General Mills
said it plans to dispose of York's 100-unit chain during fiscal
1989.
   First-quarter sales rose 11 percent, to $1.38 billion from $1.24
billion, the company said. It attributed the sales increase largely
to a more than 5 percent volume gain in consumer foods and
expansion of restaurants by 69 company-operated units since the end
of the first quarter of 1987.
   After-tax earnings from continuing operations rose to $90.8
million in the first quarter from first-quarter 1987 after-tax
earnings of $80.9 million.
   Chairman H.B. Atwater said much of the proceeds from the Talbots
and Eddie Bauer sales was used to repurchase common stock, reducing
average shares outstanding by 7 percent from a year earlier.
   First-quarter operating highlights reflect General Mills'
aggressive internal expansion programs in consumer foods and
restaurants.
   Consumer foods reported gains of 9 percent in sales and 12.5
percent in operating profits in the first quarter of 1988.
Restaurants reported gains of 15 percent in sales and 10 percent in
operating profits over the first quarter of last year.
</TEXT>
