<HEAD>Dollar Opens Lower, Share Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar weakened in early trading Tuesday
against the Japanese yen, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose moderately.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at
133.23 yen, down from Monday's close of 133.42 yen.
   The U.S. currency was weakening on increasing dollar-selling by
investors, said Takamasa Yamazaki of the Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
   ``A dollar-selling drive in the market has remained strong since
last Tuesday, while investors haven't really been buying dollars,''
he said.
   The expected announcement Wednesday in Washington of U.S. trade
figures for July was also prompting dollar-selling in Tokyo,
Yamazaki said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 136.52
points to 27,893.26 in the first 15 minutes of trading. The
widely-followed market index rose 109.64 points Monday, closing at
27,756.74.
   A spokesman for the brokerage Nomura Securities characterized
the mood on the Tokyo Stock Exchange as a ``good investment
environment.''
   ``The yen has been getting stronger, and apprehension about
higher interest rates is fading. It's the best time to increase the
market's energy,'' said Manjiro Ueda.
