<1ST_LINE>d f BC-McCormickSale     09-12 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-McCormick Sale,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rouse Company Purchases McCormick Properties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCormick & Co. Inc. has sold its real estate
holdings, amounting to about nine million square feet of office
space, to the Rouse Company for $550 million, McCormick officials
announced Monday.
   McCormick, which held the real estate through its McCormick
Properties, has holdings in the Baltimore-Washington corridor,
Pennsylvania, North Carolina and Florida.
   Appraisers valued McCormick's real estate portfolio at $471
million last November, shortly before the company announced it
planned to divest the holdings to concentrate on its food business.
   McCormick is the world's largest spice manufacturer, with 1987
sales of $1.1 billion.
   Rouse officials have indicated nearly all McCormick Properties
employees will be retained, said Larry Lichtenauer, McCormick's
manager of marketing communications.
   Rouse officials could not be reached for comment late Monday.
   Rouse holds about 2.4 million square feet of retail, office and
industrial space, including Baltimore's Harbor Place. The company
purchased thousands of acres of farmland in the
Baltimore-Washington corridor in the 1960s and designed the planned
community of Columbia.
   A May report by Standard & Poors listed Rouse's assets at $1.7
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
