<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TimberStrike     09-12 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Strike,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Workers Ratify Contract At Two Northwest Timber Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 1,400 striking workers have ratified
a four-year contract with DAW Forest Products Co. and W-I Forest
Products Inc., union officials announced Monday, in the latest of a
series of agreements aimed at ending the multi-state timber strike.
   Bill Hubbell, president of the International Woodworkers of
America-U.S., said a tentative contract approved last week was
ratified Sunday by union members in Oregon, Montana and Idaho.
   About 400 members of the Western Council of Industrial Workers
also approved the agreement, according to union spokesman Brad Witt.
   IWA business agent Bert Larson in central Oregon said the two
unions voted 3-1 in favor of the contract.
   The agreement matched one ratified Aug. 4 by workers at
Willamette Industries, Hubbell said. That agreement provided for
$1,400 bonuses during the first year of the contract, plus raises
totaling 11 percent in the last three years.
   The strike, which began June 5, at its peak idled 9,000 workers
at dozens of logging operations and lumber mills in Oregon,
Washington, Idaho, Montana, and Northern California.
   Only about 400 workers remain on strike, at Morgan Products
Ltd., of Springfield, Ore., and Lakeview Lumber Co., of Lakeview,
Ore.
   Hubbell said votes on a new contract with Weyerhaeuser Co. were
scheduled to be tallied Tuesday. The company's 6,000 union workers
were not affected by the walkout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
